<HEADLINE>Cracker solution for solo women</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684161</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FACED with the prospect of eating alone in the formal surroundings of a hotel
dining room, the solo travelling business woman would not object if she was
joined by actor Robbie Coltrane.
That at least was the conclusion of one of Glasgow's city centre hotels, the
Copthorne, which questioned hundreds of female guests on how to improve its
services for the solitary traveller.
Among more serious questions on safety, the hotel threw in the question of the
ideal dinner partner. Coltrane, whose credibility as an object of desire was
greatly enhanced by his starring role in the ITV detective series Cracker, came
out as the favourite. Least favourite companion for dinner a deux was,
strangely, Margaret Thatcher.
The hotel's survey this Christmas comes after a number of similar studies by
women's business groups which have been concerned about the facilities offered
by hotels to the ever-growing number of female business travellers.
Yesterday the Copthorne's general manager, Ms Amanda Scott, said the majority
of solo female guests felt uncomfortable dining or drinking alone. They also
resented having to contend with the unwanted advances of male guests.
In response to the dining room nightmare she said hotels needed to provide
excellent room service. On the issue of safety she said women preferred to
sleep in rooms where doors were fitted with safety chains and spyholes.
The survey of 300 guests also revealed that women would like to have an iron
and ironing board in their rooms.
</TEXT>
