<HEADLINE>Sales hot up after a cold start.Bargain hunters brave the weather for warm clothes and next year's Christmas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STARRS, ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684162</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE cold weather looked at first to have slowed down the traditional rush to
snap up bargains in the Boxing Day sales yesterday, with business starting
quietly across Scotland, but the temptations for shoppers finally proved too
strong.
Trade picked up in most areas later in the day, although shops in Aberdeen were
forced to close early to allow staff and customers plenty of time to get home
in the poor weather conditions.
Mr Nick Harvey, manager of Debenhams in the city's Trinity Shopping Centre,
said: ``Trading has been reasonably good considering the weather, but we
decided to close half an hour early.
``We had a lot of people from the city centre, but a lack of folk from out of
town. We have all been surprised by the number of people who have braved the
weather.''
Mr George Ritchie, manager of Glasgow's St Enoch Centre, said: ``We opened at
10am, and with the roads and the weather it was a slow start. But by lunchtime
they were coming out in their droves.
``Fashions are quite big at this time of year when people are given money as
their Christmas gift to spend in the sales. Sports and shoe shops were also
very busy.
``Boxing Day is a leisure day and people come out to enjoy themselves. We are
in the entertainment business today.''
Ms Tracy Walker, sales and operations manager at Debenhams in Argyle Street,
Glasgow, said: ``We opened at 9am and we had about 100 people waiting to come
in. We were selling a lot of outer-wear and our cook shop was doing well.''
Warm coats and jackets were also big sellers, along with TVs and audio
equipment, at the House of Fraser store in Buchanan Street, Glasgow. The
manager, Mrs Jan Stanners, said: ``We had queues before we opened, but the snow
didn't help.''
About 100 people had queued outside Debenhams in Princes Street, Edinburgh, by
the time doors opened at 9am. Store manager Paul Lines said the shop had been
busy all day with a diverse range of goods selling well, including winter
coats, evening and party wear, bed linen, and saucepan sets.
At the BHS store, shoppers were snapping up festive decorations, cards and
wrapping paper, in preparation for next Christmas. Store manager Allan Miller
said the surprising big seller was an elephant that hangs on the Christmas tree
and blows bubbles out of its trunk.
``People seem to be getting more and more organised but it's surprising to have
such a rush on reduced Christmas goods on Boxing Day,'' said Mr Miller. He
added that clothing, and especially lingerie, was selling well.
At the Fraser's store at the west end of Princes Street, 40 people were waiting
for the sale to start. Store manager Nancy McKenzie said: ``We expected the
cold weather would put people off. However, we have been busy.
``Men's wear has been flying out of the door and there has been a run on things
for the home, like glass ware. All in all it's been going brilliantly.''
At Olympus Sport, manageress Julie Myles said the shop had been busy all day.
Top brand name training shoes which had their #100 prices cut by #40 were the
biggest sellers.
Shops in the capital are expected to be even more busy today when the three
biggest shopping malls - St James Centre, Cameron Toll, and the Gyle - open
their doors.
The Wellgate Shopping Centre in Dundee was visited by around 28,000 people
yesterday. Manager John Morton said: ``It was quiet in the morning, but in the
afternoon it was like a Saturday. I think people must have kept money back for
the sales.'' He said fashion stores had appeared to attract most customers.
Meanwhile, many people could be waking up to a financial hangover when the
post-Christmas sales are over, according to research carried out by MORI.
One in five people are expected to be left in debt, and many could find
themselves paying off the festivities throughout next year and beyond. The
research, conducted on behalf of Beneficial Bank, also showed that credit would
be used most by young shoppers, those aged between 25 and 34, to pay for
Christmas and New Year celebrations. Almost 70% of this age group was also
planning to attend the January sales, with 11% saying this would put them more
in debt.
</TEXT>
