<HEADLINE>Record temperature lows set to continue across north as blizzards sweep in causing disruption Even colder Arctic blast forecast</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684163</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE icy conditions that have gripped Scotland since Sunday are likely to
continue, causing further disruption in the Highlands and sending Glasgow
towards an all-time temperature low.
A spokesman from the Glasgow weather centre said temperatures remained below
zero throughout the country yesterday. And he forecast the current ``Arctic
blast'' would mean even lower temperatures ahead.
He added that snow would continue to fall in the Northern and Western Isles
over the next few days, moving into Caithness and even parts of the Borders on
the east coast.
But a drop in wind speeds from 115mph on Sunday to 25mph yesterday should see
an end to the severe blizzards that have crippled those parts of the country,
he said.
Temperatures in Glasgow reached -16C yesterday morning - making the city the
coldest place in Scotland along with the area around Aviemore - and were tipped
to verge on the lowest ever reading, -17.8C, overnight.
Temperatures in Edinburgh reached a recorded low of -6C.
The weather should remain cold in the central belt until New Year with some
snow showers. Conditions could deteriorate further towards the end of the week.
Snow is lying at a depth of at least seven inches in parts of Aberdeen. The
North-east can expect continuing showers and sub-zero temperatures over the
next few days.
The forecast prompted police and motoring organisations to issue warnings that
drivers should take extra care.
AA Roadwatch said last night that icy conditions were affecting roads in
Tayside and Strathclyde and Grampian, while many islanders were completely cut
off by huge drifts in Shetland and the Western Isles.
On Benbecula, Hughena Macmillan of Creagorry, gave birth to a baby girl, Jessie
Anne, on Christmas morning in Stornoway hospital, but father Alastair MacDonald
has been unable to see the baby because he has been stranded at home by the
severe weather.
An AA spokesman advised: ``Drivers should think about only travelling if it is
absolutely necessary, and if they do they should take extra care.''
A spokesman for Strathclyde Police warned that the freezing overnight
temperatures could cause problems as people returned to work.
There have been around 70 accidents, mostly minor, in the region from Christmas
Day to Boxing Day, he added.
Strathclyde's roads department has defended its performance in the wintry
conditions over the Christmas period.
Thousands of motorists had to struggle through snow and over icy patches across
the region from Christmas Eve.
However, a council spokesman said yesterday that everything possible had been
done to keep roads open and passable.
He blamed much of the difficulty on the heavy snow which fell after roads had
been salted and gritted.
The spokesman said that 700 regional council staff, on 350 vehicles, had worked
every day over the Christmas period, spreading 3000 tonnes of salt and grit.
Their priority, he said had been to keep primary routes open.
A spokesman for Strathclyde Police confirmed that all main roads had been kept
free of major blockages, although some minor roads remained dangerous. There
were no serious accidents in the area.
Passengers on the Glasgow Underground were held up for 25 minutes yesterday
evening after ice on the track halted services.
The harsh weather has also caused disruption in England, particularly in parts
of Lincolnshire and Humberside. The South and East Anglia could soon suffer.
Race meetings due to be held at Edinburgh and Leicester today have been called
off. Prospects for Kempton, Wetherby and Chepstow, due to stage the Coral Welsh
National, are gloomy.
</TEXT>
