<HEADLINE>Region mourns finance chief</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN McCALMAN Municipal Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684164</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR Archibald Gillespie - one of the best-known figures in Scottish local
government and Strathclyde region's director of finance - collapsed and died at
his home on Christmas Day.
It is understood that he had gone for a stroll after his Christmas lunch. On
his return in the late afternoon he complained of breathlessness then collapsed
and died in the hallway.
Mr Gillespie, who was 60, had only three months to go before his retirement
when Strathclyde winds up. He was one of Scotland's most dynamic and highly
respected finance officials, even winning respect from the Scottish Office with
which he was often in contention.
Strathclyde region's chairman of finance, Councillor John Mullin, said
yesterday: ``We have lost one of the giants of local government. He was someone
we all looked up to as a great professional adviser on financial matters. We
are shocked and stunned by his death.''
A man of humour and great generosity of spirit, Mr Gillespie was prominent
during the controversial years of poll-tax collection, pursuing non-payers with
rigour.
So rigorous was he that one Militant councillor nicknamed him ``Ghengis''
Gillespie at a council meeting. He responded with a quiet smile.
Paradoxically - and he was never heard to say it publicly - Mr Gillespie is
understood to have disapproved of the poll tax as a revenue-raising mechanism.
Nevertheless he pursued its collection in the interests of maintaining council
services.
He once told a meeting of the finance committee, whose members were wilting in
the glare of poll tax controversy, that payment of taxes was an individual's
highest duty to society. He was contemptuous of the ``can pay, won't pay''
brigade whom he dismissed as ``chancers''.
His talents were publicly acknowledged when he was named as Finance Director of
the Year for 1995 - an honour that normally goes to the private sector.
Mr Gillespie was director of finance for the past nine years, having served as
depute director since the inception of Strathclyde region in 1975.
Before that he was County Treasurer for the former Bute Council from 1967-75.
From 1964-67 he had been chief internal auditor for the former Greenock
Corporation.
He was a Greenock man through and through and gave Morton Football Club his
steadfast support.
He is survived by his wife, Alice, two sons and two daughters.
</TEXT>
