<HEADLINE>Developer plans to save   industrial architecture gem</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684165</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of Scotland's finest pieces of industrial architecture could be saved, it
was revealed yesterday.
Plans exist for the imposing Argyll Works near Loch Lomond to become the
country's first ``seconds'' retail unit, and an automobile heritage centre.
The giant red sandstone factory was built in Main Street, Alexandria, 90 years
ago for the manufacture of the Argyll motor car.
Later it became a government munitions factory. The Royal Naval Torpedo
Factory, as it was then named, produced torpedoes and other arms until Polaris
missiles were introduced.
It was the setting in the 1970s for a workers' sit-in when the Ministry of
Defence shut down torpedo production.
The factory finally closed its gold-leaf painted gates for the last time 20
years ago.
Since then, and despite carrying a Category A Listing as ``a significant
industrial archeological remain'', it this magnificent landmark with imposing
copper-domed clocktower has been allowed to crumble.
Councillors and heritage groups have watched with dismay as years of neglect
have taken their toll and the factory has been scavenged by scrap metal thieves.
Marble staircases and valuable fireplaces have been plundered along with
magnificent wooden panelling from the boardrooms, management suites, and
drawing offices.
Until yesterday it seemed inevitable that the Argyll Works, now a giant,
neglected sandstone skeleton, would have to be demolished.
However, hope has now emerged that it may be saved, following the announcement
of a planning application due to be discussed next week by Dumbarton District
Council.
A Glasgow company, Acreground Ltd, has applied to create a factory retail
outlet of 20 shops selling ``seconds'' - slightly flawed goods rejected by High
Street stores such as Marks and Spencer and BHS.
The plans include also a motor heritage centre in the magnificent central
hallway.
Dumbarton planning director Philip Gaunt says the Argyll Works should be saved
and maintains this could be its last chance of survival.
Mr Gaunt said: ``This proposal would seem to represent an ideal and unique
opportunity to re-use the building and to restore it to its former glory. It is
probably the last chance for this to happen, the proposal should be fully
supported.''
A spokesman for Historic Scotland said: ``This is a satisfactory and fitting
proposal which has the potential to solve one of the West of Scotland's most
intractable industrial building re-use problems.''
</TEXT>
