<HEADLINE>Autopsy on cult death victims</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From HERVE PIOCHET Grenoble, Tuesday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684166</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORENSIC experts today began studying the charred remains of 16 members of the
Order of the Solar Temple found last week in a remote French Alpine forest
clearing.
The post-mortem examination, at a hospital near Grenoble, could take several
days and will establish whether the bodies are those of eight French and eight
Swiss nationals missing for 10 days ago, whose passports were found in cars
abandoned near the scene.
French prosecutor Jean-Francois Lorans has called the deaths a mix of murder
and suicide, mirroring the macabre October 1994 Solar Temple ritual in which 53
people died in similar circumstances in Switzerland and Canada.
``This was an organised collective murder, perhaps followed by one, two or
three suicides,'' Lorans has said.
Investigators found medicines, toxic products and flammable liquids at the
site. But they found no flammables container.
They said that of four weapons found at the site, two pistols belonged to two
French policemen believed to be among the dead.
All the bodies, including those of three children aged two, four and six, had
bullet wounds. As in the 1994 deaths, some had plastic bags over their heads.
Autopsies could provide clues to some of the unanswered questions, such as when
the victims died, who died last, and whether all those who took part in the
macabre ritual died.-Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
