<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Voting blindly</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684167</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AT times I think that our Parliamentary system is plain stupid. On December 19
the Government lost the fisheries debate by two votes - 299-297. According to
my arithmetic this means that 596 MPs voted.
I saw a minute or two of the actual debate while it was taking place. I doubt
if there more than 50 Members present in the Chamber. This means that over 500
of our honest, dedicated MPs voted without knowing what had been said during
the debate.
Obviously the MPs had made up their minds how they were going to vote, but is
it not possible that some of them might have been influenced to change their
views had they actually been present to listen to what was said?
If MPs know how they are going to vote before the debate takes place surely
this is a complete waste of Parliamentary time?
David M Graham-Service,
17 Cleveden Gardens,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
