<DOCNO>GH951227-000007</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000007</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>School boards Parents becoming more apathetic</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684168</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RESEARCH has confirmed the crucial role that parents and the home have in
children's education. Both are generally recognised as key influences, and many
initiatives at national, local, and school level strive to involve parents more
imaginatively in their children's learning. At national level, for example, the
curricular programme for five to 14-year-olds recognises, and seeks to build
upon, parental input. According to research published today by the European
Parents Association, parental involvement in official education policy is a
reality in all EU member states. This amounts with varying degrees of
commitment to parents taking part in consultative groupings and decision-making
bodies at school level. In practice, it means parents taking decisions on such
school matters as holidays, staff recruitment, or disciplinary procedures. It
does not mean playing a direct role in teaching or, generally, in children's
education. In Scotland, school boards - the Government's formal structure for
parental involvement - have decision-making powers in limited areas but cannot
intervene in the curriculum. Based on the latest election returns, however,
parents are becoming more apathetic about school boards. It seems that more are
asking if their involvement in, and commitment to, boards is worth the candle.
And their workload will increase when all schools have devolved management,
with heads taking responsibility for most school-based spending and consulting
their boards about their plans. According to the EPA, parents across Europe are
questioning the value of becoming involved on the basis of their governments'
models. With decentralisation comes more work, more expertise - which further
disenfranchises all but the middle classes according to the EPA - and a role
for parents which fails to take account of what they are actually doing.
The association is quite rightly suspicious of the motives of governments which
seek to involve parents when public funds are at a low ebb, public services are
being eroded, and the dictates of the market-place are gaining credence. In
England, it points out, schools are being made to compete on the basis of their
results and other ``outputs'' which point to their effectiveness. Yet the
dictates of the market-place do not - cannot - sit alongside traditional,
democratic educational values which espouse open and equitable access. Any
government which seeks to hitch parents to the anti-public service,
pro-market-place bandwagon must be resisted because it is indulging in
``passing fads and dangers'', says the EPA. The long-term aims of consumers -
generations of pupils and parents - must be paramount, it concludes. The
British Government's strategy is, of course, to encourage schools to opt out of
local authority control and run themselves, funded directly by the Government
and managed by parent-dominated boards. But even in England the strategy is, at
the very least, faltering. In Scotland it has never got off the ground. Parents
may be growing in apathy towards school boards, partly because of the limited
powers they have and the commitment required to carry them out. But that does
not mean they want to run their schools. If that were the case there would be
more than two in Scotland with self-governing status. School boards have been
useful in opening up the secrets of schooling and making local authorities more
accountable in terms of explaining their actions. But if we are serious about
parental involvement we have to involve those very parents who, the EPA shows,
are still on the outside. Here, several school-based initiatives - typically in
disadvantaged areas - are under way to involve those parents and guardians who
got nothing from their experience of schooling and whose children and charges
might well reach similar conclusions. That is where we must look if we want to
be truly equitable - and successful.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000008</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000008</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Boost for housing Logjam set to be broken</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684169</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NUMBER of developments have lately breathed a little more confidence into the
private housing market which has been severely depressed since the boom of the
late eighties proved to be unsustainable. The Halifax building society,
Britain's largest, has considered these and come to the conclusion that the
worst has indeed passed and that a significant recovery is at last under way.
Significant need not mean big numbers - the society believes that house prices
will rise by 2% next year and by over 5% each in 1997 and 1998, with the
possibility of what it calls a ``mini-boom'' in the latter year. So much for
the earlier fears that house prices would stand still, if not fall, for a
generation. In fact they have fallen enough from their peak levels to make them
attractive buys at the moment given the level of interest rates and the near
certainty of these falling further next year. When tax cuts, no matter how
modest, are added to the mix, it ought be enough to appeal to new buyers and
break the logjam which has left the housing market stagnant for five years.
Confidence remains the key, and the Christmas retail experience may provide the
evidence that it has re-emerged.
That is the case for optimism and, as is the way with all economic turning
points, is has little certainty. There remains a big backlog of unsold
properties (in repossession, for example) and a pent-up wedge of houses whose
owners are anxious to sell but remain deterred by the state of the market.
These facts would, of course, keep prices from soaring ahead, but that is all
to the good: a healthy housing market needs some price stability, and the
notion that house purchase is a one-way escalator to easy money has been shown
to be immensely damaging especially to those purchasers from whom the effort to
buy is too great a sacrifice even in good times. Not everyone can afford to buy
their own house and a prudent social policy will provide them also with the
opportunity to rent from varying sources, including local authorities, whose
housing programmes have been run down too much. The authorities have the
financial resources from the proceeds of their sales of earlier council stock,
and part of these should be released to pay for new developments and also to
ensure that their quality should be high. (No doubt occupants would have
purchase rights but these might be amended to allow the properties involved to
remain in council possession for some minimum period of years: there seems no
point in public money financing cheap new housing for randomly chosen
beneficiaries.)
On the mortgage front some new developments suggest themselves. Lenders should
be prevented from offering loans equal to the total value of the property
bought: the cushion afforded by a deposit must have saved many when values
fell. Legislation may be required here. The link between mortgages and
endowment insurance policies needs careful consideration: lenders should leave
borrowers free to choose rather than insisting on the two being tied together
(for no good reason other than the commission taken by the lender). Home
ownership will still represent an investment, but that will not be the primary
motive for its acquisition and its appreciation will be long term, though a
mobile society may still have people moving faster than might otherwise be
ideal. In that case the cost of buying and selling houses will become more
obvious and the attractions of rental further reinforced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`We are still a depressingly long way from seeing Scottish film becoming a success story like whisky' It's time to put Scotland in the picture</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Allan Shiach</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684170</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE past year was a good one for film-makers in Scotland. Braveheart, Shallow
Grave, Rob Roy, and other films, like Small Faces and The Near Room, were
birthed, nurtured, or otherwise brought to being in the balmy seasons of 1995.
Happy events all. But as we enter the centenary year for film, a few toddlers
taking their first faltering steps do not yet amount to an army of film-makers
stepping forth from Scotland to do battle with Hollywood.
Nor can we hope for a grown-up film community unless and until further action
is taken. Film-making in Scotland is inextricably linked to the UK and European
context. And at present, British film-makers have to try to operate in a world
in which we are disadvantaged on two flanks.
On one side stand our European competitors who are intricately and often
heavily subsidised for a variety of cultural, linguistic, and economic reasons.
On the other side, the Americans whose second-largest export industry is film
and filmed entertainment.
This latter is worth emphasising because film-making is often viewed in this
country as a marginal activity, a group of artsy folk seeking to exploit their
own egos. The Americans have demonstrated that it is in fact a business worth
over $15 billion annually, an export business expected within two years to
overhaul the aircraft industry as the United States' largest single foreign
currency earner. Hollywood bestrides the world; every country and culture
clamours for their film and television product.
This huge success is derived from a fully integrated structure for film,
beginning with script development through production to intensive marketing.
Contrast this with a British example like Carla's Song, which the eminent
director Ken Loach is at present shooting in Glasgow and Central America.
Carla's Song was finally put together with a complex web of finance including
money from Channel 4, the Scottish Film Production Fund, an Italian investor,
and a German company. Loach's worldwide status as a film-maker was hardly
reflected in the release of his last film, Land and Freedom, which was poorly
distributed with a miserly total of 25 prints of the film being made.
Highlighting the difference is Rob Roy, also developed with help from SFPF,
which was then swept up in the slipstream of a US studio, given full funding
and even fuller marketing and had at least 1200 prints made.
The American film industry is enormous, well-financed, and vertically
integrated; even films which ``lose'' money in box-office receipts recoup in
time through TV sales, video, and the growing cable universe.
So how can we hope, against this fearsome competition, to raise the little
bairn of Scottish film? There is no doubt that, beyond the welcome support
recently promised by the Scottish Office, several meaningful measures must be
taken at UK level before Scotland's film industry can stand up and begin to
walk. The evidence that this might be forthcoming is depressingly slight.
The Department of National Heritage has no apparently coherent policy on film.
It has recently and unilaterally withdrawn Britain from participation in
Eurimages, a scheme under which we were poised to benefit greatly. The DNH has
once more reduced the annual grant to the British Film Institute. And most
damaging of all, the Chancellor, in his Budget statement last month, has yet
again ignored the film sector's request for equal taxation treatment with the
rest of manufacturing industry in the UK.
This latter is by far the most serious problem we face and one which, if it
remains unattended, will not only prevent our film industry from reviving but
will eventually cause the Government real embarrassment.
deriving from an anomaly in the 1990 Capital Allowances Act, the present
situation positively discriminates against investment in film by failing to
offer investors the same fiscal environment as is afforded to investment in
other manufactured products. And while Lottery funding - a single plank in a
ramshackle edifice - has been a welcome development, it only exists as
partnership funding, making the circumstances under which private finance can
be raised a vital issue.
The situation likely to arise is one in which Lottery money is offered to
productions which will then be unable to raise the balance of their financing
because of the present hostile tax regime. Eventually these products will end
up on the shelf, unmade except in the producer's dreams. And the Lottery funds,
apparently committed to them, will disappear back into the Lottery. Opportunity
lost, initiative crushed, Government embarrassed. And Scotland no closer to
seeing an ongoing revival in its film-making fortunes.
The most frustrating part of this scenario is that the intellectual and
technical arguments leading to a possible amendment of the Finance Act were,
according to reports, accepted by a recent Chancellor and appear still to be
supported by several senior Cabinet Ministers. Implementation of changes to the
Capital Allowances Act, Section 68, removing the unwarrantable discrimination
against film, would at a single stroke open up real possibilities for
film-makers in Britain.
And Scotland, with a more advanced infrastructure for film than any other part
of the country outside London, would be significant winners in the upsurge in
production which would not only work directly to the benefit of Scotland's
economy, but it would, as several studies have shown, lead eventually to a net
inflow to the Exchequer.
The purpose of partnership funding is to ensure that producers submit projects
to the disciplines of the international market-place. We do not look for, nor
would we benefit from, subsidy.
Fairer taxation treatment actually increases net revenue to the Exchequer
consequent upon increased activity and the revival of inward investment. There
are several studies, notably in Canada and in Eire, to demonstrate this. Even
the Treasury's own economic model demonstrates that the fiscal changes being
sought would at worst be tax-neutral.
The DNH has recently set up yet another committee to advise it on film
financing. But the Government does not need a committee to inform it of the
kind of fiscal reform now urgently needed. It merely needs a sense of fair play.
We in Scotland have the technical and artistic skills - as well as the language
- to support international film-makers and develop our own industry to exploit
the worldwide opportunities which now exist.
Helping to stimulate film activity in Scotland, the Scottish Film Council and
the Film Production Fund have, over the past few years, developed initiatives,
ranging from training seminars to direct investment. These bodies are supported
by funds from the Scottish Office and supplemented (in the case of SFPF
supplemented several times over) by a variety of other sources.
But while Government support is both necessary and welcome, it can be seen in
perspective by a simple fact: the Scottish Film Production Fund grant is given
at a rate of about #0.04 per capita whereas an equivalent body in Eire receives
almost #1.00 per capita. The effect of this discrepancy can be gauged from the
fact that the Irish have some 90 film projects in development whereas Scotland
has but 30. Without a reservoir of sufficient size - as Yorkshire Water
discovered - needs cannot be met.
Some years ago SFC helped to establish the first British screen commission with
Scottish Screen Locations. On a marginal budget of some #120,000 per annum, and
without the help of government funding, this organisation has brought over #23m
worth of production to Scotland in the year past. Can any other organisation in
Britain claim a ratio of cost : benefit on this scale?
With initiatives such as Movie Makars, First Reels, Tartan Shots, and a new
five-minute film series being developed in co-operation with Scottish TV, we
are able to see young film-makers move forward. Many of these are people who
may, if successful beyond our shores, bring film production back to Scotland in
years ahead. But if we fail them now, our skill will wither and our potential
will be quickly lost.
It has been said that ``the film industry is alive and well in Britain and is
called television''. While there is a fragment of truth in the statement, it is
unfortunately not reflected in the Scottish film-making scene. British
television's overall drama budget in the UK amounts to some #500m a year. If a
mere 10% of this were to be spent in Scotland it would wholly transform
matters. In terms of building a skill base for our film-makers there is no
doubt that film-for-television could be an important arena. Perhaps some form
of ring-fencing, to ensure a proportionate contribution by Scotland, could be
devised.
But in the longer term, and apart from what we believe are zero-cost fiscal
measures applied at the national level, the enhancement of film activity in
Scotland is best accomplished by some simple measures:
n Formal recognition by government agencies that film production is an
important contributor to the cultural and to the commercial life and welfare of
our country.
n A significant increase in the Scottish Office grant to assist in the process
of development, the seedcorn of all growth.
n Encouragement of the pro-active role of SFC.
n Sustaining and growing Lottery funding levels.
n High-level government commitment to and understanding of the industry's
needs, carrying forward the industry's case for fiscal reform as well as
assisting in responding to the requirements of film-makers who are considering
Scotland as a location or production base for their projects.
We have made some worthwhile beginnings. We have proven that we have the
talents and skills to compete in world markets. Yet although Scotland has in
the past managed one of the world's most successful exports, we are still a
depressingly long way from seeing Scottish film becoming - as I believe it
capable - a success story like whisky.
n Allan Shiach is chairman of the Scottish Film Council, the Scottish Film
Production Fund and a governor of the British Film Institute. He is also
chairman of the Macallan malt whisky company.
Against all the odds, Scotland's fledgling film industry is alive and kicking
but, as Allan Shiach reports, vital change is needed if it is to flourish
</TEXT>
</DOC>
