<DOCNO>GH951227-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP in Carl case  seizes on new Act</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684171</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE new body to investigate miscarriages of justice should immediately study
the ``unsafe'' convictions of four men for the 1978 killing of newsboy Carl
Bridgewater, a Labour MP urged yesterday.
The case represented ``the last stain'' on the previous system of dealing with
alleged wrongful convictions, said Mr Robin Corbett, a former front bench
spokesman on home affairs.
The measures to strengthen the Court of Appeal's powers to weed out and correct
miscarriages of justice come into force on Monday.
Mr David Maclean, Home Office Minister, said yesterday that the measures,
contained in the Criminal Appeal Act, would make a ``substantial contribution''
to the quality of justice.
Carl Bridgewater, 13, was shot when he interrupted a burglary at Yew Tree Farm,
near Wordsley in Staffordshire, in 1978.
James Robinson, now 61, of Weoley Castle, Birmingham, and Vincent Hickey, 41,
of Redditch, were convicted of murder and sentenced to life imprisonment, with
a recommendation that they serve at least 25 years.
Michael Hickey, Vincent's cousin, who was 17 at the time of the murder, was
ordered to be detained at Her Majesty's pleasure.
A fourth man, Pat Molloy, who was convicted of manslaughter, died in 1981 aged
53.
Regular protestations of the innocence of the four men have so far failed to
convince a succession of Home Secretaries or the courts.
Mr Maclean said yesterday that the Act, which implements some of the key
recommendations of the Royal Commission on Criminal Justice, would increase the
powers of magistrates courts to reopen cases to correct mistakes.
The new independent Review Commission would investigate possible miscarriages
of justice, and refer them to the courts.
The commission is expected to be set up in the coming year.
The new measures also allow for appeals in cases where a person who has been
convicted of an offence has died.
They widen the powers of magistrates courts to vary or withdraw a sentence, or
to order a matter to be reheard.
The Court of Appeal will be able to allow an appeal against an unsafe
conviction.
This replaces the three-fold grounds for appeal which were that a conviction
was unsafe or unsatisfactory, that it was wrong in question of law, or there
had been a ``material irregularity''.
</TEXT>
