<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Skye crofters show the way</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Ross</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684172</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
David Ross reports on the achievements of a group
of crofters who have been quietly building a future
for their families on their own land
Melness crofters are currently preparing to take control of the 11,000 acres
being presented to them by their Nottinghamshire-based landlord Michael
Foljambe; their neighbours in Borgie, Skerray, and Tongue are wondering whether
the Countess of Sutherland can be persuaded to do likewise in the new year; and
everybody else connected to crofting is eagerly awaiting the Secretary of
State's White Paper. Crofting is in the headlines again.
The 20 crofters in the Skye townships of Borve and Annishader, meanwhile, are
going about their business, running their 4500 acres as they have done for the
past two years since their landlord agreed to sell; trying to build a future
for their families on their own land.
The Skye crofters have lived in the shadow of those in Assynt whose purchase in
December 1992 of the 21,000-acre North Lochinver estate from a bankrupt Swedish
land company, was to become such an inspiration to rural communities, and a
powerful symbol to the rest of Scotland. Although largely ignored, Borve's
achievement has also been crucially important and provides a more likely
blueprint for other townships dealing with private landlords.
In fact it was their landlord, Major John Macdonald, who first suggested that
the crofters should consider buying part of his Skeabost Estate. This was after
he and the crofters had failed to reach an agreement over a proposal for a
project under the 1991 Crofter Forestry Act.
There had been a tradition of particularly generous landlords on the Skeabost
Estate, most notably Major Macdonald's grandfather, Lachlan Macdonald, who took
over the estate in 1874. Reputed to be the richest man in Skye of his time, he
behaved in a manner uncharacteristic of the landowning class in the
nineteenth-century Highlands. He cancelled all arrears of his tenants and
allowed them to fix their own rents. These have remained largely unchanged.
But the people of the two townships realised that they needed more, they had to
prepare their community for the twenty-first century. Alistair Nicolson is a
native of Borve, the secretary and a director of the Borve and Annishader
Townships Ltd. He lived and worked abroad but now he is an information
technology adviser to Skye and Lochalsh Enterprise. But his place is Borve;
next door to his uncle, who lives in his grandfather's house; down the road
from his father.
``It was all kick-started some years ago by some of us wanting to diversify
from being wholly dependent on sheep and we were very aware of the declining
number of cattle. So we were looking for other options. The Crofter Forestry
Bill was going through Parliament at the time so we said we started to
investigate the possibilities. We talked to various bodies and realised it
wouldn't cost us an arm and a leg so we wrote asking for permission to plant 20
hectares from our landlord as we were required to do, but the letter came back
unsigned.
``He wasn't opposed to the principle but wanted to talk about the future
management of the estate. Eventually he suggested we buy our townships or the
whole estate. We had never suggested it, although it might have been at the
back of our minds after the earlier offer made by the Department of Agriculture
and Fisheries to hand their crofts over.''
They discussed it among themselves and decided to try to purchase their own
crofts and common grazing, 1500 hectares in all. ``There had been some who
disagreed with the forestry project but there were no dissenters to the
buy-out, everybody was behind it. The news from Assynt had given us impetus.''
Negotiations were long and drawn out and lasted the best part of a year. In the
end the crofters decided to put in an offer based on the 1976 Crofting Act
formula of 15 times a fair rent, but their rent had been unchanged throughout
the century. So they updated it by multiplying the average by five and again by
15, giving a total of about #14,000.
``That was turned down flat, but we started to talk in that region. We added
something for goodwill and something for the sporting and mineral rights and we
came to #20,000. This was agreed on the basis that the sporting rights were
leased back to him on a 99-year lease, but there isn't any sporting activity
here anyway.''
The crofters had raised most of the money themselves and had a top-up loan from
the Highland Fund, but agreement was struck in principle in December 1993 and
it was recorded on January 31, 1994.
``The first thing we did was to get our forestry project off the ground, 20
hectares planted mainly at the beginning of this year, mostly native
broadleaves, but with some Scots pine and hybrid larch. We were looking to
forestry to provide support in the same way as sheep did through subsidies. It
provides a planting premium and an annual management premium which should bring
in about #1200 a year over 20 years.
``That was stage one, now the application for phase two is in for approval.
This is about 50 hectares near the main Portree/Uig road which should bring in
about #3000 a year. So that would be over #4000 coming into the community every
year, which over the 20 years is quite a lot of money to reinvest. We are also
looking at coppiced alder as a possible timber product in this second phase.''
As in Assynt, the people of Borve and Annishader are producing imaginative
projects to help develop their interests. They are already helping the setting
up of a riding school on their land. ``We originally thought of it as primarily
a tourist attraction, but most of the trade has been from local kids. On a
Saturday there are about 20 going there.''
They are also looking very seriously at the potential of wind power, harnessing
the winds that funnel down Loch Snizort from the north-west to generate
electricity which could then be sold to the national grid.
``Of course we could always sell house sites, we could pay off the #20,000 that
way, but that's not something we really want to do, apart from giving the young
people, the families growing up, a chance to stay here.''
But it is not just the crofters who have a stake in what is happening in Borve
and Annishader. Automatic membership of the Townships Ltd was given to all the
crofters who had paid the money, and they in turn appointed five directors from
their midst. But membership is also open to anybody who is living in the area,
although the directors retain the powers to ensure that the crofting element is
never swamped by non-crofting interests.
That in itself is almost a statement, a first principle, that the people of
Borve and Annishader will not forget what they are about, what their place
means to them.
</TEXT>
