<HEADLINE>New York's mayor tries to curb reckless cab drivers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From LARRY McSHANE New York, Tuesday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684173</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT'S a typical New York City street scene: a reckless taxi driver, ignoring
traffic and pedestrians, swerves across four lanes to pick up a pedestrian
illegally standing in the street.
Now mayor Rudolph Giuliani wants to ease the chronic congestion on city streets
and make them a more genteel place.
He has proposed a daytime ban on hailing cabs in the heart of New York, with
people instead lining up politely at taxi stands and drivers queuing up neatly
for passengers.
``This law cannot work,'' taxi driver Asif Chaudray said today. ``Most people
want, `Right here! Right now!' If you go 5ft further, they get crazy. They get
mad.''
Eric Jones, 29, of New York, who was waiting patiently for a cab outside the
Port Authority bus terminal, said: ``If I want a cab, I'm just going to get
one. And most likely, he'll pick me up. That's just how it works. People in New
York don't wait in line.''
Under Giuliani's proposal - the latest in his ``quality of life'' campaign that
has cracked down on beggars and public drinkers - taxi stands would operate
weekdays between 10am and 4pm in midtown New York.
Passengers could be dumped up to 30 yards from their destinations. Rebellious
cabbies could be fined up to $55.
In New York, stepping into traffic to hail a cab is a tradition dating to the
turn of the century. It worked in the days of the horse and cart.
``New York wouldn't feel like New York if you couldn't hail a cab,'' said
Aliona Ru, 34, who moved to Manhattan four years ago. ``It's more than a New
York tradition. It's a symbol of Manhattan.''
``How does a driver tell a visitor to New York City, loaded with luggage, that
the nearest taxi stop is 100 feet away?'' asked Lawrence Goldberg, an official
with the Taxi Drivers and Allied Workers Union.-AP.
</TEXT>
