<DOCNO>GH951227-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police costs may cut other services</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Christopher Reekie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684174</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By CHRISTOPHER REEKIE
FIFE Council warned yesterday that an increase in the budget for the police
might have to be paid for at the expense of other local services.
The council was responding to the Scottish Office, which had said Fife should
have 56 additional police officers on the beat in the next year but there would
be almost no extra funding for the increase.
Councillor John Simpson, vice chairman of the council's policy committee, said
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth was continuing to cap council spending, and
Fife had been told that any increase in budgeted expenditure for 1996-97 of
more than 0.8% would be seen as an excessive increase.
This would result, he said, in a shortfall of funds available for the increased
number of police officers required, and would mean the cost would have to be
met from other parts of the budget.
Councillor Andrew Keddie, chairman of the council's public protection and
regulation committee, said: ``It's a case of giving with one hand and taking
away with the other.
``We would welcome having the additional police officers on the beat, but
community policing will become extremely difficult if it has to be at the
expense of other council services.''
The council has written to the Scottish Office for clarification on the issue.
A Scottish Office spokesman said last night that Mr Forsyth had made law and
order a priority issue and would give Fife's letter full attention when he
received it.
The spokesman said that one method of getting more police officers on the beat
was to release them from clerical functions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Education draft welcomed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684175</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDUCATION must be placed at the heart of the Europe of the future, the main
teachers' union has urged.
Mr Ronnie Smith, general secretary of the Educational Institute of Scotland,
endorsed the thrust of the draft European Union White Paper on education and
training, Towards the Knowledge-Based Society.
The paper is the first main education statement by the EU since the Maastricht
Treaty placed education in the mainstream of European policy.
Mr Smith said: ``I am pleased to note the emphasis in the paper on the need for
a broad-based education where schools can provide each individual with an
understanding of the society in which they live, as well as a sense of
belonging to that society.
``In this respect the precedent set by the comprehensive system in Scotland
will be a major contribution to debate on the issue.''
He also welcomed the commitment to lifelong learning, the recognition of the
importance of vocational education in tackling unemployment, and the emphasis
on equal opportunites.
These were all areas to which the EIS, which represents eight out of 10
teachers, was committed. Mr Smith also highlighted the paper's commitment to
the status of teachers and lecturers. It would strike a chord in Scotland at a
time of severe cuts in public expenditure, he said.
The White Paper calls for increased public spending on education, particularly
in socially disadvantaged areas.
Mr Smith continued: ``With the possibility of a Scottish parliament with
control over education drawing closer, the need to give a proper priority to
education acquires a new focus, especially as the parliament will have direct
links with the other countries of the EU.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Driver, one wheel short of a full car, heads the wrong way on M4</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684176</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PENSIONER has been arrested after driving for at least 14 miles the wrong way
along a motorway with only three wheels on his car.
He was stopped only after these three wheels were punctured by spikes thrown
across the M4. He then crashed into a police car.
The 65-year-old had ignored drivers flashing their lights and police patrol
cars as he sped along the motorway with sparks flying from the front wheel hub
of his Volkswagen Jetta.
The drama happened shortly before 3am yesterday as the man, from Neasden,
north-west London, drove west along the eastbound carriageway.
He was eventually stopped near Reading, Berkshire, when police threw a Stinger
bed of spikes across the motorway.
Police were first alerted when a terrified motorist used a roadside SOS
telephone to report the Volkswagen was travelling the wrong way in the fast
lane. It was not clear how the car had lost a wheel.
A spokesman for Thames Valley Police said: ``The car was travelling at about
50mph on three wheels, with the metal hub of the front offside wheel bouncing
up and down on the motorway, causing sparks to fly off.
``We had a string of calls from worried drivers who saw the Volkswagen bearing
down on them on the wrong side of the motorway.
``Other officers used the Stinger device to stop the car and the motorist
slewed to a halt with all three remaining tyres punctured. The Volkswagen
eventually crashed into the back of a police car.''
A motorway patrol had blocked the eastbound lanes of the M4 at Reading and held
back traffic as the car sped towards them.
Officers arrested the motorist on suspicion of being unfit to drive through
drink or drugs. He was taken to Maidenhead police station, where he was still
being held in cells.
A police spokesman said the G-registered Jetta appeared to belong to the
pensioner although it was not known why he was driving the wrong way down the
motorway or where he had joined it.
``So far he has not given a word of explanation to the police,'' the spokesman
added.
``Fortunately no-one was injured in the incident. The motorway was much quieter
than usual because it was the early hours of Boxing Day.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
