<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Isle of Man's enviable position</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684178</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS astonished that in Hamish Paton's article (Time for a tartan tax-break,
December 7) he made no reference to the economic situation of the Isle of Man.
Quasi-independent, it has complete freedom over tax-rates and legislation,
powers that Labour's proposed Scottish assembly can only dream of.
This is all the more poignant given the recent announcement that Loganair
(``Scotland's Airline'') is moving its headquarters to the Isle of Man and
showing the hypocrisy of the United Kingdom Government. ``Stick with the
Union,'' we are told, ``or you'll lose jobs and investment.''
Oh really? Why have companies like Loganair moved? Could it be anything to do
with the lower business taxation in this Crown dependency? Why should the Isle
of Man be given full autonomy to make laws and set taxes, yet Scotland not?
Could it be because the Isle of Man is suitable as a haven for rich Labour and
Tory MPs to stash their cash? Or could it be because London fears that an
independent Scotland would become a low business tax environment, encouraging
investment and real competition within the UK market, free from the incentives
of ``London weighting''?
Hamish Mitchell,
12 Dean Road,
Kilmarnock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Erratic snow saves bookies #100,000</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684179</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DESPITE what you see when you look out of the window, it has not been a white
Christmas.
That is the ruling by weather experts south of the Border who insist that it is
not an official white Christmas unless it happens in London.
But bets which specified a city will be honoured. Glasgow had no actual
snowfall so bets naming there will lose, but Edinburgh had a few flakes and
bets there will be paid.
One Edinburgh man celeafter picked up #1000 on a #140 bet. Across the rest of
the UK, punters took more than #25,000 in winnings. No snow in London saved the
bookies #100,000.
English-based meteorologist Robert Ashwell said: ``It snowed in Aberdeen,
Edinburgh, Norwich, Belfast, Manchester, Nottingham, Newcastle, and Leeds. But
this year will not go down as a white Christmas because it did not snow in
London.''
Long-range forecaster Piers Corbyn correctly predicted snow falling or lying in
10 cities. The ``alternative'' meteorologist and astrophysicist made his
predictions in September, based on changes in the sun's particle activity, and
put the money on last month. He stands to collect up to #3000.
He said: ``We also predicted a bitterly cold Christmas to New Year spell - with
temperatures as low as minus 11 degrees Celsius in places and blizzards around
New Year's Eve turning to sleet and rain in the first few days of January.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish group spreads euthanasia on Internet</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684180</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH organisation is to circulate information about euthanasia on the
Internet.
The Scottish Voluntary Euthanasia Society yesterday announced details of its
access point for information and news on subjects such as voluntary euthanasia,
living wills, and refusal of medical treatment.
Euthanasia groups in America, Canada, Australia, and Spain are already on the
Internet.
Fifteen electronic pages prepared by the Scottish group are currently available
on the computer network.
The society also distributes a book called Departing Drugs which tells people
how they can kill themselves.
But executive secretary Chris Docker said none of this information would be
transmitted on the 'Net.
``The book is only available to people who can prove they have been members of
a euthanasia group for at least three months,'' he said.
``It is a rule we have to discourage emotionally upset teenagers. We will
certainly not be giving information on how to kill yourself on the Internet.
``We want to supply up-to-date information and informed comment. We are mainly
a research and liaison group and this is an important aspect of liaison.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Foreign Digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974684181</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Plane hijack
bid foiled
DUBAI: An Ethiopian passenger tried to storm the cockpit of a Saudi Arabian
airliner on a flight from Asmara to Addis Ababa yesterday but was overpowered
by the crew, the official Saudi Press Agency (SPA) said. One of the crew
members was injured as they overpowered the man who rushed towards the cockpit,
armed with a paper knife and a broken glass bottle, SPA said, quoting an
official of the state-owned Saudia airlines.
Bomb suspects
PESHAWAR: Pakistani police identified two Persian-speaking Afghans yesterday as
the bombers who killed 42 people in the northwestern city of Peshawar last
week. Both are on the run and may have fled the country. Peshawar has a large
population of Afghan refugees who fled their country during civil war since
1979.
Three beheaded
PARIS: Gunmen, thought to be Muslim rebels, have kidnapped and beheaded three
peasants and dumped their bodies by a roadside near Algiers, an Algerian
newspaper said yesterday. Quoting victims' families and witnesses, the paper
said the peasants were killed because they had spurned guerrilla demands for
money to support their violent campaign against the government and refused to
have their sons join the rebels.
Mafia arrest
CREMONA: The desire of an alleged Mafia chief to spend Christmas with his
family led to his arrest, Italian police said yesterday. Eugenio Barresi, 35,
was arrested at the home of a friend as he celebrated the holiday with his wife
and two children, police said. They said investigators tracked him down after
discovering his family had travelled from the Sicilian city of Messina to an
area outside the northern town of Cremona.
Beach clashes
SYDNEY: Police in riot gear clashed with hundreds of Christmas revellers early
yesterday as crowds attacked a bus and cars at Sydney's famous Bondi beach,
police said. Two policemen were slightly hurt as police were struck by bottles,
stones and other objects thrown by revellers, many of them drunk, a spokesman
said. There were no arrests.
Trawler sinks
OSLO: One seaman was found dead and nine were reported missing after a Russian
trawler sank in a storm in Arctic waters off Norway yesterday, Norwegian
authorities said. 15 seamen were rescued by a companion Russian trawler and
were said to be in good condition. Officials had previously reported only 14
were rescued.
Feathers fly
NAIROBI: Kenya staged its first ostrich race yesterday with Flash Harry taking
track honours in a 200-metre sprint. Six riders and their birds battled it out
on the Ngong racecourse on the outskirts of Nairobi. Stewards looked on aghast
as several race birds scampered off to a premature start.
Yeltsin moves
MOSCOW: Russian President Boris Yeltsin left a sanatorium where he had been
recovering from a heart ailment and moved to a neighbouring country residence,
his press service said yesterday. It said Yeltsin, 64, would follow doctors'
instructions during his stay at the Barvikha residence, near Moscow. Itar-Tass
news agency said he would mark the New Year there with his family.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Series of house fires claims lives of five</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684182</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SERIES of festive season fires left five people, including a two-year-old
girl, dead and one woman fighting for her life last night.
A man aged 94 died on Christmas Day after falling on to an electric heater in
his home.
A woman neighbour was alerted when she heard John Rae's smoke alarm going off.
She found him lying in agony across the heater with his trousers on fire, but
was unable to pull him clear of the blistering heat.
She ran back into the street and with the help of a male passer-by managed to
lift Mr Rae off the heater and put out the flames.
They comforted Mr Rae, a widower who lived alone at Wellfield Road, in Hawick,
until an ambulance arrived.
He was taken to Borders General Hospital where he later died as a result of
extensive burns.
The neighbour who went to Mr Rae's aid was treated in hospital for shock.
Meanwhile, a woman was fighting for her life in hospital last night after being
overcome by smoke in a blaze at her home in Brechin Road, Arbroath.
Mrs Alison Smith, who is in her thirties, was taken to Perth Royal Infirmary
after firefighters found her slumped in her living room on Monday night.
The alarm was raised by a brother who had gone to visit her.
The woman's husband was last night maintaining a bedside vigil and her
condition was said to be ``poorly''.
Police said that the minor fire, thought to have been started accidentally, was
swiftly extinguished.
In Wales, a mother and her two-year-old daughter died yesterday when fire swept
through the upper storey of their home in Llanybri, near Carmarthen.
The woman's husband escaped by leaping through a bedroom window before forcing
his way back through a rear door to rescue their two other daughters, aged four
and five.
He was detained in hospital for treatment to severe cuts sustained as he
smashed his way through the bedroom window to escape the flames.
The two rescued children were taken to hospital for observation but were not
injured.
It took firefighters 90 minutes to bring the blaze under control and a fire
service spokesman said: ``It appears to have started in one of the bedrooms and
spread through the ceiling.''
An inquiry into the cause was under way last night but police said they did not
suspect foul play.
Police were withholding the names of the family until next of kin had been
traced.
In Bletchley, Buckinghamshire, an 80-year-old woman, who has not been named,
was burned to death after slipping on to the fire in the living room of her
home.
A police spokesman said: ``It looks as if she may have fallen across the fire
and set herself alight.''
The cause of a blaze which killed 90-year-old William Benson in his home in
Grasmere, Cumbria, yesterday was still being investigated last night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chorus of disapproval over fisheries pantomime</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alex Salmond</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684183</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAVE you heard the one about the Hogmanay haddock? This is not a reference to
one of the less successful turns at this year's TV Ne'erday shows but a
particular type of fish swimming in the waters round Scotland.
A couple of years back the whys and whereabouts of this festive fish dominated
the debate at European Standing Committee B in the House of Commons. The point
at issue was whether the haddock in question realised that the quota year ended
with the calendar and that in terms of regulation it was okay for fishermen to
catch them on Ne'erday but off limits for them to be caught on Hogmanay.
Did the haddock go into hiding at the start of the year as they realised the
nets were out looking for them once again or did they summon forth
reinforcements to cope with the restart of the quota allocations?
In reality haddock and all the other fish do get a few days respite at the turn
of the year since the pride of the Scottish fleet has been safely in port since
last Friday and will remain there until well into next week. The real question,
therefore, is will the hard-pressed Scottish fishing industry get some respite
over the coming 12 months or will it continue to drift from crisis to crisis.
Last week saw the curtain come down again on the annual pantomime of fisheries
negotiations. The plot is the same for every performance. The principal boy,
otherwise known as the English Fisheries Minister, goes into battle to deal
with a crisis situation, and comes out claiming the biggest victory over the
Spaniards since Drake drubbed the first Armada.
He then appeals to the fishing community to hail his success and is greeted by
a loud chorus of ``Oh no you haven't''.
The anger of fishing communities is understandable. Not only are they facing
regulation but they are under restrictions which make no sense either from the
economic or the conservation point of view.
Take the quota allocations for example. The constant refrain of Fisheries
Ministers is that tight quotas protect stocks for the future.
However, the fishermen know better. One of the consequences of tough quotas is
actually to increase the amount of fish being caught. First it increased the
number of discards - that is the good fish thrown back dead into the sea after
being caught in the nets.
This happens in two ways. First, the waters around Scotland are mixed fisheries
where the various species are caught together. This means that fish which are
out of quota are caught with ones which still have allocations to land. Thus
the regulations prescribe that the over-quota fish should be returned dead into
the sea.
Second, when only a small quota allocation is allowed it puts a premium on
landing decent-sized fish and thus the boats select the very best from their
catch with the smaller fish tipped over the side.
It should be stressed that these discards are quite legal as opposed to the
``black'' fish on non-market landings which are the other consequence of people
being faced with breaking the quotas or breaking up their boats. It is not easy
to feel comfortable about the operation of a conservation policy which says it
is acceptable to dump fish dead into the sea but unacceptable to land the same
fish at official markets.
However, that is exactly the policy framework which the pantomime players have
been defending over the past few years which is why Fisheries Minister Tony
Baldry would be hard pushed to beat Jack the Ripper in a straight electoral
contest in any fishing port.
While other fleets receive the policy priority and support from their
governments, fishing is treated in the United Kingdom as a poor relation.
That can be judged in a number of ways. Most dramatically in terms of
structural support where, thanks to the obduracy of John Selwyn Gummer as the
former Minister of Agriculture and Fisheries, the industry was frozen out of
European assistance available to every other fleet across the Continent.
Then, more recently, there was the mysterious deal by which Spain was allowed
to rewrite its own Treaty of Accession to the European Union in order to gain
entry into western waters some six years ahead of the agreed timetable.
Whatever was offered by Spain in exchange for this remarkable concession we can
be reasonably sure it had nothing to do with the fishing industry.
Spain now dictates Fisheries Policy from within the European Union while Norway
calls the shots in joint negotiations from outside the Common Fisheries Policy.
Little wonder under these circumstances why Scottish fishermen feel out in the
cold.
There is a glimmer of light at the end of this long tunnel. On his way out of
the fisheries talks last week with his mind concentrated by the Government
humiliation in the House of Commons, Mr Baldry remarked that perhaps in future
the annual quota policy could be modified to take account of technical
conservation - ie designing nets and fishing gear which would allow young fish
to escape alive rather than being discarded dead into the sea.
That exactly this approach had been pressed on successive Ministers by
exasperated fishermen over the past seven years is not beside the point. What
Scottish fishermen require is a Government which will see fishing as one of the
great natural resource industries of the nation. Not something to be traded
away for wider interests. When the industry achieves that degree of policy
support then more fish than just the Hogmanay haddock will be able to swim
happily in the sea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Horrors of the 1939-45 war</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684184</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS we put 1995 behind us and, in particular, the commemoration services for VE
and VJ Days, there is a real danger that we will also put the Second World War
behind us.
In fact, as power in the world passes into the hands of people who grew up
after the war, the need for strengthening and sharpening the nation's memories
of the horrors (as well as the heroisms) of the 1939-45 war is greater than
ever.
I write this letter as a former 2nd (Hong Kong) Battalion Royal Scot. Hong
Kong, sacrificed by Churchill as an ``inevitable casualty of war'', with the
troops only to be given their day-to-day orders, and otherwise to be told
nothing, was a uniquely tragic disaster area.
In the two weeks leading up to Christmas 1941 when the colony capitulated to
the Japanese Imperial Army, the spirit of Christmas was totally transcended (if
that is the right word) by the cruel and sadistic spirit of Bushido; and the
following four years were disfigured by atrocities so shameful that it would be
an insult to the animal world to call them bestial.
My resolutions for 1996 will be: (1) to send greetings to the survivors of
these tragic and terrible times, including the gallant Rajputs and the brave
young Canadian soldiers who (insult being added to injury) were dispatched to
Hong Kong as a face-saving gesture, and dispatched, therefore, to certain
defeat and humiliation.
(2) To get the Japanese to stop apologising and start to provide us with hard
evidence that they have turned their backs on the despicable behaviour of their
armed forces in the Second World War. Until that is done, the names Mitsubishi,
Toyota, Suzuki, and Yamaha will continue to make my stomach turn.
(3) To get the British Government to ``swear on oath'' that they will never
again fail to live up to their responsibilities, as they did in respect of Hong
Kong 54 years ago.
Bill Nicol,
13 St Leonard Terrace,
Lockerbie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Immense pressure for sales</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684185</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PHILIP Greig's letter (December 19) is timely.
Whatever Ian Lang said about the Forestry Commission woodlands remaining in the
public sector, it is now (and for all I know, was in his day) policy that the
commission must divest itself of 10% of its landholding by the year 2000,
and/or achieve a figure of #7-10m a year via land sales. Obtaining information
on this subject is not easy, but if I am wrong no doubt some spokesperson will
correct my figures.
This income, obtained in effect by divesting itself of capital, goes into the
Forest Enterprise funds, just as the income from the sale of timber or
Christmas trees, both renewable resources, would do.
As I understand it, Forest Enterprise has to reach a certain income target each
year. If circumstances force a reduced income from timber sales (and as the
timber price is decreed by international markets, we can do little in Britain
to influence timber prices), the pressure to increase land sales to make up the
timber shortfall will be immense. The ``bottom line'', which is always
important, is now everything.
There are only two forest types which are not for sale (at present). First
where the local populace make significant use of the forest for social
purposes; walking, birdwatching, orienteering, etc. Secondly where the forest
timber production is required for ongoing legally binding long-term contracts
with sawmillers, etc.
This ties in well with Mr Greig's quotation from John Gummer: ``The key
benefits (of selling off the FC) are that it would raise money, and would get
the forest estate out of the public sector''.
Mr Greig comments on privatisation by the back door; how right he is.
A recent gambit is to pressure the FC into contracting out the replanting of
felled areas to private operators, with little experience, if any, of this work
- which is far more difficult than the original plough planting ever was. It
also requires much more intensive supervision if it is to be successful.
The Gummers and Forsyths of this world, alas, seem ignorant of forestry, and
they refuse to believe that those who serve or served in state forestry ever
actually earned their salaries. Far better was the man in a forestry company;
the fact that he was entirely dependent on a 98% tax handout of taxpayers'
money, insulating him from any semblance of the real world, is conveniently
forgotten.
If Mr Greig expects integrity, yes, and a pride in the long-term achievements
of the Forestry Commission from this present crop of political carpetbaggers,
he is being unrealistic.
The days of the Willie Whitelaws, Ian Macleods, and the Buchanan-Smiths are
long gone. The giants of the political integrity forest are gone; we are left
with the scrub.
Roy S Carlaw,
Burleywell, St Mungo,
Lockerbie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>North Korea frees captives Crew and bodies handed over in goodwill gesture</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From LIM YUN-SUK Seoul, Tuesday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684186</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIVE crew members of a South Korean trawler seized by the North were handed
back today with the remains of three colleagues, and media reports said the
gesture may help Pyongyang win rice aid to relieve famine.
Bundled up in winter coats, the five sailors carrying identical grey suitcases
marched across the border crossing point at the village of Panmunjom after
turning to wave to their captors and shout ``thank you''.
Ashes of three others contained in boxes wrapped in white cloth were handed to
Red Cross representatives who handed them them to weeping relatives.
Survivors said one fisherman was shot and killed and another died in a fire
when their vessel, the Woosung 86, was captured in May. The third died of
illness.
South Korea's Yonhap news agency quoted a diplomatic source as saying officials
from Seoul, Washington and Tokyo would hold a two-day summit starting on
January 24 in Hawaii to discuss resuming food aid to the North.
Washington would be represented by Winston Lord, the senior official for East
Asia and the Pacific, Tokyo by deputy foreign minister Shunji Yanai and Seoul
by deputy foreign minister Lee Jai-chun, Yonhap quoted the source in Seoul as
saying.
South Korean officials could not confirm the report.
Seoul shipped 150,000 tonnes of rice earlier this year but halted further
deliveries in October after after public opinion turned against President Kim
Young-sam for delivering aid without extracting the release of the boat and its
crew.
South Korea ignored a United Nations call to maintain the aid flow and asked
Japan and its allies to follow suit. Tokyo has sent 300,000 tonnes of a
promised consigment of 500,000 tonnes of rice.
Aid agencies say North Korea needs almost four million tonnes of rice to
prevent mass starvation after floods ruined the summer grain crop.
Before the five crew were repatriated, North Korea's state-run Korean Central
News Agency reported that the captain had apologised for ``intruding'' into
Northern waters.
Captain Pak Jae-ryol had ``expressed sincere and deep thanks to the authorities
of the North for showing leniency and compatriotic hospitality and sending them
back''.
After crossing the border, Pak told reporters: ``We were cared for very well''.
Crew member Kim Bu-gon echoed his comments, although he said the group had
survived on a diet of gruel at the inn in which they were held.
The five crew warmly shook hands with North Korean military officers and
civilian officials before walking across the border and being embraced by their
tearful relatives.
Tension is mounting on the Korean peninsula as Pyongyang masses war planes and
stages military maneouvres close to the heavily-fortified Demilitarised Zone
that has divided the two Koreas since the 1950-53 Korean War.
Japan warned yesterday that starving refugees may start flowing into China from
North Korea.
``We cannot turn a blind eye to this situation in a neighbouring country, and
together with South Korea and the United Nations, we must adopt appropriate
measures,'' said Koken Nosaka, Japan's top government spokesman.
In a sign that worsening food problems are prompting an ideological tightening
in the beleaguered North, the Pyongyang media yesterday extensively reported
comments by Kim Jong-il demanding respect for ``revolutionary elders''.
Today the Korean Central News Agency reported that Kim - who has yet to inherit
the title of president and secretary general of the ruling Korean Worker's
Party from his late father Kim Il-sung - made his first public appearance in
more than one month yesterday.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Limitations of structure plans</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684187</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN MacCalman's review of Strathclyde's Structure Plan (December 18) was weak
in its analysis of the problems associated with regenerating Glasgow's deprived
areas and derelict sites.
He gave the impression that if it had not been for some unwelcome political
pressure here and a derelict land grant there, substantially more would have
been achieved.
The fact is that structure plans alone cannot achieve sustainable regeneration.
An effective regeneration strategy requires a multi-agency approach involving
not only the local authorities, but also the local enterprise companies,
Scottish Homes, government departments, the private sector, the community, and
others.
Working partnerships are difficult to achieve. Even within Strathclyde Regional
Council itself the actions of some departments did not seem to be consistent
with its structure plan or its anti-poverty strategies.
The challenge for the new unitary councils is not just to sink their
differences in the Clyde Valley Joint Advisory Committee.
They must fight departmentalism within and seek meaningful partnerships with
other agences.
Colin Armstrong,
Chief Executive,
Scottish Urban Regeneration Forum,
Broomloan House,
170 Edmiston Drive,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Millennium Link for canals</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684188</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I AM happy to reply to Mr McLaughland's letter regarding the plans to reopen
the Forth &amp; Clyde and Union canals (December 19).
The Millennium Link is a project which has been driven by the aspirations of
ordinary people in communities right across Scotland.
Our partnership not only includes the recognised public agencies but involves
local communities which have a direct interest in their environment. It was
these people who demanded that the opportunity to resubmit a revised proposal
should not be missed.
The project aims to take a neglected but nevertheless magnificent piece of
Scottish engineering and transform it for a vibrant and viable new use. It has
something for everyone, and is easily accessible to 70% of Scotland's
population.
Over 100 schools are within 10 minutes' walk of the canals. Surely the lottery
is about giving something back to communities. We are confident that the
project matches the criteria set down by the Millennium Commission.
Lottery monies are only part of the story. Other competitive funds are also
needed to achieve succss. Again, the partnership is confident the project
stands scrutiny. Urban and rural regeneration will deliver 1500 jobs during
construction, over 4000 permanent new jobs, and an annual injection of over
#40m to the Scottish economy.
Massive public support and pressure from communities convinced the Millennium
Link partnership to resubmit. The original bid was for #50m of Millennium Fund
monies towards a total project cost of #100m, with all work to be complete in
the year 2000. The revised bid for #30m envisages a two-stage project with
ultimate completion by 2010, at a total cost of #95m.
Navigation is not the main objective of the Millennium Link. It is the vital
ingredient that provides a catalyst to release the benefits. Far more people
will benefit from land-based activity than will ever use the water, but
worldwide experience has shown that the water must be actively used to
stimulate other activity.
Local experience has shown that restoring discrete sections cannot provide the
impetus in the canal corridor that the whole project can. Providing a
cross-Scotland link and making the physical connection between communities is
crucial. It is the completeness of the Link idea that makes it millennial.
The plans have never seriously envisaged the re-creation of an unlimited
headroom ship canal or freight link between the Forth and the Clyde. I totally
agree with Mr McLaughland that opening bridges would cause unacceptable
congestion and this has never been viewed as a practical option.
Indeed, the bridges recently built as part of the Glasgow Canal Project, such
as at The Stables restaurant near Kirkintilloch, demonstrate that fixed bridges
are the favoured solution.
The Millennium Link is not about resurrecting a piece of nostalgia. It is about
providing an invaluable educational, environmental heritage, tourism, and
recreational resource which can significantly add to the quality of life in
central Scotland.
James M Stirling,
Manager, Scotland,
British Waterways,
1 Applecross Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murdered girl may have been in row</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684189</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE murdered Kilmarnock teenager, Mhairi Julyan, may have been arguing with a
youth on the night of her death, according to the police.
A witness has reported seeing a girl similar to Mhairi's description apparently
having a row with a young man outside the Broomhill Hotel in the town's London
Road, at 10.30pm on Saturday, December 16.
The incident was one of two possible sightings of Mhairi released yesterday by
police hunting the 16-year-old's killer.
Detective Chief Inspector Bob Lauder, who is heading the inquiry, also gave
details of a man seen running from the area where she disappeared.
He appealed for further information on the sightings, and urged anyone
described by the police to come forward and eliminate themselves.
Mr Lauder said: ``It is possible that two of these were sightings of Mhairi. If
so, she was with someone else who knows something. But we are not sure, and the
people who saw that person are unable to take the description any further.''
The first incident involves the young couple outside the hotel.
The teenage girl, who was sitting on the wall, had dark curly hair, possibly
shoulder length, and was wearing a black bomber jacket. The male, also a
teenager, had short hair, and was wearing a dark waist-length jacket and dark
trousers.
Shortly afterwards, three young people were seen at a telephone kiosk at the
corner of Melville Street and London Road. The female outside the booth was a
teenager about 5ft tall, with longish hair, wearing a dark Hoi Polloi bomber
jacket - similar to the one worn by Mhairi on the night of her death - and
either a long dark skirt or dark trousers.
The male with her was also a teenager, with dark hair, wearing possibly jeans
and a dark, silky blouson jacket, while the male in the kiosk was aged about
17/18, with short blond hair, and wearing a light top. Mr Lauder said the third
appeal related to a man seen running from Samson Avenue, across London Road,
and up a pathway between Alloway Avenue and Dunure Drive at 12.30am on the
Sunday. He was between 18 and 30, 6ft 2in tall, of slim to medium build,
possibly with fair hair, and wearing a fawn sweatshirt and jeans.
Mhairi's body was found near a bus station in the town the day after she
disappeared while returning home from attending a pantomime in Kilmarnock's
Palace Theatre.
Mr Lauder asked the public to continue giving his team the ``tremendous
assistance'' they had so far offered, and said he was convinced that someone
still held vital information. People noticing that relatives or friends were
experiencing unexplained mood swings or acting out of character should contact
the police in confidence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Higher social class the main factor School lesson on myth of parent power</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684190</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PARENT power is a myth, according to a Europe-wide survey of their involvement
in schooling.
There has also in Scotland been an increase in parental apathy, with fewer
applying for school boards.
The research, carried out by the European Parents Association, focuses on their
role in school management.
It concludes that parental involvement is almost exclusively in the hands of
middle and upper class representatives, partly because expertise is required
for the role, which favours graduates, civil servants, teachers, and high-level
technicians.
This has led to the emergence of a few ``super parents''. The way school
administrations and even local authorities designate parents ``makes any form
of democratic participation a dead letter, guaranteeing its failure,'' says the
association.
Parents who do become involved find that the reality of the job is far greater
than the role envisaged for them.
``The decentralisation of areas of responsibility from the central
administrative level to school level generally leads to an increase in
workload, in the expertise required, and in the decision-making procedures at
the individual school level,'' says the research, published today.
Across Europe, parents are invited to participate in the management of
education, which generally means joining consultative groups and
decision-making bodies at school level.
However, says the association, this form of participative management ``is
imposing on parents an increasing burden of responsibility in the schools, and
is giving rise to some resistance and disaffection on the part of . . . the
parents.''
The Scottish Parent Teacher Council, a member association of the EPA, said the
autumn round of school board elections confirmed a growing trend of parental
apathy in Scotland.
Only 60% of Strathclyde region's schools now have full boards, and of those
less than 9% had elections. The remainder secured the minimum number of parents
to fill arising vacancies and they were appointed without election.
The authority has half of Scotland's schools in its area. Mrs Judith Gillespie,
convener of the SPTC, said there was a mixed picture in the remainder of
Scotland, with Tayside region showing similar returns, but Lothian providing
better voting returns.
The SPTC said parents were too busy to take on what amounted to another
part-time job. It feared that parental reluctance to join boards would increase
because of devolved school management (DSM), under which heads are responsible
for the vast majority of school-based spending.
All schools will operate under DSM by April next year and parents will be able
to have a say in the appointment of all staff, if they wish. But the SPTC
feared that this new management would impose extra burdens on parents.
The EPA research also advises governments not to overestimate parent power.
``The school is the school . . . The problems and future mistakes of this
institution must not be placed on the shoulders of the parents,'' it says in a
clear warning of the dangers of taking short-term, politically motivated
decisions which do not act in the long-term interests of schools or their
pupils.
The SPTC will discuss the EPA report at a meeting with the Scottish Office
Minister for Education, Mr Raymond Robertson, in the new year.
Leader comment . . . . . . . . . . . 12
</TEXT>
