<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Distraught residents join police to scour river banks for missing relatives At least 119 die in Natal flooding</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG DOONAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684191</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Edendale, South Africa, Tuesday
AT least 119 people were killed and many more are missing in floods caused by
heavy rains in South Africa's KwaZulu-Natal province.
Police divers, rescue teams, residents and helicopters today were pulling
bodies from the Umsunduzi river and its tributary, the Slangspruit, which burst
their banks.
Police spokesman Henry Budrum said 119 bodies had been recovered so far. He
added: ``We expect to find more bodies as the water level drops. We are
searching tonight and we will continue searching tomorrow.''
The victims all lived in Imbali next to the Edendale black township outside
Pietermaritzburg.
Fresh rainstorms, with thunder and lightning, hit the area yesterday. ``It is
not as severe as on Monday. The problem is the ground is so saturated at the
moment that the water runs straight into the river,'' said Mr Gary Ronald,
traffic information officer for the province.
``There are cars stuck against trees and there is clothing all over the river
banks after houses were washed away. The sheer force of the water also washed
all the vegetation away,'' he added.
Distraught residents scoured the river banks searching for relatives while a
police helicopter lifted bodies. Men, women, and children waded through mud and
bushes, many crying in anguish after discovering the bodies of relatives.
Mortuary workers said the majority of those who died appeared to have been in
their late teens. ``People have been coming to look for up to 10 people per
family,'' one mortuary worker said.
Imbali resident Enock Nhlangulela said he had lost nine relatives in the
floods. ``So far we have recovered four bodies. But we are still missing five
relatives, including my three-week old sister.
``I was lucky because I went to visit friends when the heavy rains came. When I
returned I found everyone and everything inside the house had been washed
away,'' he said.
Mrs Pendukile Masikane, 50, said she had lost her husband and a daughter.
``The water came inside and washed everything away including my husband and my
child. I managed to make it to safety, but I have lost everything, even my
house was swept away,'' she said.
The people who lost their homes were being accommodated in community halls in
the local township. Provincial parliamentarian Sifiso Nkabinde said the
regional government had declared Imbali township a disaster area.
q At least 20 people died in flooding and mudslides caused by torrential rain
in southern Brazil, the civil defence force said today.
A force spokesman said the death toll could rise in the southern state of Santa
Catarina, where rain had been heaviest, and that at least 2000 people had been
made homeless in the state.
There were also heavy downpours in the neighbouring state of Rio Grande do Sul,
which had been dry since October. About 1300 people were evacuated from their
homes due to the rain.
q Floods and landslides caused by weeklong rains in northeastern provinces of
the Philippines have killed at least 18 people, authorities said today.
The rain caused rivers to spill over into low-lying towns, disrupting Christmas
festivities and sending thousands of families fleeing to higher ground in towns
in the provinces of Cagayan, Isabela and Aurora, about 170 miles northeast of
Manila..-Reuter.
</TEXT>
