<HEADLINE>Septic shock girl in critical state</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974684192</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Septic shock girl
in critical state
A 16-YEAR-OLD Oban girl suffering from pneumonia and septic shock remained in a
critical condition last night in Glasgow's Royal Infirmary.
Lorraine Watt, from Dunbeg, fell ill on Christmas Eve and was flown to Glasgow
when her condition deteriorated further on Monday. She had developed septic
shock which affected her kidneys, lungs, and circulation.
Oil pique
THE Scottish National Party yesterday spoke out against forecasts that North
Sea oil revenues would reach a new peak of #3000m next financial year. Energy
spokeswoman Nicola Sturgeon said Scotland could not afford to lose the #3000m
to Westminster.
Victims named
TWO men who died in separate Christmas Day road accidents were yesterday named
by police. Mr George Lawrence, 71, of Seafield Road, Broughty Ferry, Dundee,
died of a suspected heart attack while driving in the city. Mr William Hunter,
60, of Strathclyde Road, Motherwell, died after collapsing at the wheel of his
car en route to Aberdeen.
Taxing times
THE average worker toils for 142 days a year to pay their tax bill, economists
have revealed. The Adam Smith Institute report calculates that we work from
January to the middle of May before our debt to the Exchequer is settled.
Archers denial
BBC insiders yesterday denied that Britain's longest-running radio soap, The
Archers, would feature an Aids storyline in the new year. A spokesman said:
``This is just groundless rumour.''
Mission post
THE Rev Dr Leslie Milton, of the Presbytery of Melrose and Peebles in the
Borders, is to take up a teaching appointment at the Ricalto United Seminary
near Maputo in Mozambique.
Pool resources
DIVERS with the Cumbernauld Sub-Aqua Club have raised about #400 for charity by
swimming a mile each under water. Eight divers equipped with scuba gear swam 64
pool lengths to raise funds for the Cash for Kids Christmas appeal.
Robbery charge
A 39-YEAR-OLD man appeared on a charge of assault and robbery at Edinburgh
Sheriff Court yesterday in connection with an alleged incident in a city shop
at the weekend. Daniel McGlynn, of Restalrig Crescent, Edinburgh, appeared
briefly before Sheriff Roger Craik. The case was continued.
</TEXT>
