<HEADLINE>Power firm criticised over job losses</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684194</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HYDRO-ELECTRIC managers face a grilling from an MP and community leaders after
coming in for stinging criticism over the blackouts.
Western Isles Labour MP Calum MacDonald highlighted job cuts by the privatised
company and will meet the company chiefs later this week. He is also to table
parliamentary questions on the subject.
Mr Macdonald said he feared the recent job cuts by Hydro-Electric were reducing
the service to islanders.
``I will be asking whether recent job losses at Stornoway power station, for
example, had anything to do with the continuing power cuts around the islands.''
Lewis councillor Roddy Murray said: ``The profit motive has affected the way
the company used to operate in the best interests of their customers.
``Pleas by the elderly and parents with young children have been met with at
best non-commitment and in some instances downright hostility. Clearly the
company no longer has the resources to cope with emergencies. Our people must
never have to go through this again.''
But a Hydro-Electric spokeswoman rejected claims that the skeleton staff on
standby over the holiday period had been too small to react quickly to the
blizzards.
She said: ``I can appreciate the frustration when people are without power for
so long at this time of year, but we are pulling out all the stops to restore
supplies - it is a major task.
``We would strongly refute any suggestion that our workforce was not strong
enough to cope - it was simply down to the horrendous weather conditions.''
</TEXT>
