<HEADLINE>Struan Stevenson examines the long-running conflict over plans for an electricity link with Northern Ireland The power struggle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Struan Stevenson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684195</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL the ingredients of a modern thriller are in the campaign to stop the
building of an electricity link between Scotland and Northern Ireland.
Politics, intrigue, big money, and international business have combined to
produce a heady mix during this almost classic environmental struggle.
The STOP (Stop the overhead powerlines) Campaign was founded three years ago at
the first sign of plans by ScottishPower and Northern Ireland Electricity (NIE)
to build a 250mw interconnector between Coylton in Ayrshire and Islandmagee in
East Antrim. A huge protest meeting in Maybole Town Hall, attended by many
hundreds of protesters and with speakers from Northern Ireland and Scotland,
forced the utility giants to alter the planned route for their #200m scheme.
However, new plans indicated that 203 giant steel pylons would march across
some of Scotland's most spectacular rural scenery, terminating in a massive
converter station south of Ballantrae. From there, 40 miles of undersea cable
would take power from Scotland to another gigantic converter station built in
the scenic splendour of Islandmagee, County Antrim. More pylons and wirescape
were planned for Northern Ireland.
Soon, NIAG (North Islandmagee Action Group) joined STOP in the battle to win
the right for public inquiries at which the protesters' case could be aired.
2000 letters were sent to the Prime Minister, to the then Scottish Secretary
Ian Lang, and to Prince Charles.
Before long, STOP and NIAG had prepared a 1500-name petition which was handed
to the President of the European Parliament, Klaus Haensch, on his first day in
office.
Meanwhile, a thick dossier of evidence was being compiled by the secretariat of
the President's Committee, with enthusiastic assistance and input from Northern
Ireland MEPs Ian Paisley and John Hume, and South of Scotland MEP Alex Smith.
The protesters' high-profile campaign bore fruit. Ian Lang agreed to call for a
full public inquiry. His announcement was quickly followed by a similar
declaration from the Northern Ireland authorities. When the Scottish inquiry
opened in Ayr, the campaigners, represented by PS Public Affairs Consultants
from Edinburgh, forced Commissioner Bruce Millan to release the highly
sensitive but crucial Ove Arup Report. This report, authorised by the European
Commission, had concluded that the interconnector was ``not the most economic
option in pure generation terms''.
NIE fought to prevent its publication, claiming that it contained commercially
sensitive information. Its release exploded like a hand grenade in the middle
of the Ayr inquiry and led to a two-week postponement of the entire inquiry and
a four-month postponement of the economic case.
In Northern Ireland, NIAG had been joined by Belfast City Council and
Newtownabbey and Larne Borough Councils, all of whom were determined to prove
that the interconnector would import high-cost electricity to the Province and
export jobs. The objectors scored an immediate hit when they uncovered a breach
of European law in the method employed by NIE to publicise their plans.
A six-month postponement of the public inquiry was granted to enable this
breach to be remedied.
ScottishPower and NIE were now smarting at the mammoth cost of these delays to
their multi-million pound project, now estimated to run to some #100m.
They fought back by claiming that the interconnection between Scotland and
Northern Ireland was stated Government policy and could not, therefore, be
challenged in a planning inquiry. The presiding commissioner at the inquiry in
Larne agreed and ruled that no economic evidence would be allowed.
The objectors immediately called for a judicial review, creating a further
precedent. This was to be the first time a public inquiry ruling had ever been
judicially reviewed in the Province. After five arduous days of argument and
debate in the High Court in Belfast, the judicial review found in favour of the
presiding commissioner and ruled all economic evidence as inadmissible.
The pendulum had swung back towards the utility companies. The objectors' case,
based on interviews with over 200 of the key industries, generators, economists
and politicians in Scotland and Northern Ireland, pointed to the fact that the
project was totally uneconomic and indeed would fail in its central objective
of delivering lower-cost electricity to the Province.
Large protest meetings were held in Northern Ireland and industry
representatives came together to draw up a dossier outlining their concern
about the interconnector and highlighting how the construction of a power plant
in the Province would be much more economically attractive, providing hundreds
of jobs.
By presenting this evidence to the Electricity Regulator in Northern Ireland,
the objectors forced him to launch a detailed investigation, the results of
which were published in June. He concluded that the Scottish interconnector was
``on average #100m more expensive than other options, after an EU grant has
been taken into account but before strategic benefits have been considered''.
In other words, the interconnector was #161m worse than other options for
locally generated power, if the #61m EU grant was discounted.
It was now clear that ScottishPower and NIE were hellbent on implementing a
project aimed at providing their shareholders with lucrative profits at the
expense of wrecking the environment in parts of Scotland and Northern Ireland
and inflicting serious damage on the Ulster economy. The admission by the
Northern Ireland Regulator that he had shown a draft copy of his top-secret
report to NIE prior to its publication, but not to any of the other generators
who had also contributed to it, threw petrol on a smouldering fire of
resentment.
It was clear that the Regulator had been persuaded by NIE to alter some of his
conclusions and ignore other essential features such as the recent
re-establishment of an electricity interconnector linking Ulster and the
Republic and had come to accept their argument that the nebulous and uncosted
long-term ``strategic benefits'' of interconnection to Scotland could outweigh
the additional #100m (after grant) bill that the Ulster electricity consumers
would have to pay.
The Regulator's Gilbertian decision caused dismay, but prompted the objectors
to turn their attention to the Northern Ireland Affairs Committee, who had been
persuaded to launch a full-scale inquiry into the interconnector and
electricity prices in the Province. Evidence was gathered over six weeks of
hearings in London and Belfast, in the early summer.
Their recently published report criticised the project and stated ``there are
many unanswered questions about whether the Scottish interconnector is the best
or cheapest option for providing Northern Ireland's future generating needs and
the extent to which advantage could be made of the link with the rest of the
UK''.
In parallel with their submissions to the Northern Ireland Affairs Committee,
STOP and NIAG campaigners presented detailed reports to the European Commission
where senior officials and commissioners within the Regional Affairs,
Environment, Competition, and Energy Directorates received personal briefings.
The Commission responded by tabling a composite report supporting the
allocation of the #61m ERDF grant awarded to the interconnector and rejecting
the objectors' case at a meeting of the Petitions Committee in Brussels in
November. However, MEPs led by Alex Smith rejected the report and called for
rapporteurs to draw up detailed dossiers on the issue in the Budgetary Control,
Energy and Environment Committees. Reacting to this breakthrough, STOP
campaigners were in Brussels again just before Christmas, urging MEPs to demand
that the #61m grant be withdrawn.
STOP and NIAG campaigners have now called for a third public inquiry into the
undersea section of the project.They point to the fact that recent MoD
revelations over 1.7m tonnes of munitions and toxic chemicals were dumped in
the Beaufort's Dyke area of the North Channel since the end of the Second World
War, have given rise to huge public concern.
The objectors state that the two previous public inquiries were only able to
deal with planning matters affecting East Antrim and South Ayrshire and had no
legal jurisdiction over the undersea section. Letters have been written to
Michael Forsyth and to all affected maritime councils seeking their support for
this initiative.
It has been a long and demanding campaign, but despite confronting the combined
might of two of the wealthiest companies in Scotland and Ireland, the
objectors, with only a fraction of the resources at their disposal and fighting
to protect their environment and their jobs, have managed to outmanoeuvre the
utility giants again and again.
The outcome of the two public inquiries is not expected until the spring of
1996 although the final decision will ultimately rest with the Northern Ireland
Secretary, Sir Patrick Mayhew and his counterpart in Scotland, Michael Forsyth.
The thousands of people who have given their time, money, and expertise to help
STOP and NIAG are hoping for a victory of common sense over commercial greed.
n Struan Stevenson is a director of PS Public Affairs Consultants Ltd. He is
also the Conservative prospective  parliamentary candidate for Dumfries.
