<HEADLINE>Precis of power line inquiry ready</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684196</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE first report from a five-month inquiry into a proposed electricity
interconnector between Scotland and Northern Ireland will be published today.
The document, running to hundreds of pages outlining the facts and evidence of
the inquiry at Ayr which finished in March, will be sent by the Scottish Office
to all interested parties for their consideration.
They will be given six weeks to send their responses to Mr James McCulloch, the
Reporter who conducted the inquiry.
The parties include ScottishPower and Northern Ireland Electricity, which want
to build the interconnector, and Stop the Overhead Powerlines (Stop) campaign,
which opposes it.
All recipients of the report have been asked not to discuss its contents
publicly. The Scottish Office has emphasised that this is only the factual part
of the report and that it contains ``no recommendations, suggestions or even
hints'' on the final outcome of the reporter's deliberations.
After the six-week consultation period, during which all sides are being asked
to concentrate purely on matters of fact or evidence, Mr McCulloch will again
consider the matter before concluding his report to Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth and recommending whether the project should proceed.
ScottishPower and NIE want to build the interconnector, expected to cost in
excess of #200m, on 203 pylons across 45 miles of Ayrshire countryside and
under the North Channel to the Antrim coast.
They argue that it will assist the economies of both areas as well as making
lots of money for their shareholders.
It is the undersea section on which objectors have been concentrating their
efforts recently, and both Stop co-ordinator Struan Stevenson and local MP
George Foulkes say that the inquiry has been overtaken by events surrounding
munitions dumping.
Mr Foulkes said: ``I will read the initial report with interest but I am
continuing my efforts to have the whole project put on ice until a proper
inquiry into the effects of the undersea cabling has been conducted.
``I am not talking about a piecemeal effort aimed at appeasing the local people
but an inquiry on the scale of the land-based inquiries in Scotland and
Northern Ireland into the electricity interconnector.
``What we have learned in recent weeks about munitions dumping in the North
Channel, and what we fear and suspect about the scale of dumping, makes it
imperative that a proper look is taken at the project before any work is
carried out.
``The possible effects not only of the excavation work but also of a
high-voltage cable running through this potentially volatile area are
terrifying.''
Mr Stevenson said: ``We have written to all the local authorities who face a
coastline threat asking for their support to have the interconnector work
postponed or better still cancelled because of the threat from munitions.
``As far as the report is concerned I cannot comment on it at this stage but
what I can say is that with the possible commissioning date by ScottishPower
now put back five years to 1999 we have already cost them around #100m which
they had not budgeted for.
``We remain optimistic that common sense will prevail and this ludicrous scheme
will be consigned to the dustbin of history.''
A spokesman for ScottishPower said that he was not in a position to comment
until the report was in the hands of the company.
