<HEADLINE>Out of proportion</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684197</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN his latest essay (December 23), Professor Steve Bruce returns to dance on
the grave of Christianity and delight in informing us that only 14% of Scottish
adults now attend Sunday services regularly.
It is only to be expected, I suppose, that a sociologist should lay emphasis on
statistics but what has that to do with objective truth? The two are
incommensurate. Truth remains truth despite numbers.
Apparently he advocates democratic truth only, a short step towards
totalitarianism. For as Stalin had it, ``It doesn't matter who votes for whom,
what matters is who counts the votes''.
To put the beliefs of Christians on the same footing as that in the ``tooth
fairy'' and ``Santa Claus'' is a crass misrepresentation of history and
indicative of a primary lack of proportion normally associated with fanatics,
not illuminati. And his reiteration of a swipe at Genesis in the passing
implies a fundamentalist interpretation that he is welcome to; but his attempt
to foist it on others is patronising.
While it is true that the Church has recently been in decline so too have its
critics, if Professor Bruce is anything to go by. Oh for the refreshing blast
from the pen of a Swinburne, Bradlaugh, or Nietzsche, real atheists to a man,
rather than what passes for an erudite essay on the subject today.
Appropriately enough we are informed throughout of the case for the defence of
Scrooge, for rarely have the words ``Bah! Humbug!'' so succinctly summed up an
article.
The Church need not fear the clarion call of such a herald for if he is in a
quandary as to what to tell his own children he is most unlikely to shake the
earth.
Tom McKay,
29 Manitoba Crescent,
East Kilbride.
</TEXT>
