<HEADLINE>Rifkind says princess's wish will be considered</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684198</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN Secretary Malcolm Rifkind said yesterday that the Princess of Wales's
wish to become a roving ambassador would have to be considered.
However, he stressed that the Queen's wishes on the issue would be paramount.
He also appeared to underline the Foreign Office's concerns about the princess
being given any formal ambassadorial position.
On Radio 4's Today programme Mr Rifkind said: ``Ambassador has a technical
meaning and a more general meaning, sometimes used of someone who helps advance
the interests of the country they belong to.
``These are issues which will be considered quite properly, taking into account
the wishes of Her Majesty the Queen. That is the single most important
consideration.''
Mr Rifkind is the first member of the Government to speak publicly about a
possible new role for the princess since she revealed her wish, in her Panorama
interiew, to be a goodwill ambassador.
Mr Major is reported to have played a crucial role in behind the scenes
negotiations between the palace and the princess.
Mr Rifkind stressed the extreme sensitivity of the negotiations saying:``I
think we are at a very delicate moment with regard to the princess's future.''
</TEXT>
