<HEADLINE>The right to roam needs new legislation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684200</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN R Holliday asks ``what happened to the legal right to roam'' when quoting
a Scottish local authority official who appeared to suggest that landowners
could compel walkers to leave their land (December 19).
Lord Sands provided the answer in 1928: ``When the presence of persons where
they have no legal right to be is expressly permitted, or permitted by
implication from tolerance, there is no trespass.''
In the same year Lord President Clyde observed: ``The word `trespasser' is apt,
in Scotland, to be a question-begging term . . . It means with us nothing more
than a person who intrudes on the land of another without that other's
permission, and it does not involve or imply the commission of any legal
offence. It is in short a popular term and not a legal one.''
From statements like these many legal experts, police officers, and
well-informed walkers have concluded that, while a landowner is perfectly
entitled to ask someone to leave their land, they cannot apply any force or
coercion if the person is simply crossing the land on a peaceful walk and
causing no damage to the landowner's interests. Otherwise the landowner is open
to a criminal charge of assault.
Nevertheless, there are many other statements, sometimes from official
organisations, or from those representing landowning interests, which suggest
that strong-arm tactics can be used to remove walkers from land. No wonder the
public is confused.
Every politician with a stake in democracy should recognise that the right to
roam is as important as the right to free speech. A commitment to legislate for
freedom to roam should be in the election manifestos of every political party
in Scotland.
Such legislation is essential if we are to continue to enjoy, with confidence,
our cultural and natural heritage whether it be on public or privately owned
land.
Dave Morris,
Scottish Officer,
The Ramblers' Association,
Crusader House, Haig Business Park,
Markinch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
