<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#40,000 for `Death on the Rock' relatives</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684201</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government has paid #40,000 in legal costs to the relatives of three IRA
members shot by the SAS in Gibraltar.
The money was paid to comply with a decision by the European Court of Human
Rights in September to award costs to the families of Mairead Farrell, Sean
Savage and Daniel McCann.
``All we are doing is complying with the court's condition that we pay legal
costs,'' a spokeswoman for the Ministry of Defence said. ``There is no question
of compensation at all.''
The payment was reported to have been made on Christmas Eve, just days from the
expiry of a three-month deadline set by the court, which had ruled that the
so-called ``Death on the Rock'' killings breached Article 2 of the Convention
of Human Rights.
The Government, which had at the time expressed ``deep dissatisfaction'' with
the judgment which it said ``defied common sense'' was keen to deny there had
been any climbdown.
``It's a legal matter in which we had no control,'' a Foreign Office spokesman
said. ``The Government is not in the position of breaking the law.''
At the time, Mr Michael Heseltine said the Government would consider
withdrawing Britain's recognition of the Convention in protest.
He was not available for comment last night, but the Cabinet Office insisted he
had never suggested the costs should not be paid.
</TEXT>
