<HEADLINE>`One-stop shop' scheme for film industry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALLAN LAING Entertainments Writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684202</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW Development Agency looks set to create an ambitious ``one-stop shop''
to service Scotland's burgeoning film industry.
It has earmarked a three-storey building in the Broomielaw which it intends to
transform into an office block to house the Scottish Film Council, the Scottish
Film Production Fund, and Bafta Scotland.
The move is seen as crucial if Glasgow is to retain its position as the
administrative centre - and natural home - of the country's film and TV
industries. The city already has Scotland's two biggest television stations,
BBC Scotland and Scottish Television, and the majority of the country's
independent film companies.
However, for some years there has been concern about the state of the Scottish
Film Council's premises. Together with the SFPF and the Scottish Film Archive,
it is housed in the ageing former Notre Dame School in Victoria Crescent Road
in Glasgow's West End. The accommodation, essentially classrooms which have
been converted into offices, is cramped and unattractive.
With more and more film-makers coming to Glasgow, the GDA has been aware that
this image does not reflect the dynamic, forward-looking industrial sector it
is supposed to be. So it has been looking around for a suitable alternative.
Having earmarked the Broomielaw site, it has now started a tendering process
for the conversion work. However, the project has still to be given the final
go-ahead by the Scottish Office. Given the Scottish Secretary's interest in the
expansion of the movie business, this is not likely to be a problem.
Senior officials at the GDA stressed that the new building would be a purely
administrative centre. The project did not preclude possible future plans for a
bigger and better centre which could house production facilities and a museum
and archive.
The only key film organisation which will not be housed in the new Glasgow
building is Scottish Screen Locations which will continue to be based in
Edinburgh.
