<HEADLINE>Not anti-Semitic</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684203</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS a former chairman of the Council of the John Buchan Society I must protest
against Jimmy Reid's association of John Buchan with anti-Semitism (December
23).
Far from being anti-Semitic, John Buchan was a friend of Chaim Weizmann and
``was regarded by British Zionists as one of their most useful allies'' (Janet
Adam Smith, John Buchan, p317).
Andrew Lownie's new book on Buchan quotes a letter to Walter Buchan condemning
Archibald Maule Ramsay's spreading of anti-Semitic propaganda in 1938: ``It is
abominable, at a time when the wretched Jews are suffering almost the cruellest
persecution in history, that Englishmen should give currency to these silly
libels, which are all invented in Germany'' (p271).
Some of Buchan's characters do express the suspicion of Jews that was current
in the first half of this century; some other characters are respected Jews;
and in The Thirty-Nine Steps Scudder's anti-Semitism is adversely commented on
by Sir Walter Bullivant thus: ``He had a lot of odd biases, too. Jews, for
example, made him see red. Jews and the high finance.''
Rev James C G Greig,
St John's Croft,
Sorbie,
Wigtownshire.
</TEXT>
