<HEADLINE>280,000 refugee Serbs starve in freezing camps</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From DAN De LUCE Banja Luka, Tuesday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684204</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL relief workers said today they were struggling to feed and
shelter tens of thousands of refugees on Bosnian Serb-held territory as winter
deepens.
Serb authorities in the western parts of the Bosnian Serb Republic are
overwhelmed by 280,000 refugees, of which 180,000 were displaced this year. Aid
workers described the north-west region around Banja Luka as ``one big refugee
camp''.
Unlike earlier stages in the Bosnian conflict, the humanitarian crisis appears
to be worse on the Serb side because of the recent influx of refugees.
``It's the most precarious time in this part of Bosnia since the war started,''
an official with the UN High Commissioner for Refugees said. ``It's similar to
the situation on the Government side in the winter of 1993.''
The International Committee of the Red Cross, responding to the deteriorating
situation, plans to set up some 20 soup kitchens serving one hot meal a day for
the most vulnerable people in the Banja Luka area.
The most pressing problem for refugees is lack of shelter amid snow and
freezing temperatures, relief workers said.
The Red Cross is handing out stoves, blankets, and mattresses to the refugees,
some of whom are sleeping in schools and army barracks.
Some of the refugees are moving into gutted houses once inhabited by Muslims
and Croats expelled earlier in the war.
Slobodan Ecimovic, Bosnian Serb deputy commissioner for refugees, said they
lacked the resources to construct housing for the displaced population.
``The conditions for refugees are difficult and could get worse,'' he said.
``There are plans to resettle them but the question is how?''
The number of refugees is expected to rise over the next months as some 17,000
Serbs in the Posavina corridor in northern Bosnia flee before the region is
handed over to the Muslim-Croat federation.
UN relief workers also fear an exodus of thousands of Serbs around Sarajevo
before their suburbs revert to Muslim-led government control.
The Serbs' international isolation has meant that far fewer international aid
agencies operate on Serb territory than on the Government side, relief workers
said.
Until October, only three major aid agencies - the UNHCR, ICRC, and the French
medical charity Medecins sans Frontieres - were working on Serb territory. More
than 100 aid groups are registered on Government-held ground.
One relief worker said: ``The Serbs have been treated as the `bad guys', and
aid agencies found it much easier to raise funds for projects on the Government
side.
``It is sometimes difficult to find support from donors for projects on
Serb-controlled territory.''
Relief workers hope a Nato-led force policing the peace accord will open up
routes through front lines next month, clearing the way for convoys coming from
UNHCR warehouses in neighbouring Croatia.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
