<HEADLINE>Shetland faces Arctic blizzards as snow storms and freezing temperatures tighten grip on North Island state of emergency</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684205</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By DAVID ROSS, Highland Correspondent, and GRAEME SMITH
SHETLAND Islands Council last night declared a state of emergency as
helicopters were drafted in to airlift aid to people in remote areas of
Scotland. They are facing a fourth day without power as a result of the severe
snow storms which have gripped the North.
There are fears of worse to come. Two more ``polar low'' depressions are
expected to sweep down from the Arctic later in the week, bringing Shetland
renewed blizzards.
Temperatures throughout Scotland are also feared to fall even lower before the
week is out. In Glasgow yesterday they hit -16C, the coldest place in Scotland
along with Aviemore, with worse to come. Edinburgh suffered a recorded low of
-6C.
Scottish Office officials have been in touch with the Shetland council offering
help.
Last night a Scottish Office spokesman said: ``We have been told that the
council is coping with the situation with their own resources. But we are ready
to give any assistance the council may think is necessary and are monitoring
the situation.''
The chief executive of Shetland Islands Council, Mr Malcolm Green, said an
emergency committee was now in operation and supervising the delivery of
services to the islanders who were ``pulling together'' making sure that
everybody was safe.
The council has set up a telephone network to pass information to islanders via
their community councils. Local numbers for people to call were broadcast on
BBC Radio Shetland, which went back on the air last night with a special snow
emergency programme.
Mr Green appealed for volunteers with four-wheel drive vehicles and tractors to
register with the council. The plan is to use them to deliver emergency
supplies of food and bottled gas to houses still completely cut off, with
isolated old people the priority.
He said the council, police, and coastguards were co-operating closely. The
council's emergency team will meet this morning for the first time since the
Braer tanker wreck almost three years ago.
Hydro-Electric linesmen have been battling since Sunday to restore power to
homes cut off as snow, ice, and heavy winds have brought down electricity lines
but they have been unable to reach many of the most isolated victims.
By last night the company, whose linesmen have been working against the
elements throughout Christmas, had managed to restore supplies to almost 19,000
homes leaving only 1500 in Shetland, the Western Isles, and a handful on the
mainland without power.
Because they live in remote areas most are prepared for periods without power
but a Hydro-Electric spokeswoman said: ``Our concern is that the gas and
paraffin which many of them use as alternative fuel will be running out.
``We have taken three extra helicopters to Shetland and four to the Western
Isles and we have offered them to the local authorities to get supplies to
those who require them or to airlift to safety those who are most vulnerable.
``We have also flown in extra helicopter pilots to Shetland to ensure there are
enough to keep the helicopters in operation.''
She said they were ``very disappointed'' that they had not been able to make
more progress yesterday. The weather had delayed the arrival of some of the
helicopters and workmen until mid-afternoon, curtailing the amount they were
able to do.
A local contractor on the island had been persuaded to dig a route in for
Hydro-Electric workers to repair the Tumlin sub station which was brought back
into operation last night, restoring power to 1100 of the 1426 Shetland homes
blacked out.
A further 770 consumers were affected in the Western Isles and emergency
generators have been taken to Uig in case power cannot be restored today.
The main problem area on the mainland is around Strichen and New Deer in
Aberdeenshire. About 170 people in Strichen have had no power since Christmas
Eve. In total around 500 Hydro-Electric workers have been mobilised over
Christmas including 100 contractors' staff called in to help.
``We are dealing with 20ft snow drifts and it is impossible to say when
everyone will have their power restored. We are working flat out,'' said the
spokeswoman.
Power cables had to be placed above ground, leaving themContinued from Page 1
vulnerable, because it would cost 10 times as much to place them below ground
and if there were faults it would take days to find them.
``It just takes one of these lines to go out. I think those who live in remote
locations know that you have to accept the risk at this time of the year. It's
not like living in a city where you can switch electricity from four
directions,'' the spokeswoman said.
Main routes in Grampian were open yesteday but police were warning motorists
only to make ``absolutely essential'' journeys.
A police spokesman said: ``If you have to make a journey it is best to check
the conditions before departing and make sure your vehicle is in perfect
condition.''
He said that although the main roads were passable many side roads were blocked
by falling and drifting snow.
He praised the teams of Grampian roadworkers who had struggled round the clock
over the festive season to keep the arterial routes clear.
Meanwhile, Shetland council offices are to close down for the next three days
except for those staff dealing with the emergency.
Most inter-island ferry services have beeen cancelled because connecting roads
are closed to general traffic and crews have been having great difficulty
getting to their boats.
Sumburgh Airport remained closed all day and is unlikely to reopen before noon
today. British Airways told passengers some flights would be cancelled and
asked intending travellers to check before leaving for the airport, where
access roads are described as ``extremely difficult''.
All but essential staff at BP's Sullom Voe oil terminal were told to stay at
home. The oil port resumed shipments late on Christmas Day when the wind
dropped below gale force but managers reported ``significant difficulties''.
The Crofters Union secretary, Mr Drew Ratter, said farmers and crofters were
becoming concerned about sheep flocks stranded where they could not be fed.
Shetland Coastguard's rescue helicopter made two more air ambulance trips
yesterday to take seriously ill patients to hospital in Lerwick from remote
rural communities.
The fishing boat Antares sailed 14 miles from the island of Whalsay to Lerwick
with a pregnant woman late yesterday afternoon. An ambulance met the boat at
Victoria Pier, Lerwick, and took her to the maternity unit of the Gilbert Bain
Hospital.
The Laerling, which normally runs summer sightseeing cruises, made a 50 mile
round voyage from Lerwick to Sumburgh to collect more than 20 airline
passengers who had been stranded at Sumburgh Hotel since landing at Sumburgh
Airport late on Christmas Eve.
One family escaped from a snowbound house on the island of Bressay by boat,
heading for Tenerife. Frank and Caroline Miller and their Christmas family
party had spent two days without power. They crossed Bressay Sound to Lerwick
in a neighbour's workboat to make sure they were in time for tonight's P &amp; O
ferry to Aberdeen.
In Kinlochbervie and Durness in north-west Sutherland, local people reported
that half the houses had been cut off.
The snow has not turned out to be the delight for skiers which many hoped.
Those who were able to reach the ski slopes found that only a few runs were in
operation.
At Glencoe the lifts remained closed because severe winds had blown much of the
snow off the runs and at Aonach Mor there were limited facilities. The Lecht
and Glenshee Ski Centres both opened after being stormbound on Christmas Day.
Cairngorm has had five chairlifts and tows open since the Monday although the
number of Christmas Day skiers was kept down as the access road was blocked by
drifting snow until midday.
AA Roadwatch last night issued the following warning: SHETLAND: All roads
closed. GRAMPIAN: A96 shut at Keith; A947 south of Turriff; A93 Aboyne-Braemar
closed; A939 Tomintoul-Granton-on-Spey passable with extreme care; A90
Aberdeen-Dundee passable with care. TAYSIDE: A90 Aberdeen-Forfar passable with
care, but down to one lane northbound; A92 Montrose-Stonehaven very icy, police
advise using A90. CENTRAL: A821 Callander-Aberfoyle closed at Dukes Pass.
BORDERS: A1 and A697 treacherous. STRATHCLYDE: A83 icy at Rest-and-be-Thankful;
Shields Road, Motherwell, ice caused by burst pipe.
</TEXT>
