<HEADLINE>Now US acts to clean up sleaze</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Patrick Brogan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684206</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Patrick Brogan reports on how Congress moves to expose dirty secrets
THE sleaze that has been flowing through the House of Commons in an
ever-increasing flood has been yet richer and deeper in Washington. Now
Congress, like Parliament, is making a first effort to clean itself up.
Not too much, though. Lobbyists are to be brought out into the open, their
dirty little secrets are to be published to the world, but the greater
corruption, the payment of huge sums of money to members of both Houses of
Congress for their electoral purposes, will continue unchecked.
House and Senate have both amended the rules governing gifts to members. They
will no longer be able to charge their vacations to lobbyists, so-called
``charity'' golf and ski trips will now be out-of-bounds if someone else is
paying, and members will not be able to accept gifts costing more than $50, or
allow lobbyists to spend more than that on a meal or drinks for legislators.
The same limitations apply to congressional staffs, which will suddenly make
their jobs much less attractive. It should also make the legislative process
slightly less corrupt: while it may not often have been possible to buy a
Congressman's or a Senator's vote with a ski trip or a good lunch, lobbyists
certainly found it possible to influence the opinions of obscure and unknown
members of their staffs with a campaign of small favours.
A much more important change finally made it through the House of
Representatives on November 29. The House then passed a Bill that had already
passed the Senate, which will oblige all lobbyists to declare themselves and
their operations. President Clinton will sign it and from next January, a new
light should start to shine in the dark places of Washington.
Current law provides that lobbyists need declare only their approaches to
members of Congress. The new law covers everyone who seeks to influence
Congressional staff, policy-making officials of the executive branch, including
the President himself and members of the Cabinet and all the other agencies of
government.
Lobbyists would have to register themselves with Congress within 45 days of
being hired or making their first contact with an official.
Lobbyists will have to file reports to Congress every six months, and here's
the juicy bit. They have to disclose what legislation or matters of policy they
were trying to influence, and how much they spend on each subject.
They have to list which Houses of Congress and which agency of the government
they approached, but they do not have to list the names of the individuals.
The passage of the Bill was a victory for reform Democrats and Republicans, and
was possible solely because of the zeal of new Republican Congressmen who came
to Washington a year ago, promising to reform Congress. Their efforts were
opposed by Republican leaders in both houses, who were quite happy to accept
lobbyists' help.
Newt Gingrich, for instance, invited lobbyists into his office immediately
after he moved in as Speaker last January, to help draft Bills.
He objected to anything which might interfere with this cosy relationship,
sending his deputies out to vote for various killer amendments. All were
defeated, however, and in the end, faced with the stark choice of voting for
reform, or opposing it, the Bill passed unanimously.
In some ways, Washington is already cleaner than London: unlike Members of
Parliament, Members of Congress are forbidden to accept salaries from lobbying
organisations.
But the sleaze factor has not been eliminated. It is still possible to buy
Congressmen. Indeed, the influence of crude money is likely to be increased.
Lobbyists will now hesitate to spend huge amounts of time and effort presenting
their cases to Congressmen or their staffs, or to government agencies, for fear
that their opponents will give great publicity to their activities. Instead,
they will simply send money to the Political Action Committees (PACs) that
finance members' election campaigns.
The connection between money, elections and policy is far more direct and
corrupt here than in London. There are no limits on what members can spend on
their election campaigns, and the limits on how they can raise the money are
easily circumvented.
Indeed, the rule that no individual can give more than $1000 to a Congressional
candidate's campaign helps the PACs, which pour their money into different
coffers - which perform the same service. There is no restriction of ``soft
money'' contributions, by which a PAC may finance a series of TV commercials
supporting their favoured candidates.
</TEXT>
