<HEADLINE>Injured Superman aids spinal charity</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684207</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SUPERMAN star Christopher Reeve, who was paralysed after a riding accident in
May, is to be the patron of a charity wheelchair push from Land's End to John
O'Groats.
Reeve, 42, is hoping to travel from the US for the Push 2000 event, which will
involve three men travelling 2000 miles in racing wheelchairs over two months.
His visit will mark the tenth anniversary of the Great British Push which
raised #400,000 over a similar route for the International Spinal Research
Trust.
Paraplegic Simon Barnes, 32, and two friends will set out from Land's End on
May 13, visiting spinal units at several hospitals on route.
Reeve, who is wheelchair-bound and depends on a ventilator to breathe, has
expressed an ambition to be on his feet again within 10 years.
He met Mr Bengie Walden, ISRT's director, and Mr Barnes at the Kessler
Institute in New Jersey, where he was a patient.
``We are hoping Push 2000 will raise #500,000 towards the #6m we need for our
research programme,'' said Mr Walden.
``Mr Reeve has an incredibly strong spirit,'' said Mr Barnes. ``If anyone is
going to help end the permanence of paralysis, Christopher Reeve is the man.''
The charity recently funded the work of a Swedish orthopaedic surgeon, Thomas
Carlstedt, who operated on a patient suffering from spinal-cord injury to give
him back the use of a paralysed arm.
</TEXT>
