<HEADLINE>TUC says pensions lack social reality</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684208</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL adult dependants of public-sector workers deserve pension entitlements,
regardless of their marital status, the Trades Union Congress said yesterday in
calling for changes to the existing law.
In a report entitled Pensions and Prejudice, the TUC says almost 220,000
families are disadvantaged by the present pension scheme.
Of the three million public-sector workers paying into pension schemes, nearly
220,000 are unmarried partners, many with children, who stand to face financial
hardship when their partner dies.
The TUC report also identifies discrimination against lesbians, homosexuals,
and people who live with parents or other relatives.
General secretary John Monks said yesterday: ``The social taboos of living
together no longer apply and the pension schemes are out of touch with social
realities. Unless the schemes change their ways people will not join them,
which is not good for our members or for the future of the schemes.''
Some schemes, including the Royal Devonport Dockyard Scheme, have already
adapted to take account of these developments. That scheme stipulates that in
the event of death ``a pension shall be paid to an adult dependant of the
member of one half of the amount of pension that would have been payable to the
member''.
The TUC wants all public-sector pension schemes - namely those covering local
government and NHS staff, civil servants, police, and firefighters - to follow
suit, but the Government refuses to act on moral, cost, and logistical grounds,
all of which the TUC rebuts.
</TEXT>
