<HEADLINE>Turkey's political parties close ranks against Islamists</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From ALISTAIR BELL Ankara, Tuesday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684209</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TURKEY'S often fractious secularist politicians closed ranks today in a bid to
prevent the Islamist Welfare Party (RP) from coming to power after it narrowly
won general elections at the weekend.
Prime Minister Tansu Ciller and rival conservative leader Mesut Yilmaz agreed
to work for a coalition supported by left-wing MPs to block the RP.
``I have said we would welcome a coalition with (the Motherland Party) Anap and
I repeat that,'' Ciller said. ``Our aim is to go towards a wide-based
government,'' she told a joint news conference after meeting Yilmaz, the Anap
leader.
Shares on Istanbul's stock exchange surged by an average 5.3% on the news that
Ciller and Yilmaz were meeting.
The anti-Western Islamists won just over 21% of Sunday's votes but do not have
enough seats to govern alone. Anap and Ciller's right-wing True Path Party
(DYP) were close behind with almost 40% of the vote between them.
Welfare's victory was the first at general polls by an Islamist party in 99%
Muslim but secular Turkey's 72 years as a modern republic.
The party has ridden a wave of discontent at Ciller's tough economic austerity
plan and bickering among the mainstream parties.
Turkey's business community and media have long called for a conservative
coalition to deal with economic ills like 80% annual inflation and a stumbling
privatisation plan.
Yilmaz said he hoped an alliance could be forged in the coming days.
Right-wing unity has failed in the past because of intense personal rivalry
between Ciller and Yilmaz. An attempt to ally their two parties in September
ended when Yilmaz stormed out of a meeting with the prime minister, accusing
her of disrespect.
Veteran Welfare leader Necmettin Erbakan, a fiery public speaker, toned down
his anti-establishment rhetoric today.
``We can form a coalition government with any of the other parties,'' he told a
news conference. ``Coalition means compromise.''
Ciller and Yilmaz have vowed not to go into government with Welfare. Erbakan
also said he had no desire to change Turkey's strict secularist constitution
and wanted to concentrate on solving inlfation, unemployment and the Kurdish
issue.
``Our nation is waiting for service. There is a need for co-operation and being
constructive,'' he said.
Erbakan said he hoped President Suleyman Demirel would give him the task of
forming a coalition, in line with Turkish political tradition under which the
biggest party in a split parliament gets the first bite at forming a governing
alliance.
The secularist bid to block Erbakan also has the support of the left-wing
Democratic Left Party (DSP) and Ciller's former social democrat coalition
partners.
But it was unclear if the left would join a coalition or support it against the
Islamists from the opposition benches.
The DSP's staunch secularist leader Bulent Ecevit said he would back a strong
government. ``We evaluated how such a government could be formed and how we
could contribute to it,'' he said after meeting Yilmaz.
Former prime minister Ecevit, a 1970s-style leftist, has frequently criticised
US-educated Ciller for her privatisation drive and free-marketeering.
Ciller called early elections after her coalition with the social democrats
collapsed in September and she lost a vote of confidence in the minority
government that replaced it.
She resigned as prime minister after her defeat on Sunday but Demirel asked her
to stay on in a caretaker role under a new government is set up.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
