<HEADLINE>Fresh South African unrest claims 15 lives</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Durban, Tuesday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684210</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIFTEEN people were killed in two separate attacks in South Africa's volatile
KwaZulu-Natal province today, police said.
Police spokesman Henry Budrum told Reuters that 10 people were killed during a
tribal dispute between two Zulu clans in the rural areas of the province called
Ngoba before dawn.
He said five other people, three children and two adults, were shot and burnt
to death at Inkonka settlements.
``We are not certain if this attack was politically linked, but we are
investigating that possibility,'' he said.
Budrum said the pre-dawn clash between the Hlongwane and Khumalo clans was not
politically motivated.
``That area has a history of faction fighting and this recent clash is linked
to an old tribal dispute and not to politics,'' he said.
KwaZulu-Natal is a scene of bitter internecine fighting between President
Nelson Mandela's ruling African National Congress and Chief Mangosuthu
Buthelezi's Inkatha Freedom Party.
The province also has a history of faction fighting where rival clans fight for
anything from grazing space to boreholes.
There has been an upsurge in violence between ANC and IFP supporters this month
although political fighting between followers of Mandela and Buthelezi has
eased since all-race elections in April last year.
Thirty-six people have been killed in three separate attacks on IFP and ANC
supporters in KwaZulu-Natal this month, including 16 massacred on Christmas Day
in Shobashobane district outside Port Shepstone, 90 miles south of the port
city of Durban.
The ANC and Inkatha today blamed each other for the upsurge in bloodletting.
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki visited looted, deserted huts in Shobashobane
villages today.
Mbeki, along with Defence Minister Joe Modise and Safety and Security Minister
Sydney Mufamadi, did not speak to reporters when they arrived to inspect the
charred belongings and looted houses of ANC supporters at Shobashobane.
ANC's KwaZulu-Natal provincial spokesman Dumisani Makhaye blamed Inkatha for
the latest massacre.
``This is part of the programme of the Inkatha to wipe out the ANC from the
province,'' Makhaye said.
But Inkatha spokesman Phillip Powell denied Makhaye's allegations, saying it
was in fact Inkatha members who had been ``subjected to a wave of killing in
the past three months''.
``Instead of engaging in rhetoric, there should be serious attempts to resolve
the problem in that area,'' Powell said.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
