<HEADLINE>Vandal leaves bakery owner evidence to chew over</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684211</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A VANDAL head-butted a bakery window with such force his false teeth flew out
his mouth and landed in the shop.
Braes Bakery owner Scott Robertson was left gnashing his own teeth when he
turned up for work in Grangemouth yesterday morning to find his shop window
shattered.
However, he was left with a smile on his face and one in his hand when he
picked up the vandal's dentures he had found lying on the shop floor.
Mr Robertson, 35, does not think police will have too much of a problem
matching the false teeth with the suspect.
He said: ``When I saw the broken window I was furious because it will cost me a
fair amount of money to get it fixed.
``But when I realised whoever had smashed the window had left their teeth, I
just burst out laughing.
``I had heard the saying `An eye for an eye, and a tooth for a tooth' but this
really takes the biscuit.
``If he comes back into the shop he won't be too hard to spot.
``Once he has paid for my window I will give him back the teeth.''
</TEXT>
