<HEADLINE>Troops and civilians die in Zairean refugee town</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From MATTHEW TOSTEVIN Kinshasa, Tuesday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684212</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UP to six Zairean soldiers and an unknown number of civilians died in Christmas
Day violence in Zaire's refugee town of Goma after attackers killed a colonel,
triggering a rampage by troops, witnesses and aid workers said.
The identity of those behind yesterday's grenade attack, which sparked clashes
and looting away from the town centre, was not immediately clear and it was
unclear whether any of the hundreds of thousands of Rwandan refugees in the
area were involved.
Regional governor Moto Mpenda told Reuters by telephone today that calm had
return to the town.
Details of what happened were sketchy. Aid workers spoke of clashes among
soldiers with civilians caught up in the unrest.
A journalist of the Zaire Press Agency told Reuters by telephone yesterday that
the dead lieutenant colonel was second in command of operations in the area.
The attacker died in the blast from his own grenade and two men with him were
caught and killed by bystanders, he said.
Aid workers said soldiers had then gone on the rampage.
Goma was the focus of the exodus of over a million Rwandan Hutus after the
Tutsi-dominated Rwanda Patriotic Front exiles defeated the Hutu army and took
power after last year's massacre of up to one million Rwandans, most of them
Tutsis.
The Kinshasa government, under pressure from Zaire's President Mobutu Sese
Seko, has dropped plans to expel the refugees by the end of the year. It had
earlier suspended forced repatriations under pressure from the outside
world.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
