<HEADLINE>Rifkind tries to play down currency fears</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684215</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN Secretary Malcolm Rifkind yesterday attempted to allay the fears of
Tory Euro-sceptics on a single European currency, but played down the prospects
of a referendum.
He said Britain would have to be convinced there would be ``very substantial
benefits'' before signing up to a single currency.
Some MPs were alarmed by the pace of moves towards monetary union agreed by EU
heads of government at the Madrid summit earlier this month.
Mr Rifkind stressed that Britain was unconvinced by the political arguments.
``Joining a single currency would be a historic decision. It would be an
irreversible decision. It would involve the transfer of significant control
over economic decision making to the European level,'' he told BBC Radio 4's
Today. ``To justify that one would have to be satisfied there would be very
substantial benefits to the British economy.''
On the issue of a referendum being included in the Tory election manifesto, he
said: ``In theory it could but it doesn't have to. In the past when there have
been referenda over our membership of the EC or devolution those were issues
that were decided at the time.''
</TEXT>
