<HEADLINE>Labour chiefs dismiss reports of party rethink on devolution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684216</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SENIOR Labour Party sources yesterday dismissed reports that Tony Blair was
planning a new commission to examine key aspects of devolution.
It has been claimed that the Labour leader wants a ``high-powered internal
review'' of the impact of devolution on English politics.
It was also that claimed the review commission would re-examine the so-called
West Lothian question, which centres on the right of Scottish MPs to vote on
issues affecting England and Wales after devolution.
Last night, however, the Labour hierarchy was adamant that there was no
substance to the newspaper reports.
The Shadow Scottish Secretary, Mr George Robertson, said: ``There is nothing in
it as far as we are concerned. There is ongoing preparation for fulfilment of
our pledge, but there is no commission set up, or being set up.''
It was claimed that the alleged review might examine the consequences of
reducing the number of Scottish MPs at Westminster from the present 72 to
perhaps 58.
Some Scottish Labour MPs have privately acknowledged that there could be
pressure for this after the first term of a Labour government, when the
Scottish parliament would have been up and running for some years.
However, Mr Robertson made it clear that any such change would be well into the
future that the party's policy was the retention of all 72 MPs.
A senior spokesman for Mr Blair's office said the commitment to legislation in
the first year was ``absolute'' and he added: ``The idea that ongoing
discussions represent a new commission of inquiry is absurd. There are
discussions all the time, but there is no new commission.''
The Tories are preparing to make Labour's devolution plans a centrepiece of
their campaign in the next General Election.
The Prime Minister believes his stance on the issue was a vote-winner last time
and can be again.
A particular target will be the so-called ``tartan tax'' which, the Tories
claim, will cost the average Scot an extra 3p in the pound.
Mr Major has said devolution would mean that the future status and number of
Scotland's MPs at Westminster would inevitably be diminished.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth went on the attack during a recent session
of the Scottish Select Committee. He strongly defended the spending deal he
achieved for Scotland and told English Tory MPs on the committee: ``There are
people who advocate the tartan tax because it may not be raised, or taxation
might be reduced.
``But I find the idea that you would continue to vote through 35% more funds
and then watch a Scottish parliament hand out tax rebates incredible. Those who
advocate change should recognise what they are opening up.''
Meanwhile, Hartlepool Labour MP Peter Mandelson is about to open a can of worms
by setting out of his own ``manifesto'' in a book to be published in the new
year.
According to reports over Christmas, it includes a coalition with the Liberal
Democrats, abolition of child benefit, no-strike deals in the public sector
and, following devolution, a reduction in the number of Scottish and Welsh MPs
at Westminster.
One angered left winger is quoted as saying: ``If he wants to have some
coalition with the Lib-Dems, I suggest he does us all a favour and joins them.''
</TEXT>
