<HEADLINE>Police chief tells clergy they must make clear they reject decriminalisation of cannabis Churches urged to tackle drugs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER REEKIE and ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684217</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR police officer, heavily involved in the Strathclyde force's anti-drugs
initiative Operation Eagle, has called on churches to play a leading role in
tackling drug abuse.
Mr James Richardson, Deputy Chief Constable of Strathclyde, also took a strong
stand against legalising so-called ``soft'' drugs such as cannabis.
He said that on a visit to Amsterdam he walked into the city-centre and saw the
results of a liberal regime in relation to immorality, drug abuse, and crime.
``Let me tell you that there was nothing there I would want to bring to
Strathclyde,'' said Mr Richardson, an elder at St Machan's Parish Church at
Larkhall.
He said the police would never cure the drug problem because it was not their
role and he called on other agencies including the churches to work at reducing
demand and diverting people away from using drugs.
When asked what he made of the Church of Scotland's board of social
responsibility which is currently examining the issue of decriminalising
certain ``soft drugs'' such as cannabis, Mr Richardson said: ``Christians
cannot possibly have an option to suggest that dangerous drugs should be
decriminalised.
``There is no such thing as a `soft' drug. All drugs by their very nature are
mind-altering or mood-altering.
``As such they are a form of escapism, quite apart from the physical and
psychological harm that they bring.
``There is no question here. Can we honestly answer to our maker for condoning
a society where drug abuse is legalised?''
Mr Richardson's comments were made in an interview in January's edition of the
Church of Scotland magazine, Life and Work.
Mr Richardson said: ``We have a responsibility to the generations yet to come
to set standards which promote a healthy society.
``The evidence is ample to show that people progress from soft drugs to hard
drugs.
``Dealers are deliberately engaged in supplying substances which they know are
harmful, but there are tremendous profits to be made here so they encourage
young people to experiment.''
Mr Richardson said that people who took dangerous drugs were trying to change
their psychological state, often because of a lack of confidence in themselves,
peer-group pressures, or hopelessness, but the churches could show these people
their own value.
``The church can help drug users by nurturing skills and developing potential.
It should use diversion techniques to give drug users alternative options, and
it should have an uncompromising teaching element which values the Gospel and
which values people.
``Parish churches could have a huge role, and there is an amazing mission
potential in this field, but we must have the faith to make it happen.''
Asked what level of success he realistically expected against drug dealers, Mr
Richardson said he was an optimist and said he thought ``if we have the faith,
the will, the resilience, and the determination, we can win the battle''.
Last night Mrs Ann Allen, vice convener of the board of social responsibility,
said she believed the majority of people in the church would agree with his
comments.
The Rev Fergus Buchanan, convener of the Kirk's 16-strong study group into
whether certain illegal substances should be decriminalised, will head a
meeting early in the new year with a view to reporting to the General Assembly
in 1997.
One of the main topics of discussion will be whether cannabis should be
legalised, either as a recreational or a therapeutic drug.
</TEXT>
