<HEADLINE>Hair-raising statistics for those beset by accident</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684218</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAIRDRESSERS and barbers have the highest mortality rates in Britain, followed
by men who work on boats.
Footballers who drive black cars are also more accident prone than average,
according to a report by a men's magazine, Maxim.
Football accounts for 440,000 injuries a year, and rugby 97,000.
Based on figures covering accidents, crimes, and injuries, the magazine found
that the living-room was the most accident-prone place in the home with some
257,000 reported mishaps there each year.
Black cars were more likely to crash than any other colour of car, with 5pm the
worst time for road accidents.
Oddly enough five people are injured by goats each year, while in the office
4000 people a year are hurt by stationery including four a year by paper clips.
Two people a year suffer damage from putty, four from shoe polish, six from
lollipop sticks, eight from toothpaste, and 10 from underwear.
At home 54,000 people suffer poisoning and 25,000 from ``over-exertion''.
A Maxim spokesman said: ``What exactly they were doing, the statistics don't
say.''
</TEXT>
