<HEADLINE>Town's old jail to become visitor centre and offices</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684220</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DERELICT 148-year-old jail is being transformed into an office block and
tourist attraction at a cost of #2.7m.
Stirling Old Town Jail is part of the town's relaunch as a visitor destination,
a key element of the #100m Stirling Initiative.
Three floors of prison cells have been converted to 4615sq ft of office space.
To guarantee elbow room, two cells are being converted into one office in each
case.
The ground floor is being retained as a visitor centre, complete with furnished
cells, model figures, and exhibitions, plus actors dressed as warders and
prisoners to tell the grim story of the nineteenth century jail.
It will open in March, but The Herald has had exclusive access to the project,
which includes spectacular views of the town from the prison's roof.
The prison opened in 1847, replacing the over-crowded and disease-ridden
Tolbooth Jail. It was taken over by the military authorities at Stirling Castle
from 1888 to 1935, then became a defence training centre, followed by a sweet
factory.
It closed in 1975, and was bought 10 years ago by Stirling District Council.
Funding for the refurbishment has come from the EU and Forth Valley Enterprise.
The Stirling Initiative is a partnership of seven public agencies which aims to
attract #100m of public and private investment into the town over 10 years.
It is almost half way there after two years, with #49.8m worth of investment
secured. To date, most of the money has come from the public purse, but a
spokesman for Forth Valley Enterprise predicted: ``Between now and the turn of
the century there will be a big increase in private sector investment.''
The forecast is based on increased confidence as developments gather speed.
Spending so far has been concentrated on three main areas - infrastructure,
environmental improvements, and the restoration of historic buildings.
Some road schemes have been the subject of criticism, as have plans for the
commercial development of the Forthside area.
Ian Wilson
</TEXT>
