<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kirk risks decline to status of a sect in twenty-first century, says retired minister</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Christopher Reekie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684221</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Church of Scotland must rediscover its identity, clarify its beliefs, and
proclaim the message of salvation if it is to survive into the next century, a
retired minister has said, writes Christopher Reekie.
The Rev Ivor Gibson is the former minister of Abercorn and Dalmeny, South
Queensferry, and now lives in Markinch, Fife. In an article in the January
issue of Life and Work, the Church of Scotland magazine, Mr Gibson says the
Kirk must reaffirm its faith in relation to other Christian denominations.
``The Church of Scotland has lost its identity, its liturgy, its discipline,
its spirituality, its distinctive character, and is almost unrecognisable as a
Reformed church,'' Mr Gibson says.
``Many people today do not know what the church stands for, what it believes
and where it is going.
``There is an appalling ignorance of the Christian message thanks largely to
the failure of religious education in schools, the collapse of Sunday school,
and the lack of church-going.
``If the Kirk goes under, it will not re-emerge, phoenix-like, in the next
century as part of an existing new universal church, but will survive only as a
small sect along with other Christian sects.''
Unless the Kirk clarifies its theology, Mr Gibson says it will ``drift like a
rudderless raft on a sea of uncertainty and will fail to leaven society''.
Mr Gibson says the Kirk's problem today is that, having lost sight of its
Reformed character and its centre ground, it has split down the middle into two
opposing wings, the liberals and the fundamentalists.
The great need of the Church of Scotland today was to restate its faith in the
Trinitarian doctrines of Reformed and traditional Christianity and to reclaim
the centre ground of theology.
Regarding other Christian denominations, Mr Gibson says: ``Let us co-operate on
common issues but go our separate ways on matters of principle.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Father of missing French hitch-hiker arrives in Britain to appeal for help</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684222</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE father of a missing French teenager arrived in Britain yesterday and
appealed for information to find his daughter.
Celine Figard's father, Bernard, will attend a news conference with police
today as detectives launch a full-scale murder hunt based in Southampton for
the 19-year-old accountancy student, missing for a week.
A Home Office computerised inquiry system is being used to co-ordinate the
search across Hampshire, Wiltshire, and the Thames Valley.
Miss Figard was last seen accepting a lift from a lorry driver at a motorway
service station near Newbury, Berkshire, last Tuesday.
Detectives yesterday said they were working on the ``worst-case scenario'' that
she had been murdered. The number of officers involved in the inquiry has been
doubled to more than 100.
A French-speaking police officer has been drafted in to the incident room as an
interpreter.
The policeman leading the hunt, Detective Superintendent Des Thomas, said he
was gravely concerned for Miss Figard's safety.
He said: ``Celine's father has given us as much information as possible to
build up a full background.''
Mrs Figard was too ill to travel and has stayed at the family home in
Ferrieres-Les-Scey, near Chalons-sur-Marne, Franche Compte, in Central France,
while Mr Figard, a farmer, travelled to England with other relatives.
Miss Figard had planned to spend Christmas with a cousin, Jean-Marc Figard, 24,
at the Ashburn hotel in the New Forest, Hampshire, where she worked as a
waitress last summer.
She had been unable to travel by coach because of the public-sector strikes in
France and had been given lifts by French lorry drivers to Newbury.
An English lorry driver had offered her a ride to Salisbury, Wiltshire, and had
said that she could use his mobile phone in his cab.
But nothing has been seen or heard of the teenager since.
Later detectives said they could not rule out a possible link with the
disappearance of a 23-year-old hitch-hiker 30 miles away from the service area
where Miss Figard was last seen.
Finnish-born Eila Karjalainen's naked body was found off the A34 at Woodstock
12 years ago.
She was found on the Blenheim Estate four months after her disappearance in
August 1983. She had been strangled.
She had been on the final stage of a touring holiday across Europe.
Detectives said at the time that she had probably been abducted as she was
hitch-hiking to Wales. Her rucksack and passport was found at a lay-by on the
A40 in Oxfordshire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mobile phones banned by restaurateur</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684223</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BUSINESSMAN has turned his restaurants into no-go areas for mobile phones.
Diners at the Piccolo Mondo Restaurant, Renfrew, and La Toscanella, Paisley,
are being asked to leave their mobile phones at reception.
If they do receive an urgent call a member of staff will alert them and ask
them to receive it outside the dining area.
Restaurateur Ian Bruce said: ``We fully accept that mobile phones are now a
part of everyday life, but they can be a nuisance.
``We pride ourselves on our food and on our atmosphere and some clients are
clearly disturbed by others conducting phone calls from the next table.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police caution toll protesters</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974684224</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Police caution
toll protesters
NINE drivers were cautioned for avoiding paying tolls yesterday during a
protest at the #25m Skye bridge. Pipers were in attendance and around 50
people, many carrying banners, took part in the demonstration held by the
pressure-group Skye and Kyle Against Tolls.
The group claims that the prices are the highest on any toll bridge in Europe.
Police issued cautions and a spokesman for the Skye Bridge Company said that
the demonstration passed off peacefully.
Snowball attack
A GANG of youths attacked a motorist who stopped to remonstrate with them for
throwing snowballs at his car at about 11pm on Christmas Day in Tulloch Road,
Perth. The group of nine teenagers, made up of boys and girls, then smashed his
car windscreen before running off. Tayside Police appealed for witnesses.
It can be done
SMOKERS have been told they really can give up the habit in an advertising
campaign launched yesterday. The #13.5m television campaign, produced by the
Health Education Authority, has been timed to coincide with New Year, the
traditional time to pledge to stop smoking. The advertisements, whose slogan is
Break Free, feature former smokers enjoying life and saying how they coped with
they problems of giving up.
Pets' choice fare
A SUPERSTORE is planning cordon bleu cookery for family pets. Asda has already
launched a turkey Christmas dinner for dogs. Now company chiefs are lining up a
new range of meals, including spaghetti bolognese for dogs and fish in white
sauce for cats.
Freezer deal
A COMPANY has signed a contract to ship freezers to freezing Moscow.
Birmingham-based Fridgeland landed the #45,000 deal to supply the ice-bound
Russian capital's first British-style superstore.
Vanishing act
WHILE a magician entertained police at their #25-a-head Christmas dinner dance,
thieves did a disappearing act with #4000 in takings. Officers discovered the
theft at the annual dance at Chigwell Police Club, Essex, and had to report the
crime to their own CID. Now ``Crisco'', the Isle of Wight-based conjurer, has
offered to do a benefit show to raise money for the officers.
Haldane hurt
PHOTOGRAPHER Roderick Haldane, 83, was recovering in hospital last night
following surgery on a fractured knee, damaged when he fell near his Edinburgh
home at the weekend. Haldane, famous for his award-winning photographs of the
Queen Mother, Sir Noel Coward, Charlie Chaplin and Marlene Dietrich, was on his
way to a lunch-time party when the accident happened in Great King Street. Last
night a member of his staff said: ``He is comfortable but rather bored and
upset to have missed all the Christmas parties.''
</TEXT>
