<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wreck in oilfield keeps her secrets</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684226</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS the Atlantic waters to the west of Shetland begin to disclose the secrets of
the oil wealth which lies below them, another mystery has emerged.
The development of the Foinaven field has revealed a vessel lying in 400 metres
of water which, four years after being spotted, has not yet been identified.
The shipwreck is believed to be a vessel which was bombed or torpedoed during
the Second World War. She lies just outside the anchor pattern for the field's
floating production, storage, and offloading vessel which is due on location in
the spring.
The 100 metre-long wreck was found during a sonar survey of the seabed.
As the Foinaven plan was developed further surveys were carried out to
determine whether the shipwreck might interfere with the routes of flowlines
which bring the oil to the surface.
A video survey of the ship was carried out three months ago and although it
showed the ship in detail it provided no clues to her identity.
It particularly interested Shetlander Les Thomson, who is Foinaven operations
manager and owns a painting of a similar vessel.
The wreck is likely to have been a coal burning merchant steamer of between
3000 and 4000 tonnes and with two cargo holds fore and aft.
Her funnel has vanished as has most of her timber deck.
However, despite being encrusted with marine growth, the sub-sea video clearly
shows a gun mounted at the rear of the vessel.
Small tracked vehicles are also visible on the remains of the forward deck but
experts say they are too small to be tanks.
A large hole in the side of the ship at the rear suggests a possible cause for
her sinking but extensive inquiries by BP have failed to shed any light on the
vessel's history.
The lack of a name of the vessel is not unusual because during the war vessels
painted out identification.
One theory which has been suggested to BP is that the vessel was on one of the
Murmansk convoys to Russia, many of which were routed round the North of
Scotland and fell victim to enemy fire.
</TEXT>
