<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#2m directed to learning projects</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684227</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN AWARD of more than #2m has been made for 22 research and development
projects by the Scottish Higher Education Funding Council as part of its
funding initiatives programme.
The announcement of the award will be made today by Heriot-Watt University,
Edinburgh, which is involved in the projects. A spokeswoman said the projects
would be run in conjunction with other Scottish universities and higher
education institutions.
A key project was a #900,000 three-year scheme to train academic staff
throughout Scotland in how to use the Metropolitan Area Network system to
improve their teaching and learning skills.
The ``Talisman'' project, which would be based at the learning technology
centre at Heriot-Watt's Riccarton campus in Edinburgh, would provide training
courses throughout Scotland.
Dr Roger Rist, the learning technology centre director, said: ``This funding
demonstrates the recognition of our position at the heart of teaching and
learning developments using network technology.
``Talisman will help academic staff throughout Scotland to make the best use of
the MAN network for teaching, learning, and research, and in turn their
students will benefit from new methods of learning and access to information
resources.''
Professor Robin Knops, special adviser to the Principal at Heriot-Watt, said:
``We are delighted that so many of our research and development proposals have
been approved against seemingly strong competition.''
</TEXT>
