<DOCNO>GH951227-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Safety concerns prompt RAC to support European time Bill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684228</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE RAC is the latest organisation to support a move to put Britain on European
time, arguing that an extra hour of daylight in the evenings would cut
rush-hour congestion and accidents.
The motoring group added its voice yesterday to a call for change which has
found few allies in Scotland. The RAC claimed that an extra hour of daylight in
the late afternoon would encourage more people to walk or use bicycles for
short journeys. It also claimed that lighter evenings would also mean more
children walking home from school rather than being given lifts.
The RAC is joining the British Tourist Authority, the CBI, and the Police
Federation south of the Border in supporting the controversial private Bill put
forward by the Tory MP for Bournemouth West, Mr John Butterfill.
He wants to see British clocks set to European time resulting in lighter
evenings but darker mornings during the winter, particularly in the North of
Scotland.
The MP has argued that more road accidents occur in the evening and that a
change to European time would mean 660 fewer accidents and an extra #1000m for
tourism.
A number of Scots MPs including Liberal Democrat MP for North-east Fife Menzies
Campbell, Labour's George Robertson, and the Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth, have already expressed their opposition to the Bill. But others,
including Labour's George Foulkes, say they will vote in favour of the Bill.
Last night the president of the National Farmers Union of Scotland, Mr John
Ross, said the organisation had already expressed its opposition to Scottish
MPs. ``Our position has always been to resist this change because, especially
in the North of Scotland, it would mean that outside stock cannot be tended to
until very late.''
He said the creation of one time zone across Europe would mean the UK belonged
to the biggest time zone in the world and added that farmers were extremely
unhappy with the proposal.
But the RAC's head of campaigns, Mr Edmund King, said: ``There are clear road
safety benefits to be gained from longer winter afternoons and tackling the
crucial darkness danger zone at the end of the school day should be paramount
in the minds of MPs considering the Bill.''
</TEXT>
