<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shotgun permits exceed 100,000</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684229</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR's Scottish home affairs spokesman, Mr John McFall, yesterday called for
tighter legislation covering the possession of firearms.
His demand followed the release of Government figures which showed a steady
rise in the number of certificates issued for handguns and shotguns.
Mr McFall said the number of permits in Scotland now exceeded 100,000, and
claimed that the statistics suggested a reversal of the decline in demand for
guns which had followed the implementation of the Firearms (Amendment) Act in
1988.
The number of applications for a new firearm certificate rose last year to
2005, up from 1783 in 1993, while the correponding figure for shotguns was
3653, an increase of more than 700 on the previous year.
Mr McFall said: ``The laws governing the control of shotguns should be brought
into line with those governing other firearms. At present, a person possessing
a firearms certificate may purchase an additional firearm only with the
authority of a chief constable.
``However, someone who holds a shotgun certificate can acquire any number of
shotguns without further permission. This situation should be changed.''
Last year, Scottish police forces recorded 1778 offences in which a firearm was
used, with the number involving a pistol or revolver up by 47%.
``The use of guns in the pursuit of criminal activities is obviously much more
common now than it was 20 years ago, and the more guns that are in circulation,
the more likely it is that something will fall into the wrong hands,'' said Mr
McFall.
</TEXT>
