<DOCNO>GH951227-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>As more travellers flock to Edinburgh and Glasgow, an old prison aims to captivate a new clientele Cities thrive in tourism's big league</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Table not available</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684230</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH and Glasgow have maintained their positions as Britain's top tourist
destinations outside London with overseas visitors.
A report by the British Tourist Authority and English Tourist Board shows
London topped the group this year with 11.46 million ``staying visits''.
Edinburgh had 970,000 while Glasgow, with 500,000, beat top English cities such
as Oxford, Bath, and York.
Inverness came tenth ahead of traditional holiday spots such as Brighton,
Canterbury, and Stratford-upon-Avon.
Mr Roger Carter, chief executive of Edinburgh Tourist Board, said: ``The large
increase in visitors to the city reflects its continuing investment in
improving tourism facilities and services.''
The board believes that confirmation by the United Nations of the capital's
World Heritage Status will attract even more visitors in future.
In Glasgow, tourist officials believe the city's Festival of Visual Arts 1996
will generate an additional 385,000 visitors and generate an additional #10m
for the economy.
Mr Jack Munro, chief executive of Greater Glasgow Tourist Board and Convention
Bureau, put the city's continued success down to sustained targeted marketing
coupled with a heavy programme of product development.
He said: ``A programme of major international events has been a key factor in
establishing Glasgow as a major European cultural destination.''
Mr Alistair Macpherson, tourism director for Inverness, Loch Ness, and Nairn
Tourist Board, said: ``As the capital of the Highlands, Inverness has always
been a major attraction for overseas visitors.
``The ever-improving road and rail connections and the forthcoming release of
the film Loch Ness should make us even more popular in 1996 and beyond.''
Scotland has enjoyed an average four per cent increase in overseas visitors
each year for the past 10 years.
The Scottish Tourist Board said it hoped to build on this growth with resources
made available by Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth for an international
marketing drive.
The Scottish Tourist Board 1996 Overseas Guide is printed in six foreign
languages and distributed throughout the world as an information guide for
visitors interested in coming to Scotland.
</TEXT>
