<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Government stalling over its plans for Trident refit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN BRUCE Defence Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684231</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government is stalling for time on the final announcement of the
destination of the #5000m Trident nuclear submarine refit programme, in the
hope that a face-saving deal can be struck with potential buyers of Devonport
shipyard.
Workers at the Plymouth yard were promised two weeks ago that they would know
their fate before Christmas. However, Parliament rose last Wednesday for its
New Year recess without a mention of the issue or of privatisation plans for
the complex.
Earlier this month The Herald revealed exclusively that a number of options
were being considered, including the possibility of the four Vanguard-class
boats being refuelled at Rosyth and refurbished at Devonport to avoid a totally
embarrassing political U-turn.
The original deal favouring the lower tender put forward by Devonport
Management Ltd, the consortium operating the yard, is no longer relevant on
cost grounds. Estimates for upgrading the Plymouth complex to meet nuclear
safety requirements range from #500m to #700m above DML's bid.
The Nuclear Installations Inspectorate, the independent body responsible for
licensing atomic facilities in the UK, has already said that serious problems
exist at the site because of the instability of the limestone base on which it
is built.
To comply with nuclear safety rules, DML would have to prove that a 16,000-ton
Vanguard submarine could be held securely in drydock during the replacement of
its highly radioactive fuel rods in the event of an earthquake or large
explosion.
Critics have always said the contract was awarded to the English yard more
because of the threat to four marginal Conservative parliamentary seats in the
South-west than because of financial or practical considerations.
The Government's last real hope of a get-out is outright purchase of the
Devonport complex, coupled to grants which might help ease the improvement
burden for a potential buyer.
</TEXT>
