<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Union sees shortcomings as a warning Tunnel fire study critical of rail safety</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>EXCLUSIVE By ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684232</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POTENTIALLY ``disastrous'' fire in the Moncrieffe tunnel last March has been
cited by the Rail, Maritime, and Transport union as an example of how
pre-privatisation fragmentation of the rail industry could make the system less
safe.
Commenting on a damning indictment of rail safety procedures contained in a
confidential internal investigation into a fire in the tunnel between Hilton
and Perth in the early hours of Sunday, March 26 this year, RMT general
secretary Jimmy Knapp said the safety plan was ``clearly wholly inadequate''.
The rail unions have been warning for some time that safety is likely to suffer
through more and more fragmentation of what in the past would have been the
sole responsibility of British Rail.
Neither Railtrack, which has overall reponsibility for rail safety, nor BR
Infrastructure Services, whose staff were involved, wanted to apportion blame
and both stressed that they had jointly investigated the incident and would
continue to work together to enhance safety procedures wherever possible.
There were no serious injuries during the fire which broke out during rerailing
operations, but the joint investigation shows that was largely fortuitous
because unknown to the fire brigade rescue team there were hazardous materials
and eight staff in the tunnel even after it was supposed to have been evacuated.
``On arrival at the scene the officer in charge from the brigade received
minimal information from our supervisor who told him that everyone was out of
the tunnel and that no hazardous materials were present'', says the report.
But both pieces of information proved incorrect ``and could have had disastrous
consequences,'' concludes the safety study completed earlier this month but not
published.
The report details how the 1210-yard tunnel includes three ventilation shafts,
all of which have been blocked off as an anti-vandalism measure, and has no in
situ lighting. Four days before the work was due to commence there were
consultations between the Tayside Fire Brigade station safety officer and
Railtrack's fire safety manager.
At 2.30am on March 26 all but two of the 27-strong maintenance team entered the
tunnel and were operating two rail laying machines some 900 yards from the
south end of the tunnel when at 5.05am one caught fire. The resulting fumes and
gas accumulation forced the staff to evacuate before any remedial action could
be taken.
Emergency services were alerted within five minutes and arrived eight minutes
later to be informed that all staff had been evacuated and all traffic halted.
Two firefighters with breathing apparatus were sent into the tunnel but were
withdrawn when the smoke thickened considerably and temporary lighting failed.
``At 05.32hrs despite assurances to Fire Brigade personnel that all staff had
evacuated the tunnel, several trackmen exited the tunnel to the Hilton end
suffering the effects of smoke inhalation. They received oxygen treatment from
fire crews and an ambulance was summoned.''
Around 5.55am the smoke dissipated sufficiently for fire crews to enter and
finally extinguish the fire at 6.07 and casualties were treated on site before
being transferred to Perth Royal Infirmary.
Conclusions include:
q There were no fire extinguishers on site to enable the fire to be tackled at
an early stage.
q There was no formal evacuation plan and the haphazard evacuation of the
tunnel resulted in eight men passing through the cloud of fumes and
experiencing smoke inhalation.
q No roll call was taken at a nominated rendezvous point which meant that the
eight were unaccounted for in a period of 25 minutes.
q Together with the unrevealed presence of acetylene and oxygen in the tunnel
this could have had ``disastrous consequences''.
Recommendations include the removal from service of all Bruff rail laying
machines until plastic fuel tanks have been replaced by steel ones and
electrical systems checked; suitable fire fighting equipment to be located on
site when similar work is being carried out in tunnels; and development of an
agreed method of evacuation in the event of emergencies to include fire
assembly points and roll calls.
Despite assurances to fire brigade personnel that all staff had evacuated the
tunnel, several trackmen exited the tunnel suffering the effects of smoke
inhalation
Investigation report
</TEXT>
