<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murdered head voted listeners' man of year</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684233</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEADMASTER Philip Lawrence was yesterday named Personality of the Year on BBC
Radio 4's Today programme.
Mr Lawrence, who was fatally stabbed outside his London school while helping a
pupil who was being attacked, polled 23,130 of the 77,570 votes cast by the
programme's listeners.
His widow, Frances, said she was deeply moved, although she believed her
husband, who was a modest man, would have been very embarrassed.
On the programme Mrs Lawrence said: ``One realises that dreadful events are in
the minority, that most people were appalled at what happened.
``That is very comforting because when faced with what we were faced with that
Friday night the world becomes an evil place. But now one can see it isn't all
evil - that it is mostly good.''
She said the Government had not gone far enough in its response to the tragedy,
on December 8, and called for a forum of politicians, churchmen, and ordinary
people to try to re-evaluate what is happening to society.
Mrs Lawrence said it should try to give guidance away from what her husband
called the ``obsessive drive for personal possession'' and back to spiritual
values.
She added:``It is not enough to get rid of knives. That won't get rid of
violence. We must attack it on a much more basic level.''
Cardinal Basil Hume, head of the Roman Catholic Church in England, said: ``I am
very moved at the award. Philip Lawrence was a good husband, a good father, and
a good man.''
Runner-up, for the second year running, was the Prime Minister, who got 18,260
votes.
Third was assassinated Israeli prime minister Yitzhak Rabin, followed by the
Princess of Wales, Labour leader Tony Blair, and the Queen Mother.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sri Lankan urged to alter action</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684298</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE International Cricket Council (ICC) has urged Sri Lanka off-spinner Muttiah
Muralitharan to alter his suspect action to guarantee his future as a Test
player.
Cricket's world governing body issued a statement after Muralitharan's bowling
method was ruled illegal by Australian umpire Darrell Hair on the opening day
of the second Test against Australia in Melbourne yesterday.
``We sincerely trust that the BCCSL (Sri Lanka Cricket Board of Control) will
work with this player to take whatever corrective action is necessary so that
he can continue to represent his country,'' ICC chief executive David Richards
said in a statement released through the Australian Cricket Board.
``To that end, the ICC remains prepared to assist the achievement of this
objective in any way that we can.''
In detailing its past concerns over Muralitharan's bowling action - dating back
three years - the ICC defended Hair's ruling: ``It is every umpire's duty to
apply the laws of cricket fully and impartially and we stand in full support of
those umpires who execute this responsibility to the best of their ability. The
relevant law is clear and the game cannot accept any breach of this law,'' the
statement said.
Muralitharan, whose action has been questioned in the past, was no-balled seven
times in three overs before switching ends without further incident. He claimed
the wicket of Mark Waugh for 61.
Australia, leading the three-Test series 1-0, finished an eventful day on 234
for three.
Asked if Muralitharan's Test future was under threat because of the umpire's
decision, Sri Lanka team manager Duleep Mendis said after close of play:
``Naturally, it is. If it continues, obviously we have to do something about
it.''
He said that Muralitharan may try to make a slight alteration to his action.
The Sri Lankans were clearly stunned by events yesterday, just 24 hours after
they were exonerated by the ICC of ball-tampering during their defeat in the
first Test two weeks ago.
q.WEST Indies slumped to their fifth successive limited-overs defeat on tour in
Australia when they lost by four wickets to Queensland in Brisbane yesterday.
Replying to West Indies' 50-over 206 for eight, Queensland cruised to 207 for
six with 17 balls to spare.
After three defeats against Australia and Sri Lanka in the World Series
tournament and a humiliating loss to the youngsters of the Australian Cricket
Academy, West Indies' top order failed yet again.
They were in dire straits on 121 for six after 35 overs before off-spinner
Roger Harper rallied the innings with an unbeaten 46 from 51 balls.
Harper, who smashed the last ball of the innings for 6, shared a 77-run
partnership from 88 balls with Jimmy Adams to lift their side to a respectable
total. But it was to prove inadequate when Queensland captain Stuart Law got
into his stride.
Law, a member of Australia's limited overs side but overlooked for Test duty,
scored 70 from 84 balls.
ROUND-UP
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>When `cheers' turned to tears</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684299</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JAMES Traynor's recollections of past England-Scotland confrontations revives
many memories. The Scottish media did their best to play down our humiliating
defeats, while heaping praise on our few successes.
I remember the headline Three Cheers For Scotland in an evening paper on April
15, 1961, which raised my hopes as I was unaware of the result - but
underneath, Nine For England soon informed me of the reality.
It is a pity that the war-time internationals between the two countries are not
included in the records. No less than 14 matches were played and, while
Scotland got done over in most of them, I remember seeing one of their few
successes, a 5-4 win at Hampden in April, 1942.
The highest attendance at a war-time international was 133,000 at Hampden on
April 22, 1944, when England won 3-2. England had legendary players in Swift,
Mercer, Matthews, Carter, and Lawton, who proved on most occasions - including
an 8-0 win at Manchester - too far ahead of the Scots in skill.
One unusual incident occurred in the match at Hampden on April 17, 1943
(England won 4-0). An off-the-ball incident saw England's Stan Cullis collapse
in agony. The Scots player involved never played for Scotland again.
John G Hall,
33 High Street,
Stewarton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>THE CLASSICAL HIGHS OF 95</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684300</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Performances of the Year
q LOCK, stock and barrel of awards to the St Petersburg Philharmonic Orchestra,
its chief conductor, the sensational Yuri Temirkanov, and the late Peter
Tchaikovsky. The legendary St Petersburg Phil took up a residency in Glasgow in
October during the week of the fifth anniversary celebrations of the city's
Royal Concert Hall. In two nights they gave three concerts. Over the three
shows they played all six of Tchaikovsky's symphonies.
The concerts included some of the most searing and emotional perfomances I have
ever heard, with Temirkanov in devastating form, and the unbelievably
rich-sounding band producing playing that was out of this world: stupendous
orchestral articulation in a sensational finale to the Fourth Symphony, a
completely heartbreaking Fifth that reduced even the hardest-nosed listeners to
tears, and a final Sixth Symphony that plumbed the depths of Tchaikovsky's
fatal depression, ending in utter blackness.
Record of the Year
q COMPLETELY partisan view here. James MacMillan, whose level of inspiration
appears to be unfaltering, last year produced a work unsurpassed in his output,
the intensely moving Seven Last Words from the Cross, for chorus and string
orchestra. This year, the CD recording was issued, confirming the work as a
masterpiece. Spellbinding and awe-inspiring, the music is powerful, majestic,
harrowing, and beautiful enough to move the most entrenched agnostic. One to
live with and cherish.
Music book of the Year
q MAYNARD Ferguson's astonishing study of Mozart - ``Mozart: A Life'',
published by Hutchison - brings the genius to life, characterising him as never
before. Every aspect of Mozart's life, from his composing facility, his
personal relationships, and - above all - his ambivalent relationship with his
father, the endlessly manipulative Leopold, who turned the infant prodigy into
an industry and made him psychologically dependent, leaps off the page.
Indispensible.
Scoop of the Year
q THE tiny Vale of Glamorgan Festival, run on a shoestring with a part-time
administration, and so brilliantly devised that it stands as an exemplar of
contemporary music festival, stunned the world and the musical establishment
when it won Britain's biggest arts prize of #100,000. The Vale festival,
beating off the giants and multinationals of the classical music business, had
earlier picked up the #25,000 prize in the music category - this had been
announced and awarded in Glasgow.
In the final, each category winner - from music, theatre, opera dance, visual
art and film - competed for a further #75,000. The results were announced in
the Olivier Theatre at London's South Bank Centre with the cream of the
establishment represented. As the announcement of the Vale of Glamorgan's
success was made, a spontaneous and bloodcurdling series of Pictish whoops of
triumph was heard to erupt among the dinner-suited mob.
It's long-enough ago now for me to admit that they came from this writer, who
had been on the judging panel for the music award, and who, with composer Steve
Martland, had fought to get the Vale of Glamorgan first prize. Well done, the
small fry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>In search of clues</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Conrad Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684301</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TO perform Cosi fan tutte on an island in the Bay of Naples is no more a
guarantee of success than to perform Die Meistersinger in Nurnberg. Yet it was
in the shadow of Vesuvius that Mozart set his last Italian comedy, and there is
always the hope, however romantic, that the atmosphere of the place might
induce someone to stage it there.
It was for Ischia, therefore, that I recently embarked to test the truth of the
theory. Each year in the idyllic villa where Sir William Walton once lived, and
where his widow continues to commemorate him in various ways, a three-week
course entitled The Actor in Opera is held. With Martin Isepp, from
Glyndebourne, as musical director, Colin Graham as producer and Catherine
Wilson and Leonard Hancock (both formerly of Scottish Opera) as assistants, a
small team of gifted young British and Italian singers are taught how to
portray the roles they have already learnt to sing.
Graham, a half-Scot who, with Sir Alexander Gibson, once presented Peter Grimes
and Pelleas et Melisande for Scottish Opera, is a producer in the old-fashioned
mould, who presides serenely over stagings that grow out of the music and are
invariably true to the story line. Just before this year's sessions, however,
he had to undergo emergency heart surgery. A replacement was needed. And so,
into the calm of the Walton villa and its exquisite Italian gardens, stepped
Ian Judge like the proverbial bull in a china shop.
Judge, too, has worked for Scottish Opera, though rather more recently than
Graham. In Falstaff he obscured Verdi's music beneath layers of knockabout
comedy. In Bellini's Norma he so offended the company's women choristers that,
in his own words, he is unlikely to be invited back.
From the start he made plain that working on Ischia was a bit beneath his
dignity. The singers, he said, were ``slow.'' The Walton museum, where the
performances took place, was the wrong shape. It all seemed more trouble than
it was worth.
Yet gradually Cosi cast its spell. The room was rearranged so that the opera
could be presented in the round, with the singers so close to the audience that
everybody could share their unfolding emotions. And to liberate his cast from
what he considered to be their lethargy, Judge devised various tasks for them -
singing arias while improvising wholly incongruous action, learning how to move
at a wholly different pace from the music. As time ticked by, a meticulously
detailed scenario began to evolve.
Working in the round, it soon became apparent, is more challenging than singing
from behind a proscenium arch. The singers must learn to project their
personalities in constantly changing directions. Their entrances and exits,
because they take place through the audience, must form part of the drama. Not
until you see such a production in rehearsal do you realise quite what it
involves.
Because Judge was working with inexperienced performers, it seemed possible
that his staging might prove a misjudgment. He simply did not have time to get
the sort of results he desired, especially in the presence of an increasingly
exasperated musical director (and in fact, in the end, only Act One of the
opera was staged, with Act Two presented in a concert version).
Yet although his demands at times seemed brutal, they were pertinent to current
trends in opera. ``If you're going to enter while music is being played, you
must always enter faster than the music,'' he told one singer. ``Don't enter
slower, and don't enter at the same speed or you'll seem to be dancing.'' What
Mozart himself would have expected is hard to say, but seemed beside the point.
``Despina, release yourself from the music. What you're doing is starting to
fit your actions to the notes. Do everything in the wrong rhythm. Some very
famous singers are completely locked into the music. Don't let this happen to
you.''
But the rehearsals were not merely a matter of movement, even if a lot of time
was spent showing the unwilling Italian Dorabella how to fall down during an
aria. ``What you must do is fall and turn. Your knee mustn't hit the ground.''
(Judge thereupon fell expertly upon the Italian marble floor, but ended up in
casualty with a damaged knee).
The following day was spent going through the text in search of psychological
``clues''. The implications of Don Alfonso's cruel practical joke were
analysed. The cast were asked to decide for themselves what happens at the end
of the opera. ``I won't tell you,'' Judge told them. ``Mozart always leaves the
ends of his acts open.''
Though some would say that the ending of Cosi is perfectly explicit if Don
Alfonso's final lines are followed, modern producers are invariably blind to
what they don't want to see. As rehearsals progressed, Judge seemed displeased
to be told that the action of Cosi is meant to take place within a single day,
or that when, in the context of this opera, the clock strikes six it actually
means noon (Italy, in Mozart's time, used clocks that struck no higher than
six).
It was at this point - for me if not yet for the rehearsals - that time ran
out. The public performances, when finally given, won praise, and the
production, in an amended version, went to Wexford.
Ian Judge's version of La Belle Helene forEnglish National Opera has won
muchpraise. Conrad Wilson saw him at workin Italy earlier in the year,
alongsideother former Scottish Opera stalwarts
</TEXT>
