<HEADLINE>Cork second best in duel with Cullinan.South Africa have edge after full day's play</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684302</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOMINIC Cork was forced to settle for second place in the fourth Test yesterday
after St George's Park had staged its own version of Derby day in Port
Elizabeth.
Cork kept England's flag fluttering by picking up two wickets when they were
most needed, even though the early going looked anything but helpful for a
thoroughbred fast bowler.
However, he could not find a way past Daryll Cullinan, the batsman who was his
Derbyshire team-mate last season. but the pair do not act like best buddies and
both are coy when asked about their professional relationship.
Cullinan wore the bigger smile yesterday after having led South Africa out of
trouble and into the relatively calm waters of 230 for four by scoring an
undefeated 83.
``It's not particularly a rivalry,'' said Cullinan. ``But I think he enjoys
getting my wicket. He's a good competitor and that brings the best out of
batsmen.''
Cork failed to pick up anyone's wicket during South Africa's only innings at
Durban, where the third Test was wrecked by rain. In Port Elizabeth the
all-rounder found himself operating on a pitch that was slow enough and low
enough to break a bowler's heart.
A capacity crowd of 18,000 witnessed a rare event in recent South African
history - a full day's cricket without a single interruption for bad weather.
Mike Atherton's failure to guess correctly between heads and tails could yet
prove to be the most significant moment in this match.
The bounce is likely to become variable and if there is turn by the time of the
fourth innings of the match, South Africa have an 18-year-old wrist spinner -
Paul Adams - who will be only too keen to exploit it.
After the close of play bookmakers rated England 8-1 outsiders to win the Test,
with South Africa at 2-1, and the draw 4-9 favourite. For the moment, though,
England are by no means out of it, thanks mainly to Cork's ability to conjure
up a little magic.
His first trick came when South Africa, moving along slowly but surely, had
reached 57 for nought. Brought back just before lunch, the all-rounder moved
one away just enough to clip the outside edge of Andrew Hudson's bat.
That was the inspiration England badly needed. After the interval they picked
up two wickets in the space of three overs.
Hansie Cronje, determined not to repeat the reckless drive against spinner
Richard Illingworth that brought his downfall in Durban, overdid the caution by
taking 24 deliveries to get off the mark. Then, having pulled Peter Martin to
the fence, South Africa's captain fell two deliveries later.
Driving at Martin, Cronje failed to get to the pitch of the ball and was
superbly caught by Atherton, anticipating the stroke and diving to his right,
at short extra cover.
When left-handed opener Gary Kirsten, having just completed a half-century
including nine boundaries, snicked Mark Ilott low to first slip, South Africa
were wobbling on 89 for three.
Cullinan looks a far better batsman when attacking rather than defending, and
he refused to let a potentially tricky situation prevent him from going after
anything remotely loose.
There is a rumour that Cullinan did not particularly enjoy his time with
Derbyshire. If that is true, scoring runs against a former colleague would
inevitably give him particular satisfaction. But he refuses to give anything
away on that score.
In any event, South Africa's No.4 rose to the challenge which Cork and the rest
of England's attack were presenting during a picture-changing stand of 118 with
Jonty Rhodes.
Cullinan, who walked away undefeated and only 17 runs away from the second Test
century of his career, collected 13 boundaries - a good number of them driven
handsomely though the covers.
``We were wobbling a bit after lunch, but Daryll and Jonty both played
marvellous innings,'' said home coach Bob Woolmer.
Rhodes enjoyed one slice of luck on 20 when edging a forcing shot against Ilott
that Graeme Hick, leaping at second slip, touched but could not hold.
Soon afterwards he hooked Cork for the 6 that completed a century partnership
and it looked as though England would finish the day with only three wickets to
show for a spirited bowling performance.
Cork, however, had other ideas. Rhodes had made 49 when he pulled a short ball
from the paceman low to Robin Smith at square leg and the tourists could feel
reasonably satisfied, if not thrilled, with their efforts.
