<HEADLINE>Dallas will be at home</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEVE LIVINGSTONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684303</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN FOOTBALL
THE Dallas Cowboys earned the right to home-field advantage throughout the
playoffs by defeating Arizona Cardinals 37-13 at the venue for Super Bowl XXX
in Sun Devil Stadium, Tempe.
Running back Emmitt Smith tied up the league rushing title and in the process
broke one of the NFL's most prized records. With a three-yard run late in the
match he surpassed the record for most touchdowns in a season - the 24 set by
Washington Redskins' running back John Riggins in 1983.
Smith, who already had the league rushing title before the game, also tied a
team record with his eleventh consecutive game with at least one rushing
touchdown. It was his 100th career touchdown - tying him for ninth on the
all-time list behind the 156 of San Francisco wide receiver Jerry Rice.
The Cowboys (12-4) lost the home-field advantage to San Francisco last year,
and were beaten 38-28 by the 49ers in the NFC championship game. This time, the
right to play at home until the Super Bowl has gone to the Cowboys.
STEVE LIVINGSTONE
</TEXT>
