<HEADLINE>Two faces of generosity Street touts are now the big issuethat daily faces pedestrians andSTEPHEN FERGUSON just can'ttake - or give - any more</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684304</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE streets of Glasgow are not safe. Not safe at all. Guns and knives,
aggressive words, motor vehicles careering out of control, city-centre smog,
drug-induced acts of depravity - all are fears that most of us have grown
accustomed to. We know they're there, but still we go out, we swagger along, we
sing merry tunes in our heads. We're twentieth-century folk; both brave and
stupid.
But there is a growing fear on the streets today employing a different kind of
weapon, one cunningly disguised behind a waxed smile and a bleeding heart, one
that challenges our chirpy complexion.
The weapon - increasingly present in the city centre - is the dreaded,
much-feared question; unsolicited, brutally direct, delivered in a pucker
manner by a total stranger, and one that the chosen victim feels unable to
ignore. Questions like: ``Would you like to make a donation?'', ``Would you
like to buy a copy of . . ?'', ``Are you interested in . . ?'', and ``Can I
tempt you into . . ?'' Endless questions making endless demands on our
generosity and civility.
This escalating fear is brought to us by the street touts - and suddenly they
seem to be everywhere. No-one is safe. The perpetrators strike indiscriminately
and with little or no warning. They are after everyone of us, after our money,
after our time and attention, after our allegiance to a cause.
Basically we're all people with little missions. There are those who like to
take a ball of thought and wander the streets unravelling it at their leisure,
while some seek to defeat huge shopping lists in record-breaking time, others
seek to rein the sprawling energies of children as they keep one clear
destination in mind.
Missions unsuccessful. Now, interruptions knot the mind and impede our
ambitions: the sharpened rhetoric of Living Marxism sellers; the brandished
tins of good causes rattling like sabres; furtive, murky-eyed men selling
arcane pamphlets and felt-tipped pens; the dispossessed, ghostly faces of the
homeless with their apologetic and childlike stares, their bony hands
stretching out for spare change, and something ineffable that money can't buy.
Not to mention the vacant disposition of migrant Buddhists waving their
esoteric books like grenades made of strange-smelling paper.
Are these growing pieces of mobile ``street furniture'' something that pestered
shoppers will simply have to get used to?
At the moment no single body is in control of this expanding limb. Major
charities are licensed by the Secretary of State and are, therefore, allowed to
tout for donations at any time - in just one day in October Oxfam sent 175
volunteers on to the city centre streets. Only smaller charities must apply to
Glasgow City Council, and the licensing department reports that where a charity
had previously asked for one day in a year, now they can be requesting up to
five days.
``Buy a copy of the Big Issue'' is the clearest and most heard request on our
streets. But the magazine distributed by ``the homeless'' seems to be growing
out of the creator's control. The magazine claims to have no clear figures on
how many people are selling the magazine - all it can say is that roughly 3000
people are selling the magazine in Scotland. And with the magazine having been
classed as a ``street paper'' it is free of council control.
The reasons for the growth in numbers of people touting on our streets are
varied, but distil into one barrel: necessity. Charities, the homeless,
political organisations, religions, scam merchants, all are after money - they
need it, and touting seems a quick way to get it.
Blame is invariably placed at the Government's door. The homeless blame
stringent legislation that has turned the social safety net into a loosely
cordoned-off abyss. Charities blame the National Lottery for forcing them to
traipse the streets branding the captured/generous (delete as appropriate) with
an invariably unsightly sticker. Socialists are a little different - when not
blaming the Government for one misdemeanour or another, they turn to blaming
each other instead.
But Scots are generous people. Always have been. They give, then give again,
just for the sheer shiny hell of it. So maybe street touting is just the old
community spirit - said to be oh so dead today - returning in another form. A
bit like giving a bowl of sugar to a neighbour - it's just that the community
is somewhat bigger, and you're highly unlikely ever to see the bowl - or the
sugar for that matter - returned. Convinced? Thought not.
Generosity that is boundless is as rare as a five-headed baby. But it's
difficult to be bountiful with the feel-good factor still missing, presumed
dead. And each week there's the National Lottery inculcating the belief into a
nation that there is no need to give something in return for nothing.
Generosity, if not having five heads, at least now has two faces.
Get used to it. Stomach it. Is that what we're learning to do? Or are we
already learning to walk past it, head down, gaze averted? The rise in street
touting is indeed an exposed artery showing the current social state of the
country, but the growing reaction of people is equally telling.
Slowly people seem to be mustering the ability to decline requests - and thus
another barrier between people is steadily being erected for the sake of our
own needs, or wishes, or whatever we want to call them.
And so another fear stalks the shadows threatening to invade the daylight; the
death of generosity itself, its weapon cutting like a swallowed razor blade.
Perhaps it would be better, after all, just to get used to street touts, to
endure, rather than face such a frightening reality walking the streets;
unavoidable, right inside every one of us - even if it is one we can acquire
free of charge.
</TEXT>
