<HEADLINE>`Flyer' can pass this tough test</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684306</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUBLIN Flyer can prove himself a chaser of the highest class with victory in
today's rearranged King George VI Tripleprint Chase at Kempton, writes White
and Gold.
The dashing front-runner was one of last season's top handicappers, successful
in thrilling style in the Gold Cup at Cheltenham and the John Hughes Trophy at
Aintree.
He looked worth a crack at the best opposition when defying 11st 8lb in the
Mackeson Gold Cup at Cheltenham on his reappearance last month, rallying
splendidly to beat Egypt Mill Prince by half a length. His jumping will stand
the test in a race which promises to be run at a searching gallop.
By contrast, neither Barton Bank nor One Man inspire total confidence at the
fences in a race which has lost some of its edge now that the original entry
has shrunk.
Atours can give David Elsworth a third successive win in the Bonusprint
Christmas Hurdle after Muse and Absalom's Lady. The seven-year-old developed
into a smart hurdler last term, going down by just a neck to his stable
companion in this event.
He scored in small fields here and at Wincanton before a close second to the
then Champion Hurdle favourite Large Action at Ascot over a two-and-a-half-mile
trip which is possibly too far for him. Atours will be well suited by this
return to two miles.
Easy Buck looks the best bet in the Tripleprint Handicap Chase. The gelding
showed useful form in winning twice last season and does not look to have
deteriorated, judged on his reappearance victory at Newbury last month.
The eight-year-old hit the front soon after halfway and would have scored by
further than his eventual length-and-a-half winning margin but for tiring in
the closing stages.
</TEXT>
