<HEADLINE>Frenchmen to play compatriot games</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684307</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN ENGLAND
DAVID Ginola prepared himself to come face to face with Eric Cantona for the
first time in England today, confident that Newcastle will show they have
earned the right to call themselves the best team in the country.
Ginola's public dispute with his fellow Gaul has been well documented, although
he did hold out an olive branch last week by expressing the hope that both men
would be named in the French squad for next summer's European Championship
finals.
But the friendly overtures will go on hold for 90 minutes as 28-year-old Ginola
and his St James' Park team-mates aim to extend the lead over Alex Ferguson's
Manchester United to a commanding 13 points.
Ginola, outstanding as Kevin Keegan's side clocked up their tenth successive
Premiership home victory over Nottingham Forest on Saturday, roared out a
message of defiance as he declared: ``I think we're better than United at the
moment.''
``We're mentally very good, very strong, and we have the right team spirit
within the squad - in fact, everything that helps you to play good football and
be happy on the pitch.
``I think it's an important game, but it's not the last game of the season, not
even the most important one of the season.
``We're 10 points ahead and even if we lose we'll still be seven points ahead,
so it won't be a major blow.
``But if we really want to be able to call ourselves the best team in England,
we have to be able to beat United tomorrow.''
Ginola exuded confidence when asked if he felt nervous about walking out in
King Eric's realm.
``It will be my first time at Old Trafford, but I've played against Real Madrid
in the Bernabeu, against Barcelona in the Nou Camp, and Milan at the San
Siro,'' he said. ``So I don't think playing at Old Trafford will be a problem,
although I expect I'll get a few boos from the United fans because I'm the
second Frenchman in England, after Eric Cantona.''
Keegan is likely to stick with the side on duty at the weekend - with Philippe
Albert consigning the unfortunate John Beresford to the bench - although after
toying with a 3-4-3 formation against Forest, the manager indicated he would
revert to a more orthodox 4-4-2.
By contrast, the 3-1 defeat at Leeds on Sunday meant Ferguson's outfit have now
gone five games without a win, and the manager's injury problems are mounting
up.
Steve Bruce's damaged hamstring means he will almost certainly join central
defensive partner Gary Pallister on the sidelines. After the disastrous attempt
to counter the thrust of Tony Yeboah - a player comparable to Les Ferdinand -
with Paul Parker at Elland Road, the manager faces a dilemma.
David May seems likely to return, but Ferguson is pondering his options with
French trialist William Prunier, Gary Neville - whose brother Philip could come
in at left-back with Dennis Irwin switching flanks - and Roy Keane all possible
choices.
Ferguson, who admits his side simply must win, also awaits news of Ryan Giggs'
foot injury. His biggest hope will surely be that Andy Cole's strike against
Leeds will be the perfect morale-booster before the #7m man's first game
against his former club.
``Andy looked as if he could score all game on Sunday,'' said Ferguson. ``Every
time the ball went near him there was a smell of goals off him, which was very
refreshing.
``He's had his bad spell, but he had five strikes at goal on Sunday, all on
target, with a firm, crisp strike to score the goal. Andy's all about scoring
goals and hopefully that will get him off on a run now.''
Just a dozen or so miles north of Old Trafford, Bolton will be looking to build
on their first away point of the season - at Tottenham - when they take on a
bullish Leeds side.
Bolton's White Hart Lane heroics could not prevent them losing yet more ground
at the bottom and Dutchman Richard Sneekes, an early substitute for Andy Todd,
could make his first start in nine games.
Leeds have midfielder Carlton Palmer suspended so South African
internationalist Lucas Radebe, on the bench against Manchester United, may step
in nine months after undergoing major knee surgery.
</TEXT>
