<HEADLINE>Punters are frozen out</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WHITE AND GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684308</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE weather dealt racing a massive blow yesterday with all 10 meetings on the
British mainland abandoned, the first time for 33 years that a complete Boxing
Day programme had been wiped out by the elements.
Prospects for the rest of the week are grim with the Welsh National, feature
event at the Chepstow meeting, joining Wetherby, Leicester and Edinburgh on
today's casualty list.
Clerk of the course at the Welsh track, Rodger Farrant, said: ``The stewards
inspected the course this afternoon and had no alternative but to abandon the
meeting. Parts of the course are still frozen and the overnight weather
forecast held out no prospect of improvement.''
However, the Welsh National may not have been lost. Last season's race was
transferred to Newbury after the Chepstow meeting was abandoned and another
switch could be in the offing.
``We're not going to do anything today, but will begin to look at it
tomorrow,'' said Rob Hartnett, spokesman for Corals.
Kempton's King George VI Tripleprint meeting was the last of the Boxing Day
fixtures to fall, with clerk of the course Michael Webster abandoning the
meeting at 11.40 after three previous morning checks.
Hopes of staging the feature race at today's scheduled meeting looked bleak
when Webster said: ``The forecasters predict it will be a little colder tonight
with temperatures dropping even to minus eight degrees.''
An early inspection is scheduled this morning at the Sunbury track, and if the
meeting fails to go ahead, plans are in hand to run the King George at Sandown
Park on Saturday week.
Tomorrow's prospects in Britain look grim with Taunton the only track not to
call for an inspection, and although a course spokesman gave the going as good
to soft, he also described the track as ``frozen.''
Noon inspections have been arranged at Carlisle and Stratford, with Cliff
Griggs, Plumpton's clerk of the course, scheduling an early check.
The last time all Boxing Day fixtures in Britain fell to the weather was during
the big freeze of 1962/63, when the only meeting staged between December 22 and
March 7 was at Ayr on January 5.
q THE eagerly-anticipated jumping debut of River North has been postponed until
the New Year following the abandonment of Kempton yesterday. The Peter
Savill-owned five-year-old, due to contest the Bonuspost Novice Hurdle, is now
likely to be re-routed to the Tolworth Hurdle at Sandown on January 6.
A Group 1 winner on the flat, River North could be aimed at the Champion Hurdle
if he makes his mark over the minor obstacles.
q PROMISING novice hurdler See More Business is bang on target for the
#27,000-added Challow Hurdle at Newbury on Saturday. Bridget Nicholls, wife of
trainer Paul, confirmed the gelding a definite starter should the meeting beat
the forecast heavy frost.
``He is absolutely fine and has come out of his race at Sandown in great form.
He will definitely go for the race if the meeting gets the go-ahead, but that
seems pretty unlikely at the moment, doesn't it?'' Mrs Nicholls added.
</TEXT>
