<HEADLINE>`Gallant' recovery</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684309</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHARLIE Swan made a remarkable recovery to rescue favourite backers yesterday
afternoon as Limerick beat the frost that obliterated the rest of the Boxing
Day programme.
Riding for the first time since injuring his right arm at Clonmel on December
8, Swan was cheered to the echo when he somehow maintained his partnership with
Go Go Gallant after a desperate mistake two out in the Holmes O'Malley &amp; Sexton
Handicap Chase.
The well-backed 7-4 favourite had jumped to the front three out and appeared
all over a winner bar a fall when he slipped going into the second last, landed
on his nose, and slithered along the ground before recovering to score by seven
lengths.
``He met it all wrong after slipping taking off, but he kept his balance, and,
luckily, the mistake did not take too much out of him. I know now that my arm
is okay again,'' said Swan.
Swan and trainer Fergie Sutherland were expected to also collect in the
featured Murphys Irish Stout Chase, but this time another favourite, Lisselan
Prince, had no answer to the power of the Danny O'Connell-trained Love The Lord.
``She is improving all the time but deserves a little break before we bring her
back with some of the good novice races in mind,'' said O'Connell.
``We were thinking of bringing her to Uttoxeter in March for the final of the
Tattersalls Mares Series, but she might get too much weight now.''
</TEXT>
