<DOCNO>GH951227-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Raise a glass to festive sport</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN MEEK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684311</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT comes round with the inevitability of the demand from the Inland Revenue,
the first call of the cuckoo, a player swearing to die for a jersey, or just
swearing, the Hearts and Hibs boards promising a brighter future, or even a
future, a new Albion Rovers manager, an England team pledging to play open
rugby, and a senior athletics official vowing to rid the sport of drugs.
Yes, it's the let's have a winter sporting break time, folks. Happy
hibernation, see you in the spring.
The calls to shut down the whole of outdoor sport in Britain are loud, yet
varied. There are those who would retire from the action as soon as the nights
draw in; it often becomes windy and wet in November which reduces the skill
factor so evident in all our games. Pause for thought.
But Christmas, indeed the whole festive season, brings the campaign to a
hysterical height. Give our lads a break over the holidays, Mr Scrooge, let
them go home and sit round the fireside - the television would be more accurate
- with Tiny Tim. Please don't send them out in the cold. Bah. Humbug!
I've seen two rugby matches in the past week and I bet the players would not
have missed either of them in exchange for a mound of mince pies.
Ask Master Peter Phillips, who made his debut for the Scottish Schools against
France on Friday, whether he would rather have been at Balmoral than
Murrayfield.
It wasn't a great game, but it was a grand family occasion - considerably more
fun than slumping in the armchair - in which mums, dads, sisters, brothers were
all encouraged to join in. But some poor boy might have broken an ankle or an
arm and spoiled his Christmas.
Yes, he might. And it could have happened just as easily ski-ing in the
Cairngorms, falling off a sledge in the local park or walking on frozen
pavements. We can't all join the Cotton Wool Club.
My second match was the Christmas Eve South v Glasgow district encounter, which
was switched from Selkirk to Murrayfield. This finished 23-5 in the Borderers'
favour and was probably the most entertaining game in the district championship
so far.
There were no complaints from Scotland wing Craig Joiner, who helped himself to
two tries, nor from Craig Chalmers, who looked a much more commanding figure
than of late. Glasgow scrum half Cammy Little did his prospects no harm either.
Indeed, the only moan I heard was from the Stirling County captain, Kevin
McKenzie. He was upset that the North and Midlands clash with Edinburgh on
Friday had had to be postponed.
The SRU are taking some stick for staging the district competition at this
time. I think that is unfair. Bad weather can appear at any time and there is
no evidence at all that the players hate turning out during the festive period.
Quite the reverse. I was due yesterday at the Edinburgh Academicals v Edinburgh
Borderers fixture at Raeburn Place which fell to frost like the rest. Now
Borderers are an invitation club, they only play 11 games a year, and the
reward for turning out, no matter who you are, is no more than a few beers and
a good nosh.
Yet, on Boxing Day they still managed to field a side sprinkled with caps.
Their secretary, Malcolm Murray, told me: ``We have some very loyal members and
lots of guys who just love taking part.
``The Boxing Day fixture is our biggest of the year and always attracts a good
crowd. One man even phoned from Gala to find out if the game was on.''
Exactly. What the moaning minnies do not realise is that games like this are
part of the festive season, that it brings people, families, out of the house
to see friends, enjoy a match and even a jar or two.
The footballers who were happiest yesterday were ones who got on the park. Just
ask the Celtic players if they enjoyed sitting it out.
There were hundreds of frustrated owners, trainers and jockeys throughout the
country as the Boxing Day card was decimated. And what a groan went up when the
big Kempton meeting, with the King George VI Chase, finally got the
thumbs-down. For this is another British sporting institution - who in the name
of Desert Orchid would want it run in April?
That is the other serious point. If there is to be a festive shut-down what is
to happen to the present fixtures?
Is rugby to begin in August? That will go down well with the wives. Is football
to become a summer sport? Would National Hunt racing not be much more
dangerous, for men and horses, on baked courses? Let us accept that this was
just a very cold year and continue to enjoy the sporting festivities.
What would you like to do, I inquired of my four-year-old grandson, on
Christmas morn? ``Get out on my bike and play football,'' he replied.
There's hope.
</TEXT>
