<HEADLINE>Quality guests at Menzieshill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684312</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOCKEY
IN THE present weather conditions, genuine winter sports like indoor hockey
come into their own but the Scottish Hockey Union is repeatedly accused of just
playing lip service to the game, even although it puts the more traditional
outdoor hockey in the shade when it comes to staging international events.
Insights Menzieshill, apart from maintaining a high quality of hockey, also
keep the sport in the limelight with their annual tournament, which begins this
afternoon at the Dick McTaggart Sports Centre in Dundee.
Maureen Golden and her band of workers have again put together a high-class
field, with the presence of English champions Old Loughtonians, the North
American select side Dita Travellers, and the Scottish Under-21s, as well as
Torbrex Wanderers, Touche Ross Gordonians, Bett Inns, and, of course, the
Scottish champions, Menzieshill.
Old Loughtonians will enhance the level of competition, while the participation
of Dita Travellers again emphasises the great commitment of their captain Peter
Jones to indoor hockey.
The former US captain is now prevented from competing in the Scottish league
because of the introduction of new rules which prevent the involvement of
foreigners. Not to be outdone, Jones has put together the Dita Travellers, from
players in Canada and the States, for a 10-day tour to Britain, starting with
the Menzieshill event.
There will, of course, be considerable interest in the Scottish Juniors. They
are using the tournament as part of their build-up to the finals of the
European Under-21 Championship in Zurich. With half of the 12-player squad
competing regularly for Indespension Western, they also will provide sterling
opposition.
Menzieshill will go into the three-day tournament on their own patch with a
full-strength squad, including a fit again John Christie, and so will be
expected to retain the trophy.
Scottish Under-21 squad: Derek Stark, Graham Joyce, Richard Forsyth, Stuart
McMorrow, Ewan Miller, Vishal Marwaha (all Indespension Western), Andrew
Balchin, James Burns (both Grange), Lawrence Docherty (MIM), Stefan Jachnick
(Touche Ross Gordonians), Alan Ralph (Ciba Kelburne), Mark McMahon (Pender
Uddingston).
Today's order of play: Insights Menzieshill v Bett Inns (4.15); Dita Travellers
v Torbrex Wanderers (5.10); Touche Ross Gordonians v Old Loytonians (6.05).
</TEXT>
