<HEADLINE>Jones again sees red mist</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684313</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FA PREMIERSHIP
VINNIE Jones was sent off for the eleventh time in his career in Wimbledon's
win against his old club Chelsea at Stamford Bridge yesterday. The 2-1 victory
was Wimbledon's first in 15 Premiership starts but, with the league's top sides
out of action yesterday, Jones ensured he would again be hogging the headlines
for all the wrong reasons.
The transfer-listed Welsh inter-nationalist was given his marching orders after
55 minutes when he lunged into Dutch man Ruud Gullit from behind for his second
bookable offence. But the visitors were 2-1 up and held on to win - as they did
when Jones was banished in their last victory against Liverpool in early
September!
Chelsea took the lead after 11 minutes through Romanian Dan Petrescu, who was
also on the receiving end of a Jones clattering for his trouble. But two
headers in four minutes from Robbie Earle and Efan Ekoku put Wimbledon 2-1 in
front.
Dean Holdsworth had a chance to steady 10-man Wimbledon's nerves with a
spot-kick after Ekoku was brought down midway through the second half. But
Dmitri Kharine saved - and Holdsworth was pulled off within five minutes.
The Premiership's top two, Newcastle and Manchester United, had a day off
before today's showdown at Old Trafford, and third-placed Liverpool's game at
Aston Villa was called off hours before kick-off because of a frozen pitch at
Villa Park. The weather also ruled out Coventry's game at West Ham.
But Tottenham failed to take their chance to go second when they were held to a
goalless draw at Southampton.
There was little festive cheer for a crowd of 15,238 at The Dell as Spurs
keeper Ian Walker was not called upon to make a save, while opposite number
Dave Beasant was stretched into action only once, when Teddy Sheringham shot
straight at him in the last five minutes.
After 10 games, Gerry Francis's side have still not lost away - but a win
yesterday would have been priceless.
QPR's mini-revival ended at Highbury, where a 38,000-plus crowd saw Paul Merson
grab two second-half goals in a 3-0 victory for Arsenal.
Ian Wright had scored the first a minute before half-time to put the Gunners on
their way to their first victory in five Premiership matches - and their first
against their London rivals since April 1991.
It was a dream first league start for Adrian Clarke, who helped create both
Merson's goals. But QPR plunged back into relegation trouble after beating both
Bolton and Aston Villa before Christmas.
Middlesbrough, needing victory at Everton to move up to second, suffered a 4-0
mauling at Goodison Park.
Andrei Kanchelskis, who chose to join Everton in the close season rather than
link up with former Manchester United team-mate Bryan Robson at Middlesbrough,
was the inspiration behind the victory.
Kanchelskis scored one and set up one of Graham Stuart's two goals while Craig
Short also netted in Boro's heaviest defeat of the season.
Nottingham Forest ended Sheffield Wednesday's recent revival with a 1-0 victory
at the City Ground, Jason Lee grabbing the sixth minute winner.
Later last night, Alan Shearer kept up his amazing Ewood Park scoring record to
help Blackburn to a 2-0 win over Manchester City.
Shearer had found the target in all of Rovers' previous nine home league games
this season and he needed just 11 minutes to maintain that record, slotting
home from 20 yards for his twenty-fourth goal of the season, his ninety-ninth
in the Premier League.
Blackburn's other goal, five minutes after the break, came from England
midfield player David Batty, who unleashed a right foot shot which screamed
into the top corner for his first goal for the club since signing from Leeds 26
months ago.
</TEXT>
