<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>no headline present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684314</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE mid-life crisis is not going according to plan. The new year brings what
friends and alleged well-wishers persist in calling ``the Big Four Oh''
(whatever happened to the Big Three Nine?), but it's hard to summon up a decent
sense of impending doom.
This could well be mistaken for late-blooming maturity, the equanimity,
perhaps, of an individual who has learned at last that you are only as old as
you feel, that age brings its own rewards, that life is what you make it, and
other such consolatory tripe. Somehow I don't think so.
Forty I could live without, it is true. Left to my own devices I would shuffle,
without even passing ``Go'', directly to 41, if only to avoid any and all of
the appalling ``surprise'' parties soon-to-be-former friends may, entirely at
their own risk, be planning.
Policy statements on this subject have already been issued and fair warning
given: proceed at your peril.
But that doesn't mean the columnist has been pitched into a slough of despond
by the sound of ticking clocks, the thought of chances missed, days wasted, and
deadlines for dazzling achievement overlooked. Far from it.
If there is a real problem with this entirely trivial anniversary it is the
embarrassing absence of proper angst.
This seems hardly fair. I had taken it as read that half the point of being 40
was the chance it allowed to wallow in bleak depression, to fret over human
frailty, to worry about flab, money, responsibilities, politics, the planet,
and why no-one seems capable of writing a decent pop song any more. To grow up,
in other words.
Yet thus far there's no sign, not even a flicker, of honest despair.
In fact - and this may be the truly worrying part - the list of things about
which it seems impossible to care less grows by the day, exponentially, like a
vast trivia quiz in which every question is a trick one.
This makes life harder for the humble pundit than you can know.
Consider, if nothing else, the prose liable to ensue. The brief but peerless
response ``Who cares?'' is not, take it from me, quite what editors are looking
for when the condition of, say, the royal marriage is to be discussed.
Who cares? is a good question none the less, and one that ought to be
compulsory for all those mature, 40-something professionals who earn their
bread from being professionally upset, active, interested, caring, or worried.
The world may be in a bad way, but it always was. That is not, in itself, the
point.
There are things worth worrying about, of course, but only a few about which
anything useful can then be said. A sense of proportion - meaning a sense of
relative values and scale - is the only weapon we have.
So when did you last see it in action? Public concern over the Prince of Wales
is a case in point, in fact.
The tricky constitutional issue involved in an acceptable future designation
for Camilla Parker-Bowles aside (Trollop-in-Waiting? Floozy to the Royal
Bedchamber? Bit on the Side by Appointment?), I defy any sane person to explain
what interest is left to be squeezed from this pulped fiction.
Yet half the world could burn and space would still be found on the front pages
for a snap of Charles shooting something small and harmless.
Thousands could be homeless and millions unemployed (ah yes, so they are) and
our media would be striving for a balanced portrayal of each party's
deeply-felt views (as seen on the righteous BBC) on why it is all someone
else's fault. Britain might be most of the way down the tubes but you, citizen,
will be the last to hear.
It is no accident. There is a huge and growing gulf between the ``news''
allowed the public - all that stuff we mature adults are daily told to worry
about - and what actually happens and matters. They keep it all hid, kid, and
they do it on purpose.
The media's agenda - all those spurious rows, passing scares, forgettable
scandals, and irrelevant controversies - is the modern version of bread and
circuses, the perfection of distraction. The things we are invited to worry
about are rarely the things we should be worrying about, and the chief among
these, paradoxically, is how information itself is controlled.
And am I not, even as I write, a part of all this? Up to a point, Lord Copper,
only up to a point.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
