<HEADLINE>Media should lay off Airdrie</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684315</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Herald report on the Dunfermline-Airdrie match (Dec. 18) by Douglas
Campbell has again shown a recurring media-led attack on Alex McDonald and his
team.
As an Airdrie fan I am sure some will take this as more partisan whining, but I
do consider my views to be objective, in particular in relation to this match
and absurd match report.
Airdrie played Campbell's beloved Pars out of the match for long periods with
Anthony Smith and Paul Harvey showing delightful football skills. Harvey
continued this into the second half before being kicked out of the game by
Dunfermline defenders and a referee whose decisions left both teams wondering
what was going on.
The only criticism that could be levelled at Airdrie was lack of penetration up
front.
As to Airdrie's cup record, over the past five years not only did they reach
two Scottish Cup finals but lifted the B&amp;Q Cup and made numerous other
semi-final appearances.
I am sick and tired of the ``well they don't let you play against them''
routine. Who does? The media ought to concentrate on the opposition's lack of
skill to break Airdrie down, as surely Airdrie are not responsible for other
teams shortcomings.
The majority of Airdrie fans back Alex McDonald's techniques and management
style.
Robert Hamilton,
20 Inverdale Avenue,
Airdrie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951227-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The morning after the night before</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684316</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR those who live their lives according to the Wildian maxim ``I can resist
everything except temptation'', this is a troublesome time. Temptation lurks
behind every pub, fridge, and bedroom door in the season of frolics, fun, and
fattening foods. A mischievous voice on our shoulder whispers ``moderation is a
virtue but it's bloody boring'', and your notion of pulling in the reins means
abiding by H.L Mencken's advice, ``I've made it a rule never to drink by
daylight and never to refuse a drink after dark''.
Now that Christmas is over and accounted for, we're girding our loins and our
livers for Hogmanay, traditionally the favoured feast of Scotland. But while we
are still bang in the middle of a period of excess and reckless behaviour - the
time when even the frostiest of maiden aunts tends to giggle, defrost, and have
one Advocaat and lemonade too many - it's becoming tinged with a slight
foreboding, with the knowledge that pleasures have to be paid for, that all
indulgences, be they epicurean or carnal, have to be squared with a day of
reckoning.
Because fast on the heels of the hedonism of Hogmanay comes the gravitas of New
Year's Day, a strange chilly day, whatever the temperature, when we have to
steel ourselves to all the terrifying promise of a fresh year. Are we up to the
challenge?
New Year's Day offers us the ultimate in clean slates, with desk diaries as yet
unblemished by all those irksome appointments which may or may not be
cancelled. The coming year presents an exhilarating vista of 365 days bursting
with unexplored potential. But no matter the strength of our determination to
make the most of this opportunity, in our heart of hearts we know it will be a
downhill slide. As usual, as the year advances we will careen, with
ever-increasing speed, away from our good intentions.
Mine are always the best intentions. I'm a sucker for new year resolutions
which is a bit pathetic considering I'm the sort of person who believes Resolve
is something you purchase at the chemist's the morning after the night before
to make the devils dancing on your eyelids disappear. Unfortunately, as diehard
addicts of Weightwatchers can testify, willpower ain't for sale. You can't buy
it in handipacks in Boots, more's the pity.
Six years ago, as Robbie Coltrane and Glasgow welcomed in the new year at
George Square, I headed off north with a friend to taste a traditional Scottish
Hogmanay in Ullapool. It didn't quite work out that way. We ended up dancing on
the breakfast bar of a Nigerian trawler with two cute Frenchmen, a middle-aged
Aussie couple, a strange Englishman, and a dozen worse-for-wear Nigerians,
failing to hear Big Ben's bells on a tiny, tinny radio belonging to one of the
fisherman. But that's another story and I don't know y'all well enough to share
it.
The next morning my mate and I stumbled through the fog of a hung-over blur to
embark on a refreshing new year's morning hike. We pulled on woollies and
boots, packed some hair of the dog, and rushed out into the dawn. Well, OK, it
was almost midday but so unusually early for us it felt like dawn. Two hours
later we sat in a sheltered cove a few miles outside Ullapool, gazed out at the
water, and gulped on freezing tins of lager and air so fresh it was almost
frisky. Then we made ambitious plans.
That New Year's Day sense of the world being your oyster is exacerbated when
you are in the middle of nowhere and everything is clean and glistening with
frost. As my lungs filled with the finest oxygen my heart filled with grandoise
ambitions. Fuelled with good Scottish air and good Scottish booze I made bold
declarations.
Nineteen ninety would be the year when I would untap my fountain of promise. I
would know no limits. My career would rocket into the media stratosphere. I
would write a book, nay, a play, nay, a Hollywood screenplay, oh, what the
heck, all three. I would learn how to drive. I would buy a car. Never mind the
fact that I couldn't afford even the lessons; that Hollywood cheque would take
care of all that. I would buy a sports car and a pair of Raybans.
My confidence would increase and my dress size would shrink - deploying my
euphemistic avoidance of the dreaded word, diet. My wardrobe would no longer be
all black but my bank balance would be. I'd do volunteer work at an old folks'
home and discreetly keep it a secret from everyone I knew. I'd be kind to
children and animals and be a stricter vegetarian - no more sneaking the fly
party-sized sausage roll at buffet functions.
I was convinced I'd achieve all this and more. In fact, I was so convinced I
wanted to head straight back to Glasgow to put it all in motion. The only thing
that stopped me was the next half a dozen cans of lager we consumed. And the
fact that I was stranded in Ullapool at the whim of my mate as I couldn't drive.
I was practically buzzing, I was so high on hope. I was completely deluded.
Thank God you can't sue yourself for breach of promise. Because, of course, I
didn't keep any of my new year resolutions. Not even the relatively
inconsequential ones - like always cleaning off my make-up before going to
sleep, or always washing out the coffee mugs before the onset of that green
mouldy stuff that floats in top.
The very memory of the resolutions dwindled away as the months rolled by. The
occasional reminders - those naughty sausage rolls, that irritatingly empty
file on the computer named ``creative'', mascara stains on pillow cases that no
amount of super-strength Persil could ever shift - caused slight twinges of
conscience, pangs of regret.
Ah well, never mind. There's one advantage in not keeping those 1990
resolutions. I don't have to dream up new ones for 1996. I'm already digging
out Hollywood agents' phone numbers and eyeing up sports cars. But not a black
one. Well, it simply wouldn't go with a new wardrobe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
