<HEADLINE>Tapping into Papua New Guinea's reserves</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684317</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INVERNESS-based economics consultant Tony Mackay will soon be swopping the cold
climate of Inverness for the tropics.
For Mr Mackay has been head-hunted by the Government of Papua New Guinea, where
he will be a key adviser to the Government during the next five years.
An authority on the oil industry, Mr Mackay does regular studies for BP and
Shell and will be sharing his expertise with leading Papua New Guinea
politicians and civil servants.
He will be helping them to get the maximum benefits from Papua New Guinea's own
promising, but little-tapped, oil and gas reserves, which are dwarfed by
multi-billion pound deals in neighbouring Indonesia and Australia .
It is the biggest contract that his firm, Mackay Consultants, has landed in its
ten-year history.
Mackay Consultants, which has economists working in its offices in Stirling and
Brussels, as well as its Inverness headquarters, will be hiring extra staff for
the contract.
The contract is being funded by the World Bank, and Mr Mackay will be spending
six months based at the capital Port Moresby each year for the next five years.
Mr Mackay, whose family comes from Wick, Caithness, said: ``It will be a most
exciting challenge. I will be giving them advice on on all aspects of their oil
and gas policies, including the terms to be drawn up for new licences to
attract the maxiumum interest from the world's oil companies, while protecting
local interests.''
</TEXT>
