<HEADLINE>Here is the news - from Strathclyde police</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Tom Shields</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Diary</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684318</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Television prides itself on its lean and efficient news machine with a
thrusting young staff at the cutting edge of information and technology. Some
people say it is also very cheap employing weans just out of school to do the
news.
But their rivals were impressed last week at the latest innovation by Scottish
TV. Rival news gatherers at last weekend's re-enactment of a murder in
Kilmarnock were somewhat stunned to see the Scottish TV camera person shoot an
interview with the detective in charge. The difference was that a spokesperson
from Strathclyde police information department was asking the questions on
behalf of Scottish TV.
Well, why not. Just cut out the reporter, that awkward journalist between the
PR department and the interviewee. We wonder what Gus MacDonald, a Glasgow boy
who made his name as a robust investigative reporter on World in Action, would
make of that. Perhaps he should ask Angus J MacDonald, chairman-elect and chief
executive of Scottish TV.
Every little helps
THE Scottish work ethic is alive and well. As evidence we produce Mr Archie
Norman, chief executive of Asda supermarkets. When he is not at his desk or
boardroom table, Mr Norman is to found in one of his many corner shops stacking
shelves.
``He's got us at it too,'' says his PR chief Jennie Cropper when the Diary
enquired about her boss's habit.
Could we have a comment from the boss? ``Don't know where he is. He drops in at
any store he fancies and starts piling up tins,'' said Ms Cropper.
This is an attitude which could usefully be adopted by other leaders of
industry. In fact I have decided to allow Liam Kane, chief executive of The
Herald, to write the Diary over the new year.
Planning ahead
WE are indebted to the horoscope column of the magazine Good Housekeeping for
the advance warning to those of a Virgo disposition that in 1996: ``Uranus will
bring unexpected changes in your working life, which could result in sudden
windfalls.'' See Uranus, see wind?
Now you know
THE Diary does its level best to avoid the super information highway. But more
than one person has been on-line to bring to our attention the bit on the
Internet called FTP. No, the Pope (whom God preserve) is not involved. FTP is
an acronym for file transfer protocol.
Stand by our Dan
LIKE the abattoirs who extract the last brain cell of the cow for use in Scotch
pies, the Diary lets nothing go to waste. Thus we offer the thoughts of one
Josh Billings who writes to us from Los Angeles on the subject of BSE: ``Was
Desperate Dan an original victim of mad cow pie disease? Of immense strength
but unco-ordinated and scared shitless of his mother, could he be the new hero
for the late 1990s? We could talk a deal with Disney: Desperate Dan - The
Movie.''
Get to the point
THERE is this chap called Ewan Cameron in the Glasgow office of Ryden the
property people who keeps sending the Diary sundry sweetmeats in a pathetic
attempt to promote an office block which he is trying to let. First he
delivered a plain loaf, claiming their building was ``the best thing since
sliced bread''.
He followed this up with a miniature of whisky and a lump of coal, inviting us
to be their first foot.
Now he has sent us a slice of toast of a dubious sell-by date and a jar of
Auchentoshan whisky-flavoured marmalade to toast the property. We must advise
Mr Cameron that while his ruses are entertaining, us chaps at the Diary have
much more serious issues to discuss, even at this time of year.
PS - When is the champagne opening?
Only joking
MORE sustenance through the post. Dundee, the city of Discovery, sends us a
dram and a wee slice of their eponymous cake. The downside (there is no such
thing as a free lunch) is that they also send the Dundee factpack.
This factpack includes a section entitled 12 things you didn't know about
Dundee - which doesn't quite match the efforts of this very Diary which once
compiled 800 interesting facts about Clootie City or whatever name is your
preference for the City by the Silvery Tay.
Fact No.1 is that ``Dundee is the sunniest city in Scotland with an average of
3.7 hours of sunshine every day''. This brings to mind the famous Dundee
expression, ``Ah doubt it''.
We are more prepared to believe fact No.4 that ``Dundee is investigating
providing school pupils with nut-free school meals'', but we fear it may be too
late. And fact No.5 that Dundee has more detached homes than the UK average.
After all, who would want to live right next door to someone from Dundee?
Fact No.10 - ``Dundee had the first ring road in Britain'' - is hardly
surprising given that the first prerequisite for a good night out in Clootie
City is finding the road out of town.
Another interesting fact. Dundee lies beneath its very own volcano, the Law
hill. It's extinct, unfortunately.
(Editor's note - only someone who is so fond of Dundee would be allowed to get
away with so many insults about the place.)
</TEXT>
