<HEADLINE>Cut off in their prime</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE WALKER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684320</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE soundtrack of the movie biography of Carlo Broschi, the renowned eighteenth
century castrato singer known as Farinelli, posed a big problem for the sound
engineers.
The early castrati, who were the pop stars of their day, commanding big fees
and celebrity status, came to Italy from Spain in the middle of the sixteenth
century. Writings of the time describe their big muscular physiques, abundant
stamina and the extraordinary lung power which enabled them to perform
astonishing feats of vocal athleticism. The castrati sang the soprano parts in
the Sistine Chapel, where the Catholic Church forbade the presence of women.
Some found lucrative employment at the Medici Court in Florence and a few, like
the Neapolitan Farinelli two centuries later, became opera divas especially in
the Pontifical States and the kingdom of Naples where women were banned from
performing in theatres. The last castrato (and the only one who survives in a
scratchy old recording), Alessandro Moreschi `L'angelo di Roma', died in 1922
and the gory practice of castrating boy sopranos thankfully died with him. So
for film-maker Gerard Corbiau, there was no question of a quick snip.
Farinelli performed the works of his brother, Riccardo Broschi, and of his
mentor Nicola Porpora whose company rivalled Handel's in worldwide fame. All
three composers are featured on this award-winning film soundtrack in which the
powerful and hypnotic sound of Farinelli, spanning the castrati's normal range
of three-and-a-half octaves, actually belongs to two singers: the countertenor
Derek Lee Ragin and the soprano Ewa Malas-Godlewska, whose voices have been
electronically melded.
Ragin recorded his part in Amsterdam and Malas-Godlewska recorded the higher
notes beyond his reach from Switzerland, where she was working. Then the tapes
were sent to IRCAM, Pierre Boulez's sound laboratories at the Georges Pompidou
Centre in Paris, and a musical ``map'' was made of the harmonics before a final
``Farinelli'' voice was blended electronically. It sounds totally convincing,
full of warmth and colour, with hardly a hint of any ``synthesized'' process or
digital fusions, and if you can't catch the elegant film (the blood bath
doesn't last long) the soundtrack Farinelli Il Castrato gives a vivid enough
flavour of Baroque brilliance to be enjoyed independently.
The surprise hit of this year's London Film Festival, Angels &amp; Insects, is a
dark tale of Victorian repression based on the fascinating novella by Booker
prize-winning author, A S Byatt.
An impoverished Northern anthropologist is trapped by marriage in the decaying
ambience of the bizarre Alabaster family, in a world which is beginning to
recognise the impact of Darwin's revolutionary ideas.
In Angels &amp; Insects the Balanescu Quartet, occasionally augmented by guest
players to become the Luminitza Chamber Orchestra, not only plays the score: it
even makes a cameo appearance as musicians in a key dance sequence Waltz.
Balanescu had always intended that the commission should be more than a side
project and after the film recordings the musicians reconvened in the Abbey
Road Studios to develop the music to a point where it could work on its own as
a theme and variations. Even without Mark Rylance and Patsy Kensit as lovers in
a tangled web of mystery and deceit, Kristin Scott Thomas as the creator of the
artificial ant-paradise, and a strong cast that also includes Anna Massey, the
music plays out the story's intricate relationships between the human
characters, in the natural world, and between the angels and the insects.
</TEXT>
