<HEADLINE>Choosing a little light reading</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>book review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684321</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lex Gold, director general, Scottish Chamber of Commerce.
TAKING a break from the excitement of running a business is a great way of
recharging the batteries . . . but for some of us, the festive season can
become a little tedious as we feel that nagging itch to get back into harness.
Give yourself a break. Pick up a book and relax. But which book? Most of us
have our favourites, to be read and re-read and savoured.
Today the review elbows the Business Books to the edge of the shelf and invites
some of its regular contributors to share their thoughts on the lighter
literature that occupies them occasionally. Like all Christmas crackers, there
may be a few surprises in store:
Black Sea by Neal Ascherson, charts the rise and fall of ancient cities, proud
tribes and evil empries. Ascherson wanders through the debris of current
calamities, guided by a wonderful sense of history and journalistic skills that
border on the uncanny. Marabou Stork Nightmares by Irvine Welsh, led me back to
his earlier books Acid House and Trainspotting - and the conclusion that while
the drugs of choice may change, much remains constant in Scottish life.
I have just read Michael Montignac's Dine Out and Lose Weight for the second
time, to reconfirm and enjoy again the knowledge that the worst excess when
dining out is to eat the bread rolls and that a glass of white wine is less
fattening than potatoes or white rice. This book explodes many myths about the
food we eat.
John McClelland, world vice president, Digital Equipment Corporation.
I haven't seen the film . . . but I have read, and thoroughly enjoyed, The
Bridges of Madison County by Robert James Waller. I also re-read The Master of
Ballantrae by R L Stevenson, and can recommend Captain Corellis Mandolin by
Louis de Bernieres.
Nigel Clifford, chief executive, Glasgow Royal Infirmary.
Once you accept the key principle of animals talking to one another The Wolves
of Time by William Horwood proves to be an epic account (first in a trilogy) of
the last few wolves scattered across Europe making their slow and frequently
painful journey back to their ancestral homeland. Set against a background of
environmental pollution and human conflict, this book is much more apocalyptic
than the usual animal tale and has a powerful bite which others in the genre
frequently lack.
Bill Furness, BT national manager for Scotland.
I am cheating . . . the best book I expect to have read all year is one of my
Christmas presents! To Lie with Lions by Dorothy Dunnett is the sixth in her
medieval adventure Niciolo series. Give yourself another treat and read my
all-time favourite - the ``Crawford or Lymond'' series.
Aileen Beattie, director of auditing, Institute of Chartered Accountants of
Scotland.
On a recent flight to the Far East, I thoroughly enjoyed John Fowles' Daniel
Martin. It was a well-constructed novel, and I was left with a pleasurable
feeling of regret on reaching the last page.
Authors who kiss and tell are not really my bag. However, when the story
tellers are Lady Thatcher in The Downing Street Years and John Cole in As It
Seemed to Me that is something else. In the course of describing some of the
most momentous events of recent decades, Cole's inscrutable TV mask of
impartiality falls away. With Lady Thatcher, as always, you get what you see.
The Thatcher version of events benefited from the author actually having been
present on the key occasions and as such, has the greater credibility. At
least, that is how it seemed to me!
I am an addictive reader of Napoleonic naval fiction (and history), having been
brought up on C S Forrester's Hornblower stories, which still repay a second
read. By far the best of his successors in Patrick O'Brian, whose stories of
Jack Aubrey and Stephen Maturin do so much than tell a sea story. His latest is
The Commodore but spend some time reading the whole sequence, from Master and
Commander.
If like me you are looking to escape over the holiday break from the world of
work, why not set yourself the task of reading the Isaac Asimov ``foundation''
series - seven books in all which deal with another time, another place in
which the only thing recognisable is human nature! If you are looking for
something less demanding and funny, how about Drop The Dead Donkey 2000, a very
clever adaptation of the Channel 4 comedy series which I guarantee will be more
than watching reruns of 1970s comedy shows on the TV over the festive period.
Philip H Miller, managing director, Miller Developments.
Julian Critchley's dry, self depreciating humour is infectious. A Bag Of Boiled
Sweets is sharp, pitchy, illuminating and packed with political insight. He has
occupied a unique place at Westminster for more than two decades, and appeals
to that basic human instinct to read gossip about the all-powerful. Who could
not like a man who disarmingly quotes Orwell on autobiography: ``A man who
gives a good account of himself is probably lying, since any life, when viewed
from the inside, is simply a series of defeats.''
Mike Shaw, commissioning producer, BBC Radio Scotland.
q Book Review is complied and edited by Stuart Paul of the University of Paisley
</TEXT>
