<HEADLINE>REGULATION Ex-banker urges financial services shake-up</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684322</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORMER Bank of England official today called for a complete overhaul of the
UK's financial services regulatory system.
Mr Michael Taylor, formerly of the Bank's supervision division, criticised by
politicians over the collapse of Barings and the Bank of Credit and Commerce
International, said the present system had become unwieldy and ineffective.
Writing in a paper published by the Centre for the Study of Financial
Innovations, a non-profit think-tank, he proposed the establishment of two new
commissions to take over supervision of the industry from the Bank, the
Securities and Investment Board, the City of London's top watchdog, and other
regulatory bodies.
Under his twin peaks strategy, there would be a Financial Stability Commission
which would have responsibility for the soundness of the financial system in
all its aspects - banks, building societies, investment, insurance and
wholesale financial markets.
A Consumer Protection Commission would oversee conduct of business in the
retail markets.
The two commissions would be separate and independent but could co-operate
closely and share a number of commissioners.
If they came into conflict, disputes could be resolved by the Treasury, said Mr
Taylor.
The paper said the new structure would clarify the aims of financial regulation.
At present, it was not clear, for example, whether the Bank's main role was to
promote financial stability or protect investors, aims which often conflicted.
Mr Taylor now runs a degree course in financial regulation at London Guildhall
University.
</TEXT>
