<HEADLINE>Royal Highland Show orders worth #80m</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684323</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SURVEY conducted by an independent research company as visitors left this
year's Royal Highland Show has confirmed the event's standing as one of the
major agricultural trade shows in Europe, writes Robert Ross.
The profile of the farmer-visitors showed that half of them came from farms of
more than 250 hectares. A total of 63% of all farmers who visited the show said
that they had considered purchases - mainly of machinery.
About #7.3m was actually spent at the show and decisions were taken during the
show period to spend an estimated #80m. In addition more than #3m was spent on
general purchases at the show.
The report also dispels the perception that farmers attend almost exclusively
on the first two days of the four-day show.
On the Thursday 39% of the 31,000 visitors were farmers and even on the final
day - generally regarded as a ``family day'' - 20% of the 47,600 attending were
from the farming community.
The total number of farmers and land industry professionals attending the show
has increased since the last survey, conducted in 1992.
Mr Hywel Davies, chief executive of the Royal Highland and Agricultural
Society, said: ``This is an endorsement of the society's policy of making the
show a business event, and not one only for farmers but also for others with
responsibility for managing the countryside and rural resources.'' The exit
survey also established that 72% of visitors could be classified as ``affluent,
economically active decison makers'' - cited by the RHASS as evidence that
taking trade space at the show repreented a worthwhile investment.
Visitors were generally satisfied with the standard of services provided at the
show although criticisms were made of lack of seating and signposting around
the ground. The society has plans to spend up to #16,000 resolving these
particular criticisms for the 1996 show.
Mr Hywel Davies said: ``The importance of the Highland Show as an international
market place for Scottish agriculture is confirmed by this survey.
``We will continue to work for the future of Scotland's land based industries
by improving the facilities, the content of the show and the way in which we
inform the general public about agriculture.''
</TEXT>
