<HEADLINE>RETAIL TRADE Snow boosts convenience stores</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684324</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONVENIENCE stores are benefiting from the snow storms which have brought
misery to thousands of Scots.
On a like-for-like basis, Dundee-based convenience stores chain Morning Noon &amp;
Night has enjoyed an 11.5% rise in festive sales.
When the sales of the rapidly-expanding chain's most recent acquisitions were
taken into account, turnover in the week to Christmas Eve was up 32% on last
year.
Chief executive Eddie Thompson yesterday attributed the increase in sales to
poor weather conditions and the change in Scotland's Sunday licensing laws.
Because Christmas Day fell on a Sunday last year, when shops were closed,
Morning Noon &amp; Night's 25 outlets reaped festive benefit from the licensing
change for the first time this year.
In the North-east and far North of Scotland, which both had heavy snow
throughout much of last week, Mr Thompson believes that people reverted to
their local stores for items forgotten during their supermarket shopping
expeditions.
</TEXT>
