<HEADLINE>It's easy going for a song</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TIM DE LISLE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684325</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Face the music: TIM DE LISLE lists 10 ways to write a great song
PEOPLE say that everybody has a novel in them, but it seems much more likely
that everybody has a song in them. Novels are long and complicated and
effortful. Songs are short and simple and - well, if not effortless, certainly
a lot easier than novels.
While writing a great book tends to be a lot harder than writing a lousy one,
writing a great song is much like writing any other song. And there are many
different ways of doing it . . .
n Dream it
THIS is the easiest way of the lot. The only conscious effort required is
keeping a tape-recorder by the bed. One morning in 1965, Paul McCartney woke up
at his girlfriend Jane Asher's parents' flat in Wimpole Street with a tune in
his head. He called it Scrambled Eggs and the next line was ``Oh my darling
you've got lovely legs.''
The tune was so complete, he thought it must be someone else's, and sang it to
people to see if they recognised it. ``Eventually it became like handing
something into the police,'' he said. ``If no-one claimed it after a few weeks,
I would have it.'' He changed its name to Yesterday and it is now probably the
most-recorded song in history, with 2000 versions.
This sounds like a total fluke. But a few months later, at a motel in
Clearwater, Florida, the same thing happened to Keith Richards. He woke up in
the middle of the night, picked up a guitar, switched on a tape-recorder and
played the most famous riff in rock: the first five notes of (I Can't Get No)
Satisfaction. Then he went back to sleep.
n Overhear it
THIS one isn't hard either. The words to A Whiter Shade of Pale, by Procol
Harum, were written by Keith Reid. He had gone to a party given by record
producer Guy Stevens and his wife Diane in Gloucester Avenue NW1. At one point
Stevens said to Diane: ``My God you've just turned a whiter shade of pale.''
(This was to be expected in 1967.) After that, all Reid had to do was add a few
lines about light fandangos and vestal virgins, and get Gary Brooker to come up
with a variation on Bach's Air on the G-String.
n Translate it
ONE of the great ballads of the pre-rock era is Autumn Leaves, recorded by
Sinatra, Bing Crosby, and all the usual suspects. They probably wouldn't have
touched it if it had remained Les Fuilles Mortes, by Jacques Prvert. Written
in 1945, it was translated a decade later by Johnny Mercer, a Tin Pan Alley
craftsman who went on to write Moon River.
n Make a list
LIST songs make the same point again and again, with different examples.
They're easy, and fun, to write, because of all the proper names you can use.
The master of this art was Cole Porter, whose lyric for You're the Top reads
like a travel brochure: ``You're the top!/You're the Coliseum /You're the
top!/You're the Louvre Museum.''
n Ask a lot of questions
BLOWIN' in the Wind, by the young Bob Dylan, is dead simple - a folk tune, with
no bridge or middle eight. Its distinction lies in a series of nine
metaphorical questions: ``How many roads must a man walk down/Before you call
him a man?'' The only statement in the song is the answer, which, my friend, is
blowin' in the wind.
n Compose an irritating ditty and leave the rest to fate
WHEN The Sound of Music opened on Broadway, in 1959, My Favourite Things was
probably rated great only by Richard Rodgers, Oscar Hammerstein II, and any
surviving governess. Greatness was thrust upon it, for reasons that remain
obscure, by John Coltrane, the jazz saxophonist. He kept on recording it, and
each time it strayed further from the nursery. In the end it was not
unrecognisable as My Favourite Things, it was barely recognisable as jazz.
n Keep it simple
MOST great songs are straightforward and none more so than You Send Me by Sam
Cooke. It has only one verse, of four lines, and the chorus can't have taken
too long either: ``You send me,'' it goes, ``you thrill me. Honest you do.''
Admittedly, it helps if you have a voice as grainily gorgeous as Cooke's.
n Strike a bet
SOME of the best pop lyrics have an odd thing in common: they included one
long, incongruous, unmusical word. It's as if someone had bet the authors that
they couldn't fit the word in.
In My Funny Valentine, the word is ``unphotographical'', which the lyricist
Lorenz Hart suavely uses as a whole line, just after ``Your looks are
laughable.''
n Steer clear of rhymes
THE Stevie Wonder song most often heard in hotel bars is You Are The Sunshine
Of My Life. You won't find many rhymes in it. ``You are the sunshine of my
life,'' it goes, ``That's why I'll always be around.''
Behind the lack of rhyme is no lack of reason. The obvious rhyme for ``life''
was ``wife''. The snag was that the song was (allegedly) addressed not to the
then Mrs Wonder, Syreeta Wright, but to a backing singer called Gloria Barley -
you can hear her on You Are The Sunshine Of My Life.
n Borrow a riff, and a slogan
ONE of the few unmistakable classics of the 1990s is Smells Like Teen Spirit by
Nirvana. It's crunching riff is strangely reminiscent of More Than A Feeling by
Boston, a band as unfashionable as Nirvana were cool. Once the late Kurt Cobain
had seen a TV commercial for a deodorant called Teen Spirit, the riff soon lost
the whiff of old fart.
n All the songs discussed here are featured in Lives of the Great Songs, edited
by Tim de Lisle (Penguin, #6.99).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
