<HEADLINE>Those falling spirits</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KENNEDY WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684326</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SYMBOLS of luxury throughout the world, France's most distinguished distilled
drinks, cognac and armagnac, are in commercial peril. This winter's rail and
public transport strikes have made it unusually difficult to supply the spirits
to shops and taken the edge off many people's appetite for celebration. But the
underlying problem is one of falling consumption at home and abroad - four
consecutive years of declining sales, linked to economic recession worldwide.
Although sales in 1994 increased a little by comparison with 1993, the
producers are afraid that foreign buyers could lose the taste for brandy if the
slump lasts.
In the autumn, brandy producers in the normally conservative areas of Cognac,
in the west of France, and Armagnac, close to the Spanish border, lobbied the
Minister of Agriculture for financial support and even took to the streets of
the town of Cognac to protest about their plight.
Government help was refused, however, and Agriculture Minister Philippe Vasseur
angered both local distillers and vineyard owners who provide wine for brandy,
by advising them to diversify their production.
In 1994, 147 million bottles of cognac were produced. Almost 95% worth around
#1.4 billion were exported. The United States and Canada bought nearly 28
million bottles, while the European and Asian markets absorbed 67 and 50
million respectively.
North American and British consumption of brandy has dropped by almost half
over the past eight years. Sales in Japan, where almost as much cognac is drunk
every year as in the US and Canada, have increased by around 12% during the
same period, but slumped by a quarter in Germany, another major client.
The French themselves, meanwhile, just seem to be going off brandy. Producers
blame recent legislation aimed at curbing publicity for alcohol, competition
from the lower quality, lower-priced spirits in supermarkets as well as from
distilled drinks such as whisky, vodka and gin, which are becoming increasingly
popular.
As a result, some 338 million litres of cognac, several years' production, are
having to be stored in cellars in their oak casks or, in a case of fully
matured spirit, in glass containers kept away from daylight, for the day when
sales will pick up.
Sales of armagnac, meanwhile, have dropped by 35% over the past five years.
Producers who have been forced to stock more than 22 million litres are
complaining of a vicious circle of falling consumption and the expense of long
storage, which can only increase prices.
Distillers blame wine growers for contributing to the glut by producing too
much wine. Wine growers on the other hand complained that big distillers, many
of which have been taken over by multinational companies, are more interested
in promoting foreign spirits which they import, especially whisky, at the
expense of their home-grown tipple. Everybody complains about the effect on
home consumption of heavy taxes, which represent 45% of the price of a bottle
of brandy.
As we stock up
on Hogmanay bottles,
KENNEDY WILSON
looks at how the
French are alarmed by
a cognac slump
</TEXT>
