<HEADLINE>You're never too old to make a splash</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anvar Khan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684327</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
She's a goer, a trier, and a doer - and she's `about 75'.
Anvar Khan catches up with Betty Paton for whom life began again at 60
I WAS alerted to the achievements of Betty Paton of Faifley via a phone call
from one of her friends, a Mary Black from Clydebank. ``She does everything,''
said Mary of her best pal. ``She was the Scottish fencing champion, she goes
canoeing, she spent last Christmas on the sands of Oban.'' Doing what?
``Surfing. And she can do 13 Eskimo rolls in a oner.'' And how old is she?
``About 75.''
There are very few ordinary people who will be remembered by so many.
Immortality is the preserve of the famous, the propagation of a life, an
official duty of the chattering classes. It's important to look at death if you
want to talk about life, especially in Betty's case. Death gets things in
perspective. Some of us would like an extra 20 years for each good deed, others
are quite happy for them to be chalked up on the big blackboard in the sky.
Betty Paton is a woman, perhaps, who thinks it unbearable that the quality of a
life lived has no bearing on the date of the great departure.
Her transition into her most active years, as an OAP, began when her mum, dad,
and husband died within 18 months of each other. She had nursed her parents in
her own home. ``It went quiet,'' she says. ``I didn't know what to do.
``I had a brother; he died five years ago. I had a sister; she was 27 when she
died. My father had cancer and my mum died from missing my father. She was
supposed to have died of old age but she was only 69.''
Some say that death is the greatest equaliser, but they're wrong. Ministers and
Priests tell you it's this journey that influences the next. But people aren't
born equal, they don't get the same opportunities or talents, they won't
equally be remembered when they've gone, and they are not equally treated when
they live or when they die. Some get big graves some get cheap ones, and, if
you are a believer, some go to heaven while others go to hell. There's a
genuine unfairness about existence and existing, all the way.
Betty says: ``When I was young, girls learned to knit and sew, go to church. I
was a Sunday School teacher, but when I went outdoors during the weekends,
church had to stop.''
The world closes in on single, elderly women. The British OAP can lead a silent
life, a trip to the local shops can span a whole day. ``I don't know why I'm so
active'' Betty pauses. ``Sometimes I think, oh, I need a stretch'' and to
illustrate she jumps up from her chair and hangs like a orang-utang from the
threshold of the kitchenette door. Betty says she's not competitive, but she
performs when she has a point to prove.
``I started competitive fencing in 1977, and that was only to justify the work
the tutor was putting in for me.'' She was 57. ``The club became good enough to
enter competitions. In fencing there is a snob factor, and our coach was a cab
driver, while other coaches were university graduates, doctors, and lawyers. We
were poo-pooed because we were working class. We came through it, but the
prejudice gave me the edge.''
Her long-term pal and voluntary media adviser, Mary Black, also told me that
when Betty decided to take up canoeing she met with a bad attitude. Something
about a ``po-faced lot from Jordanhill'' looking down on this ``wee old woman
with specs and a hearing aid''.
But Betty is a goer, a trier, and a doer. She bestows support and leadership
upon a legion of local residents and friends, organising hill-walking
expeditions from Rowardennan, to Inverbeg and Crianlarich. She is at present
studying history ``between the wars'', but the class is going to fold, she
says, because people ``keep dropping off''. At the age of 75, colleagues
``dropping-off'' is a real hazard, and there are few peers left with whom Betty
can compete. Betty likes to beat those younger than her, people of 72 for
example. She recently broke a record held by the Clydebank Ladies Swimming
League, founded many years ago, in which she was a member. She shows me her
awards. ``These are all for being the best in an age group, mine is 75-79. I
like to earn them.'' What she means is that at her age they tend to give you a
gong just for managing to turn up.
It wasn't just the effort to fill her time which propelled Betty into sporting
activity at the age of 60. She tried to be an old person. She tried ``sitting
there, in classes at the local community education centre, doing the stuff that
old people do, making dough things, making paper mache things, then the woman
in charge said, `Let's make some Christmas tree decorations now.' I thought,
`My grandchildren are over 20, I don't want this!'''
She shows me an album which records favourite events; I can see her surfing in
Bute, in a wet suit in Oban, and hanging from a wire, walking her body from one
edge of the river Orchy to the other, a vision in rubber above the rapids.
``I'm sensible about sport, I don't do bungee-jumping,'' she says, quite
seriously. ``I couldn't do parachuting now, because of my arthritic knee. I
love canoeing, but I don't do white-water rafting, my reactions are slowing
down and you need a fast reaction on water.'' She adds, ``You get a nice high
after a swimming training session though.''
But Paton inspires her friends' love and respect. When she abseiled down the
black hole stairwell of Glasgow's Hospitality Inn last month she raised #400
for Help The Aged. ``Ooh, a fortnight later I did it twice,'' she shines.
``They invited me back.'' She plans another abseil for charity down the
stairwell of Glasgow's Central Hotel on St Valentine's Day. She has no fear.
Unlike even some younger women, she doesn't see herself as prey. ``I'm not
afraid of going out at night. I've attended self-defence classes and you must
walk assertively: if you're easy meat, that's when they'll attack.''
Fit people never entertain physical vulnerability. Betty Paton does not want to
be treated as a decrepit now, as a grandmother (she has one daughter), just as
she despised it then, when it was punishment for being a girl.
``I met my husband in 1943. I was 23 and in the WAF. He was a soldier and he
was called up to India. We had to make a decision and were married in three
days. I remember the minister went to the church door and addressed the
pavement - ``Would everybody stop please?'' - and he read the bands from
there.'' Any decision worth making, you spend seconds on it rather than days.
``I would have loved to have gone abroad then too, but only nurses were
allowed. But after I retired I did ballroom and Latin American dancing, and I
got up to gold, and then I went into teaching it. With the swimming I've been
to Australia in 1986, Denmark in 1988, Paris in 1993, where I got two gold
medals.''
By the way, Betty also knits, paints, and sings. ``It's taking advantage of
what's being offered to you,'' she says. ``A lot of people hee and haw and then
it's too late.'' Then again, maybe it never really is.
</TEXT>
