<TEXT>
GOLF
THE inaugural Southern Open championship, to be played at Southerness next
season on dates still to be confirmed, will have the Edinburgh-based Carnegie
Sports Management as a major sponsor. Neil Simpson, the PGA Scottish region's
secretary, is involved in talks with local companies, trying to enlist their
support in establishing the tournament, the first over 72 holes to be taken to
the south-west.
Although the links on the Solway Firth, where the Scottish Amateur championship
was held last summer for the second time, is the best-regarded course in the
area, the likelihood is that the tournament, in which 144 players will start
after a qualifyng round and a pro-am competition, will be taken to other
venues, as has been done annually in the long-established Northern Open.
q.IN what may be a golfing first, two Nevada golfers recorded holes-in-one on
consecutive shots. John Legarza, 60, and Tom Gabelman, 59, delivered aces on
the 162-yard, par-3 sixteenth hole last week at the Dayton Valley Country Club
using a No.5 and No.4 iron respectively.
</TEXT>
