<HEADLINE>Jack Frost wins as Thistle forget to turn up the heat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR Chief Sports writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684330</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNDERSOIL heating is the answer to the Scottish weather, absolutely no doubt
about it. Basically, all you have to do once the system has been installed is
flip a switch or two, sit back and watch the festive movies.
The snow can tumble all night, but the players from clubs with the underground
works don't need to care. They know when they arrive next day all will be well.
The game will go on . . . unless it is scheduled for Firhill.
Partick Thistle's people arrived at their ground yesterday morning ready for
action, but recoiled in disbelief when they saw, or rather couldn't see, the
pitch. It was somewhere under four to five inches of snow.
It turned out that while the heating system had been switched on it was not
left at the proper level - times are hard in football, but surely this was not
a cost-cutting exercise - and the snow was able to settle and pack. A referee
was called in and, although the ground was soft enough underneath, there was
too much of the white stuff lying on top and Hibernian were told not to bother
leaving the capital.
``We were all very disappointed,'' said Partick Thistle secretary Robert Reid.
``The matter will be looked into.''
Oh dear, sounds like officialese for ``somebody is about to get his backside
kicked.''
Hibs manager Alex Miller might want to come through to Maryhill and punish the
culprit himself, because if the match had gone ahead he would have had at least
one of his his suspended players available for Saturday's game against Rangers
at Ibrox. Michael O'Neill's ban would have ended yesterday, but now he will
complete the punishment by watching the Rangers game from the stand.
Celtic also might be starting to worry, because two of their players, Peter
Grant and John Hughes, would have completed their three-game bans had
yesterday's match against Raith Rovers beaten the weather. Now Tommy Burns must
hope his team's match at Tynecastle goes ahead on Saturday, otherwise Grant,
who has already missed one game against Rangers because of suspension, and
Hughes will sit out out the January 3 Old Firm game at Celtic Park. Both can be
influential players and Burns will want them available.
It isn't just managers who dislike postponements, however, because club
directors also get annoyed when their home games are called off. Most clubs
need the revenue and matters are made worse when the electricity bill runs up
overnight for no useful purpose.
Thistle's match was only one of 19 games postponed over the Christmas period
and most were rescheduled yesterday for the first available midweek - Tuesday,
January 9 and the following evening - although Thistle won't benefit. Hibs have
already been booked for the satellite television game against Aberdeen at
Pittodrie on Monday, January 8.
This means Falkirk, who were supposed to play Aberdeen yesterday, also will be
idle that midweek. Their premier division match against the Dons, and also the
one between Thistle and Hibs, have been rescheduled for the following midweek,
Tuesday, January 16.
Raith Rovers' game against Celtic will be played on Tuesday, January 9, and
Hearts and Motherwell will meet on Wedneday, January 10.
The Scottish League moved quickly yesterday to reschedule games - it truly is
amazing what these people can achieve when they go to work - and in the first
division the Clydebank v Airdrie fixture, which last Saturday was postponed for
the third time, hopefully will be played on January 9. Apart from the weather
the re-arranged matches in the lower divisions could also be affected by
replays in the Tennents Scottish Cup, which begins to get serious on Saturday,
January 6.
If any of the ties that day are drawn they will, as cup-ties usually do, take
precedence over league matches and be replayed the following midweek. Other
rescheduled matches are:
First division - Airdrie v St Mirren, Clydebank v Dundee, both January 16;
Dumbarton v Dunfermline, St Johnstone v Morton, January 9.
Second division - Ayr United v Clyde, Forfar v East Fife, both January 9; Queen
of the South v Stenhousemuir, Stranraer v Berwick Rangers, both January 10.
Third division - Albion Rovers v Caley (postponed from Saturday, December 23,)
Brechin City v Alloa, Cowdenbeath v East Stirling, all January 9; Livingston v
Queen's Park, Ross County v Arbroath, both January 10.
</TEXT>
