<HEADLINE>Not the ticket</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684331</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOLLOWING the draw in Birmingham for the finals of Euro '96, I was disappointed
to discover that only 7000 of Wembley Stadium's 70,000-plus capacity had been
allocated to supporters of Scotland for the match against the Auld Enemy on
June 15 next year.
Glen Kirton, of Euro '96, stated that Scotland are only ``one of 16 teams''
competing in the championships and, as such, would be given no special
treatment.
It would be interesting to learn how many tickets have been allocated to fans
of England, the host nation (but still only one of 16 competing teams), for the
aforementioned match.
David Jardine,
11 Cassalands,
Dumfries.
</TEXT>
