<HEADLINE>Smooth lines of torque</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>roat tests</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684332</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE only mistake I made when driving the Citroen Xantia 1.8 16-valve was to
take it to the press launch of a new car of a different make. Although it had
the benefit of being much more recently off the drawing board, the other car
could not hold a candle to the Xantia in terms of ride quality. In fact, the
difference was almost embarrassing, when it came to chatting with the rival
manufacturer's representatives.
All cars date, some more quickly than others, and some companies have
particular features of their designs which keep in the top rank while the car
in general fades in appeal. As far as its mid and upper-range models are
concerned, Citroen has been going its own individual hydro-pneumatic suspension
way for more than 40 years, and by no means all of the opposition has caught up.
There are other cars in its class which handle more sportingly, and Citroen has
never quite managed to figure out how to stop the interlinked suspension
kicking the tail up over a hump-backed bridge. But the suspension system which
was tried out in a few of the ``Maigret'' Citroens, before really coming to the
fore in the DS19, can smooth out road surface bumps and ripples like nothing
else at the Xantia's size and price.
Another feather in the Xantia's cap is that it continues to look remarkably
fresh. On many cars in its class, the critical observer can see little gauche
elements of styling, or places where unnecessary ornamentation might be
removed, but Citroen has created a simple, attractive, uncluttered Xantia line.
The company's basic engine range is fairly old, and this is another area in
which you simply cannot hold back the tide of progress. All-new engine ranges
come along very rarely, and are phenomenally expensive. It is not unheard-of
for what is fundamentally the same engine to last in production for 30 years
and more. Regular up-datings help the situation, but eventually nothing can
stop an engine feeling past its sell-by date.
Citroen's major change in 1995 was introducing 16-valve heads to the 1.8 and
two-litre Xantia models. These have made a considerable difference to the
engines' performance, economy and throttle response. The 112bhp multi-valve 1.8
will sprint a manual transmission Xantia to 60mph in 10 seconds, waft it on to
a test track 120mph, and give far better mid-range performance than the older
eight-valve, thanks to meatier and better distributed torque.
It tends to irritate some of the anti-car lobby that a more powerful engine is
often a more economical one, but better engine efficiency improves things all
round. The 1.8 multi-valve manages about 47mpg at 56mph, 38 at 75 and 27 on the
urban cycle.
While these are not class-leading figures, they are above the 1800 norm.
Showroom prices for the 1.8-litre manual transmission Xantia are #13,080 for
the LX and #14,750 for the SX which comes with ABS as standard. One feature of
the Xantia is that it is roomier inside than a glance at its apparently low
build suggests, and it has a sensible luggage volume.
The current fascia is neatly laid out, although still with that rather annoying
passenger's grab handle which cuts into shelf space. Citroen goes to far
greater pains than previously to keep down interior noise levels, and a few 400
or 500-mile motorway days proved how effective its sound-deadening work has
been. While some other drivers feel the lack of back and thigh support, my own
eccentric driving posture, which a colleague has likened to driving from the
rear seat floor, suited the Xantia well enough.
Ross Finlay drives a Citroen that has stayed fresh
</TEXT>
