<HEADLINE>Macfies aim to reverse trend</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684333</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH champion Senga Macfie and her sister and fellow internationalist,
Helen, are set to reverse the trend by moving from London to Scotland in a bid
to further their squash careers.
The London-born pair, who played for England as juniors, have family in
Edinburgh, and are making plans to establish a base there within the next
couple of months.
While all the Scottish men have headed to England on turning professional,
Senga is convinced that the reverse turn could be just the ticket to revitalise
her career.
Once ranked as high as No.12, she has slipped one place to No.22 in the latest
world rankings, and has already made her new year resolution: to get into a
training routine that will help her regain a place in the top 16.
``In London, I have no organised practice pattern,'' she explained. ``I feel I
am just drifting along at the moment, and I reckon the change could be just
what I need to get going again.
``I know I should be higher in the world rankings. It's a case of working
harder, and getting into a routine.''
Winning her first Scottish championship earlier this month was a huge boost for
the 27-year-old, and she is now hopeful that she can make her mark in the
British National championships in Birmingham next month, an event in which she
is seeded in the 5/8 bracket.
``I want to keep playing full-time for at least another few years,'' she
continued. ``I'm sure a move to Edinburgh would be good for me, and that I
would find plenty of practice partners.''
For 25-year-old Helen, who was also a member of Scotland's European
Championship bronze medals team last season, the latter half of this year has
been ruined by glandular fever.
However, she has now been passed fully fit, although the illness forced her to
pull out of the Scottish Championships.
She also wants to make her name as a full-time player, and could make a start
to her comeback at the next Scottish Grand Prix ranking event, the Edinburgh
Sports Club Open, which takes place from January 19 to 21.
SQUASH
</TEXT>
