<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The true art of conservatism</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Fry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974684334</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT may seem like whistling in the dark to claim that 1995 has been a good year
for conservatives, yet I think there are sound reasons for saying so. The main
one is that nobody, but nobody, neither at home nor abroad, neither in the East
nor in the West, in any ivory tower or think-tank or assembly of the great and
good, has come up with an agenda which can match in coherence or conviction the
one which conservatives have actually set for the world in the past quarter of
the twentieth century.
Of course, conservative parties in power do have their little local
difficulties and, heaven knows, as in Britain has enough of them, most of its
own making. The fact remains that in practically all the major countries
conservatives are indeed in power.
Even where that is not strictly true, conservatives make the running. The
United States has a Democratic President, but a Republican Congress which has
taken over the direction of domestic affairs, while he wanders around the world
bringing peace to everyone. This is a commendable separation of powers, even if
it leaves Bill Clinton with nothing to say on the big issues which actually
concern Americans. But since he has nothing to say anyway, it may be all to the
good.
Where conservatives are right out, or have never been in, the same thing holds.
Ruling parties of other complexions, from Mexico to Spain to Russia to India to
New Zealand, struggle to catch up with the conservative agenda, to absorb,
master, and apply it. They roll back the state, they tear down barriers to
trade, they liberalise, they privatise.
The same thing holds even where conservatives have been around a little too
long, now grow tired, carry the millstones of their mistakes round their necks,
and so face the threat of going out. Power is sweet, and to lose it is bitter.
Still, conservatives should never mind too much, because conservatism is not
absolutist but goes along with the ebb and flow of events.
The British Conservative Party, the prime example in this category, has, after
all, been around for three centuries. In the 95 years of this century it has
been in Government for all but 30. At the end of the century - as I am sure
will be true at the end of history, too - it is seen to have been right.
Britain's great experiment during the century has been with socialism or at
least collectivism. It was a legitimate experiment, which conservatives anyway
did not oppose in every jot and tittle, and in a few respects it produced some
useful results. But overall it did not work. For its own good a complex society
must avoid placing itself in the hands of mad scientists. They will always go
too far, and ours did.
In sending them packing, Britain performed a service not only for herself but
for the world. At the global level, too, the great experiment of the twentieth
century has been at least with collectivism, and more especially with socialism
in a precisely conceived sense - all power to the state, and to the mad
scientists who worked for it or in some cases actually ran it.
Even then, going along with the ebb and flow, conservatives often gave a
hearing to what they had to say, being in the end the most reasonable of men.
If anything they were too fair and, perhaps, for longer than they should have,
they did not care to fight socialism or collectivism hard enough.
But there were always sticking points. The outstanding contribution of Mrs
Margaret Thatcher, President Ronald Reagan, and of others in the conservative
roll of honour, was to say that they should no longer be just sticking points.
They should not be a mere minimum that no democracy should give up, but a
maximum, the measure of everything else.
What were those sticking points? One was the security of the state, rather
different from the state security beloved of the mad scientists. In its
methods, not its aims, it could demand policies almost as unpleasant, however.
For Britain it meant maintaining a nuclear deterrent, occasionally even
fighting wars. But it succeeded. The deterrent deterred, foes were faced down
or if necessary beaten and now, for the first time in centuries, Britain really
has no external enemy.
A second sticking point was the freedom of the individual. If collectivism had
produced some useful results it had also exacted a price, trying to do too
much, the state did too many things badly and so it self-generated social
tension and disorder.
Then it imposed high taxes and coercive laws in a vain effort to suppress them.
By 1979 the choice was clear, either more of the same, with no guarantee of a
better outcome, or less, letting individuals do what they want rather than
being ordered about by politicians and bureaucrats.
Are there any more conservative sticking points? Well, no. So long as the state
is secure and individuals are free, things can be left to run on much as they
will. Corrections and adjustments are required from time to time. Sometimes
they bring the security of the state and the freedom of the individual into
conflict. But, unlike in socialist systems, this conflict is not necessary. The
true art of conservative politics is to avoid it.
It can be done, and on the whole we living in the western countries under
conservative governments during the final quarter of the twentieth century do
it rather well.
The proof of that lies in the fact that anti-conservatives do not propose to do
it differently or, if they do, have no coherent plan to follow. Should Tony
Blair replace John Major before long, policy will in broad terms remain the
same. The conservative agenda is still there. Conservatives can be happy about
1995 and, whatever befalls, confident about 1996.
</TEXT>
