<HEADLINE>SNFU considers special needs of Shetland farmers Union to decide on assistance call</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684335</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FARMERS and crofters in Shetland - where the islands council yesterday declared
a state of emergency - have been among the worst hit by severe winter
conditions over the Christmas holiday period.
Mr John Ross, president of the National Farmers Union of Scotland, will decide
today if there is a need to call for special assistance from the Scottish
Office.
Union office bearers and staff on Shetland spent yesterday checking with
farmers on how severely stock has been affected by the exceptional weather
conditions. In the light of their reports Mr Ross will decide if the situation
merits calling for special help from the Scottish Office in getting fodder
supplies to remote areas.
The worst affected part of Shetland mainland was in the the north where there
were reports of drifts up to 11ft deep. Mr Ross said that he had one report
from the NFU Shetland area president, Mr Addie Doull, who farms at the north
end of the Shetland mainland. Yesterday was the first day since Saturday that
he had been able to venture out at all.
``It was just too dangerous to contemplate leaving the house,'' said Mr Ross.
``It is only now that Addie and others in a similar position will be able to
assess their situation.
``I have asked him to phone round his area and determine how serious the
problems are. In the light of these reports I will decide if there should be
concern for animal welfare with regard to sheep in particular and livestock
generally.''
Mr Ross said that the NFU area secretary on Shetland, Margaret Farquhar, had
been alerted to be on stand-by ready to co-ordinate any emergency measures. The
SSPCA in Shetland were also being kept informed.
Mr David Nicolson, NFUS crofting convener, who lives between Sumburgh and
Lerwick, said that for the south of the Shetland mainland yesterday was their
best day since the weekend.
His son had managed out for the first time to check sheep on the hill. ``We are
trying to get hay out as best we can,'' he said. The farming pattern on
Shetland meant that there were a lot of hill sheep and sheep kept on common
grazings and it was proving difficult to get out to them.
In the Grampian area, which was also badly affected by severe weather, the
police said that they had had no reports of stock in difficulties.
``I think animals are more sensible than humans - they tend to find a safe
place and stay put until conditions improve,'' said a spokesman and police
headquarters in Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
