<HEADLINE>Brewster to the rescue after Renicks' glorious opener Hamilton just fail to cause an upset</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684336</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Dundee United 1, Hamilton 1
BASEMENT outfit Hamilton almost produced a David against Goliath victory to
warm the chill on Tayside as Iain Munro's visitors upset the odds in
yesterday's first division meeting.
A crowd of 6109 braved the sub-zero temperatures, but only those sporting the
Accies colours warmed to matters at the close of play.
A sparkling strike from visiting defender Steve Renicks contributed to the warm
glow surrounding the visiting support, his sixty-fifth minute highlight from 30
yards entering the list of candidates for goal of the season.
Accies, however, failed to follow up on that success by allowing their hosts to
spring back into the contest inside three minutes.
Had the visitors managed to stick in and contain an increasingly frenzied and
annoyed United, then an even bigger form book shock may well have been on the
cards as Billy Kirkwood's side grew in frustration the longer the contest
progressed.
United were again thankful to the scoring talents of striker Craig Brewster who
latched on to a head flick from substitute Owen Coyle off a Jim Bett free kick
to fire home the equaliser.
Mind you, judging by the territorial advantage they held throughout the
proceedings, the leveller was no more than United deserved on an afternoon when
they huffed and puffed without ever threatening to blow down the strongly-build
Accies' house.
Renicks, later to become his side's goal hero, was a defender supreme during
the early stages dominated by the home side, the full back booting clear from
under his own crossbar after Brian Welsh's header appeared net-bound off Andy
McLaren's corner.
Then, minutes prior to the interval, was another goal-line clearance, this time
executed by Chris Hillcoat, who stopped Gary McSwegan's header, again off a
McLaren cross.
Renicks was at it again, six minutes from the end, when completing his second
goal-line clearance of the afternoon by nodding clear another effort from Welsh.
In between times it proved to be the all-round excellence of the visiting
rearguard which held the key to the affair, central defender Crawford Baptie
and co. handling everything that the hosts could throw at them in a display
ready made to convince manager Munro he is on the right lines in his plans.
The visitors' refused to give United time on the ball in the vital midfield
department, an area in which Jim Bett recently has been ruling with something
more than a bit of flourish.
Thus deprived, United resorted to firing balls forward from back to front, thus
eliminating what has in recent weeks been their major asset. In short, they
were out-thought in terms of tactics.
United did, however, have outstanding performers in Steve Pressley and Maurice
Malpas, and it is no coincidence on a day when they failed to contrive scoring
opportunities that both are defenders.
The outcome meant that the Tayside outfit reduced the points gap between
themselves and leaders Dunfermline to only two, while Accies, despite their
heroics, still failed to relinquish their bottom of the table spot - still a
point adrift of second bottom Dumbarton.
Three players were booked in the contest, home man Jim Bett and visitors Jim
Sherry and Jose Quitongo.
DUNDEE UNITED - Maxwell, Shannon, Malpas, Pressley, Welsh, Bett, Winters,
Johnson, McSwegan, Brewster, McLaren. Substitutes - Coyle, Dailly, Hannah.
HAMILTON - Ferguson, Hillcoat, Renicks, McStay, Baptie, Paterson, Sherry,
McEntegart, Geraghty, Lorimer, Quitongo. Substitutes - McCormick, Thomson,
Cormack.
Referee - T M McCurry (Glasgow).
</TEXT>
