<HEADLINE>Building society confident of recovery Halifax predicts housing upturn</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684337</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S biggest building society, the Halifax, is confident the housing
market is starting to emerge from a double-dip recession.
While no strong recovery is thought likely in 1996, the society raises the
possibility of a mini-boom in the following year.
Last week money suppply data and building society lending figures for November
signalled a possible improvement in the housing market to come.
There was a limited recovery in 1993 from the worst of the recession, but the
market unexpectedly subsided once more in 1994 and 1995.
There were geographic variations, however, and Scotland was not affected as
badly as other areas, particularly South-east England.
The Halifax said the blame for the second downturn rested on a number of
factors - reduction in Government help for home-owners, continued high real
interest rates and expectations that nominal rates would rise, low consumer
confidence linked to lower job security and, most important, sharp increases in
personal taxes in 1994 and 1995 which squeezed disposable income.
These would not have so much impact in 1996, the society said. Interest rates
are now expected to fall and tax cuts will boost incomes.
Consumer confidence should strengthen with income growth, but the absence of
Government measures in the Budget to help the housing market means no strong
recovery is likely next year.
However, it believes the prospects for 1997 onwards look more promising than at
any time since the eighties. Interest rates are at historically very low levels
making mortgage costs much less onerous. Moreover, most people now consider
they will remain at these levels or even fall further.
The Halifax said the tax cuts expected in April should boost real incomes and
would be a major factor in promoting the long-lost ``feel-good'' factor. House
purchases are expected to rise quite sharply in 1996, certainly reversing this
year's 10% fall.
This is not expected to feed through quickly to prices, although the trend,
particularly in the second half of the year, should be clearly moving upwards.
Overall, the Halifax is looking for around a 2% increase next year with the
upward trend in both house moves and prices becoming more pronounced in 1997
and 1998 with rises of more than 5% likely each year.
The society suggested that, as expectations of further house price rises became
more widespread, there could even be a mini-boom in 1997 with both transactions
and prices rising by up to 10%.
``We hope the Government would see no particular wider problems in this - a
one-off correction in the market following years of weakness.
``It is doubtful whether it would spill over into more general inflation
through rising consumer demand given the battering the consumer has taken in
recent years and the `equity release' would be very limited,'' the Halifax
argued.
The society said it would, in fact, be very helpful for the housing market
since it would restore confidence in home ownership. It would also bring back
more normal conditions of buying and selling and would help to eliminate
negative equity more quickly.
</TEXT>
