<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Not a year for good vibrations</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684338</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Michael Tumelty looks back at a time of upheaval and insecurity in Scottish
music
IT is possible that, if the Scottish music scene in 1995 will be remembered for
anything, it will be the fact that, perhaps imperceptibly at the time, it was
the year the tectonic plates in the structure of musical society began to shift.
Over the previous few years, there had been rumbles, some of them subterranean,
that all was not well. Yards of print - nay, kilometres - had been produced in
the form of a succession of reports which tended to back a theory that Scotland
was over-subscribed with musical resources; that there were too many
organisations chasing too few gigs, too few audiences, too little money.
Rationalisation, reorganisation, and restructuring were being bandied about as
the buzz words. Smack in the middle of the developing storm was the country's
biggest musical organisation, Scottish Opera, which - year on year - seemed to
roll from from one threatening financial crisis to another.
The immediate target for rationalisation, which had been identified some years
earlier, was the orchestra of Scottish Opera. The attempt to merge it with the
BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra had long since appeared to have run aground,
despite the recommendations made in a report written under the chairmanship of
Helen Liddell, who had become so fed up with the subject she went and got
herself a quiet job somewhere in London.
In fact, after running for ever in the press the subject finally seemed to have
dropped over the horizon. Until May this year, when, out of the blue, an
announcement was made which suggested that yet another attempt to ``solve'' the
problem of over-provision of orchestras in Scotland was to be made.
For this one, the key players were shuffled. Yet again, of course, Scottish
Opera was one. But out went the BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra, and its place
at the collaborative table was taken by both of the other professional
orchestras in Scotland - the Royal Scottish National and Scottish Chamber
orchestras.
Alarm bells rang all over the place at the appointment of company doctor Sir
Lewis Robertson as chairman of the latest committee. They rang even more
stridently at the fact the entire caboodle was parcelled up and launched by the
Scottish Arts Council, once again donning its ``honest broker'' cloak.
The meetings went on. Nothing came out. All parties involved continued to
insist (when they said anything at all) that they had all entered the process
with what they called a ``white sheet'' approach - no preconceptions, no
preconditions. The RSNO chief executive summed up the vagueness of the whole
situation when he said: ``We'll go in and see what comes out.''
In truth, everybody knew that there was no way any meaningful collaboration
could take place without a sacrifice - if there was a ready solution it would
have been found earlier, and without committees, investigations, and reports.
And, at the same time, everybody knew that, unless a solution could be found
which addressed what Scottish Opera executives said was the basic problem -
that its company was fundamentally underfunded to the tune of #750,000 per year
- the whole exercise was a waste of time.
Behind closed doors, the committee shuffled every conceivable permutation of
Scotland's orchestras, fetching the BBC SSO back into the equation. In early
October they announced their findings, and - surprise, surprise - it was
proposed the Orchestra of Scottish Opera should be disbanded, and its work
carved up among the other three Scottish bands.
And this is when the tectonic plates began to shift. Scottish Opera called a
press conference, fronted by its big boys - chairman Sandy Orr, general
director Richard Jarman, and music director Richard Armstrong - who did a volte
face on their views of some years earlier, and rejected the findings of the
committee.
The opera bosses declared that, rather than see Scottish Opera's orchestra
dumped, they had decided to preserve the integrity of the company's musical
resources and, instead, put the company onto a part-time basis (while admitting
this would very likely be the start of a process of erosion).
The music establishment went ballistic. The unions (bar one, the Musicians'
Union) accused the opera company of dangerous brinksmanship. The Scottish Arts
Council, which had been doing its best to remain invisible during the whole
process, sent out its own thinly-veiled condemnation of Scottish Opera's
rejection of Sir Lewis Robertson's recommendations, while at the same time
accepting the decision of the company to go part-time.
Cynics in the wings suggested immediately that the SAC was weeping crocodile
tears as there was an influential cadre within its ranks who wished that
Scottish Opera, with its high-profile recurring problems and its immense drain
on funds, would fold up tents and disappear. More of the SAC in a moment.
The seismic crunch became audible when the Royal Scottish National Orchestra
and the Scottish Chamber Orchestra, on the afternoon of Scottish Opera's crisis
news briefing, decided to issue their own press releases. Privately, the
orchestra bosses confessed that they were ``completely pissed off'' with
Scottish Opera's management.
Publicly, each orchestra stated categorically that the underfunding problems,
which Scottish Opera brandished daily like a banner of despair, applied equally
to their own organisations, and they were extremely concerned that their own
predicaments would be swamped by the tidal wave of news and noise about the
opera company.
To this end, both orchestras spoke out. The Scottish Chamber Orchestra revealed
- with figures attached - a horrifying timetable predicting its own financial
crisis within two years. Paul Hughes, chief executive of the Royal SNO, said
that the whole question of the funding of all of the national companies had to
be addressed ``before we all have to go part-time or worse''.
The chairman of one of the orchestras went off his head at the Scottish Arts
Council (off the record, of course) saying that ``these people should be out
there putting their heads on the block for all of us, arguing with the
Government on our behalf''.
The SAC kept its inscrutable smile firmly in place and shrugged sympathetic
shoulders, coming out with interminable quotes full of bureacratese, which
amounted to nothing much at all. ``The arm's length policy,'' mused one
orchestral executive, ``is a useful tool, not so much for keeping the
Government away from us, as keeping the Arts Council away from accepting direct
responsibility for anything.''
Then Seona Reid, director of the SAC, appeared finally to get off the fence. In
a newspaper interview she was quoted as saying: ``Perhaps Scottish Opera,
insteas of scaling down from the large, grand production, could plan outwards
from their extremely successful mid to small-scale performance.''
This was electrifying. The quote was buried deep in the story, and thus had no
real public impact, but was - without question - the most important quote of
the whole saga. The SAC director appeared to be suggesting that Scottish Opera
dump altogether what it considered to be its primary function and operate as a
small-scale outfit, adding only anything else it could afford. Invert your
role, appeared to be the message.
The implications were profound. If applied, by choice or pressure, such a
decision would almost certainly mean the complete dismantling of Scottish
Opera, its orchestra, chorus, technical and administrative structure. Those who
read the piece and picked up on the resonances were astounded.
Ministers at the Scottish Office were reported to be ``incandescent'' at what
the SAC director had said. Not that they didn't necessarily sympathise with the
sentiments; but they couldn't be seen to be associated with such an expression.
And, whether Seona Reid's inflammatory statement was directly responsible or
not, it wasn't long before secretary of state Michael Forsyth was to enter the
fray himself.
Just before that, however, there was a momentary diversion of optimism as Lord
Younger of Prestwick, chairman of the Royal Bank of Scotland - a long-time
sponsor of Scottish Opera - staged a public display of confidence in the
beleaguered management of the opera company, and presented them with a
no-conditions-attached cheque for #100,000 to allow them to keep trading.
Shortly after that, the Scottish Office took direct action by reshuffling the
pack, leaving out all of the symphony orchestras, and producing a new character
in the drama - Scottish Ballet. Michael Forsyth instructed Scottish Opera and
the ballet company to get round the table, with his own minister for arts, Lord
Lindsay, to see if the two theatre-based companies could operate together, save
money, and survive.
And we await the outcome, though there are already noises that any savings from
an opera-ballet marriage would be insufficient to meet the basic underfunding
problems of the opera company, and, in any event, would entail reductions in
performances of both art forms.
In a separate context altogether, Hugh MacDonald, head of music for BBC
Scotland, revealed that the BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra was facing a 5%
reduction in its own budget for next year, and that the SSO was in just the
same predicament as the independent symphony orchestras.
So there we are. Scottish Opera, the Royal Scottish National Orchestra, the
Scottish Chamber Orchestra, and the BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra. All the
major national music companies; all with uncertain futures. It may be hard to
argue the case for such national insitutions when commercial industries are
collapsing and there are people with no jobs and damp houses.
But if this was a more enlightened country - and let's not beat about the bush,
here; we are being governed by political philistines - the unique cultural
heritage Scotland has in these organisations would be resourced, not just
adequately, but to the extent that their flagship status would never be in
question. Some chance, eh?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
