<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Smith demands victory - and the champions deliver Rangers take full advantage of their title rivals' day off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER, CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974684339</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANGERS took advantage of the postponement of Celtic's match against Raith
Rovers at Stark's Park yesterday to increase their lead at the top of the
premier division. With their oldest, and, this season, most dangerous rivals
unable to play, the Ibrox men tightened their grip on their league title.
It was imperative that the champions should take advantage of the situation, as
they played the only premier division game to survive the day.
They knew they could not afford to slip up, as they had done in their last
game, against Motherwell, when they dropped two points and helped Celtic narrow
the gap to two points.
This clash, with Kilmarnock, had to produce three points for the Ibrox team -
and it did so. By half-time Rangers had delivered what manager Walter Smith had
demanded from them. They were two goals in front and the match, essentially,
was over.
Rangers had moved with purpose and assurance from the moment the game kicked
off. At times, however, there was a lack of the incisive passing which is
necessary to produce goals and it took them until the twenty-fourth minute
before they went ahead.
Before that goal, Gordan Petric had shot high over the bar, Charlie Miller had
headed off target, and Oleg Salenko had seen a shot stopped by Dragoje
Lekovic's legs. That try must have encouraged the Russian because five minutes
later the striker did score.
Paul Gascoigne, back after a two-game suspension, picked out Brian Laudrup on
the left wing with a marvellous pass. The Dane played the ball into goal and
Salenko moved in to stab it over the line.
Eight minutes later, Kilmarnock had their best chance and referee Bill Crombie
angered Rangers' players and supporters with his part in the penalty-box panic
which struck the champions.
Initially, the referee awarded a corner, despite the fact that his linesman,
who seemed to be better placed, had signalled for a goal kick.
When the ball came over he then penalised Alan McLaren for a challenge on Tom
Brown and awarded an indirect free kick 12 yards from goal. Rangers protested,
and although Crombie stood firm, Richard Gough cleared the danger.
Afterwards, Kilmarnock manager Alex Totten admitted: ``We should have done
better with that free kick. We should have taken something from it.
``Instead, Rangers cleared the ball, stayed in front, and then we lost a second
goal in injury time. That was a bad blow.''
It proved the killer blow and, once again, Ibrox's enfant terrible, Gascoigne,
was involved. Petric played in a cross, Gascoigne chested it down, then flicked
it goalwards, only for Kilmarnock defender Jim Lauchlan to stop it with a hand.
The referee awarded a penalty and Gordon Durie sidefooted the ball confidently
into the net.
To be fair to Kilmarnock, they did try to carry the game to Rangers after
half-time. In 60 minutes, Paul Wright sent a shot wide from long range and
minutes later tried again from the edge of the penalty box with a shot which
went dangerously close.
But Rangers remained in command, although, at times, there was still
over-elaboration from Gascoigne and Laudrup.
For instance, eight minutes from the end Laudrup delayed when he had the ball
in the penalty box and Lekovic had strayed from his goal-line.
Eventually, the Dane passed to Miller, but the youngster shot high over the bar.
Three minutes later, Lekovic saved from Gascoigne but, in injury time, he was
unable to stop the Geordie.
This time, Salenko made the chance and Gascoigne cheekily sent one defender the
wrong way and then poked the ball home from close range. It was a fitting
finale to one of Gascogine's better performances.
Manager Smith said: ``We were glad to get the win, and I was pleased with the
way we played. Gascoigne made a good return and scored a good goal.''
However, Smith refused to accept that the three points would give his side a
psychological advantage over Celtic. ``I doubt if it will make any difference
at this stage,'' he said. ``Still, it is good to have the game behind us and
have another three points in the bag.''
Smith, however, must realise that if Rangers can maintain this run - they have
gone 15 games unbeaten in the league - they could go into next week's game
against Celtic with a commanding lead.
If the weather does not relent, Celtic could find themselves idle once more at
the weekend while Rangers will be able to play their home game against Hibs. It
is not inconceivable that the champions could travel to Parkhead with an
eight-point lead.
They will, however, go into that match without Stuart McCall and Ally McCoist,
who were both missing through injury yesterday. Neither will be ready for the
weekend and both are doubtful for the Celtic game. Durie, who limped off in the
closing minutes yesterday to be replaced by Ian Durrant, is also a worry for
the weekend with a thigh knock.
There were four bookings in the match, Robert Connor, Neil Whitworth, and
Brown, of Kilmarnock, and Rangers' Miller.
RANGERS - Goram, Ferguson, Robertson, Gough, McLaren, Petric, Miller,
Gascoigne, Salenko, Durie, Laudrup. Substitutes - Durrant, McInnes,
Mikhailichenko.
KILMARNOCK - Lekovic, McPherson, Reilly, Henry, Whitworth, Lauchlan, Mitchell,
Connor, Wright, Brown, Holt. Substitutes - Montgomerie, Maskrey, Meldrum.
Referee - W N M Crombie (Edinburgh).
RANGERS .......... 3
KILMARNOCK ..... 0
</TEXT>
