<HEADLINE>Walker eyes 200m</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684340</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ATHLETICS
NEW Year Sprint champion Doug Walker will switch his attention to the 200
metres if he fails to defend his title in this year's professional gala at
Meadowbank on Sunday.
Walker, joint back-marker with Elliot Bunney off half a metre for the big
sprint, is the scratch man for the 200m open handicap which has a start limit
of 20m. Off 20m is Mel Neef, who will make Walker work to earn the #400 first
prize.
Walker's coach Dave Gibson believes that his man is up to the challenge.
``Doug's flying - if anything he's running better than he was at this time last
year,'' he said.
Among the others Walker has to chase is Bedlington's John Hedley, training
partner of Britain's Sportsman of the Year Jonathon Edwards, who starts off 8m,
and two former New Year Sprint winners Neil Sneddon (Edinburgh Southern) and
Tommy Finkle (Jedburgh), who join Borders junior international Iain Horsburgh
on the 9m mark. Strongly tipped Borderer Lee Notman (Hawick) is off 12m.
Heriot-Watt University student Walker was reckoned to have given one of the
best displays on record by a back-marker in winning last year.
</TEXT>
