<DOCNO>GH951227-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951227-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951227</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Whitbread may be Forte's `white knight'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974684341</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RUMOURS of a #1000m ``white knight'' role for Whitbread in Forte's battle with
hostile bidder Granada could be confirmed as early as today, some believe.
According to one newspaper, official confirmation of a #1000m offer by brewing
and leisure giant Whitbread for Forte's restaurant business is likely to come
before Stock Exchange trading resumes at 8.30am.
Hotel magnate Sir Rocco Forte and Peter Jarvis, chief executive of Whitbread,
are rumoured to have agreed terms on Friday, with advisers finalising details
over the Christmas holiday.
A deal for the sale of Forte's roadside restaurants and service stations in the
UK and France, and its Travelodge budget hotels, would greatly strengthen the
group's defensive hand.
It would allow Forte to repay a significant proportion of its debt and could
also facilitate a special dividend or share buy-back to release value to
stockholders.
Forte's shareholders would have to ratify the sale, which is thought likely to
materialise only if they first reject the #3300m bid by leisure giant Granada.
The purchase of Forte's restaurant division would mark another major milestone
in Whitbread's strategy of diversifying out of brewing. In August, Whitbread
paid #201m for tennis and fitness group David Lloyd Leisure, whose most
profitable leisure club is at Renfrew.
A month later it acquired the 41-strong Costa Coffee chain, which has outlets
at Glasgow and Edinburgh airports and Glasgow's Queen Street and Central
stations.
No-one at Forte or Granada was available for comment yesterday. Whitbread said
it never commented on market rumour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
